Abstract: THE STUDY,TO BE CARRIED OUT BY THE US GEOLOGICAL SURVEY, INVOLVES AN INVENTORY OF EXISTING WELLS,EXPLORATORY DRILLING AND CONDUCTING PUMPING TESTS ON NEWLY DRILLED AND EXISTING TUBE WELLS. Abstract: LOAN TO BRAZILIAN INSTITUTE OF GEOGRAPHY & STATISTICS (IBGE) WILL FINANCE TECH ASSIST OF AN ECNMC & METHODS STATISTICIAN TO ASSIST THE EXISTING BRAZILIAN INSTITUTE OF STATISTICS' (LBE) DEPT OF INDUSTRIAL, COMMERCIAL & SERVICES STATISTICS TO EXPAND & IMPROVE PROGRAMS OF ECNMC, INDUSTRIAL & CONSTRUCTION STATISTICS. ACTIVITIES WILL INCLUDE CONTINUATION OF PRESENT PROGRAM OF ANNUAL, QUARTERLY & MONTHLY INDUSTRIAL STATISTICS; DEVEL OF PROCEDURES FOR ELECTRONIC COMPUTER EDIT OF REPORTED DATA, AN ESSENTIAL STEP THAT WILL IMPROVE EDITED DATA & REDUCE REQUIRED EDITING TIME; INTRODUCTION OF WORK STANDARDS & QUALITY CONTROL; COMPLETION OF THE ELECTRONIC COMPUTER PROGRAMMING ON MODERN SYSTEM TO BE INSTALLED IN IBGE; & DEVEL OF IMPROVED INDUSTRIAL & COMMERCIAL ORGANIZATION CLASSIFICATION SYSTEM CONSISTENT WITH THE CURRENT SITUATION. WITH ASSISTANCE OF EFFICIENT SYSTEMS, IBGE WILL BEGIN STUDYING RESPONSE BIAS & SAMPLING VARIATION TO OPTIMIZE ECONOMIC SAMPLE SURVEY; IMPROVE & EXTEND COVERAGE OF PRESENT CONSTRUCTION & BUILDING STATISTICS; INITIATE NEW PROGRAMS FOR ANNUAL & QUARTERLY SURVEY OF DISTRIBUTED TRADE, PROFESSIONAL & PERSONNEL SERVICES & TRANSPORTATION & COMMUNICATION; & ESTABLISH SPECIAL STUDIES OF THE USE OF SAMPLE SURVEYS IN ALL NEW PROGRAMS.
Personal Author: KING, ARNOLD L.|HATTON, CHARLES L.|et al.

Abstract: PROJECT TO BRING HLTH-MED'L SRVCS TO LARGER PERCENTAGE OF POPULATION, ESPECIALLY IN RURAL AREA. ALSO WILL ACHIEVE BETTER COORDINATION AND INTEGRATION OF HEALTH ACTIVITIES CARRIED OUT BY VARIOUS NATIONAL HEALTH AGENCIES. HEALTH CENTER AND PUMAR WILL BE BASIC IMPLEMENTING UNITS OF BROAD RANGE OF MOH DECENTRALIZED HLTH SRVC TO INCLUDE: ENVIRONMENTAL SANITATION, MOTHER-CHILD HEALTH, IMMUNIZATION, CONTROL OF COMMUNICABLE DISEASES, FAMILY PLANNING, NUTRITION, HEALTH EDUCATION, AND OUTPATIENT CLINICAL SERVICES. WILL EXPAND BASIC HEALTH FACILITIES TO AREAS OF 1,500,000 BY END OF 3-YR PROJECT, OR 80% OF 1971 POPULATION. IN 3 YRS COUNTRY'S HEALTH SERVICES WILL ACHIEVE COVERAGE THAT WOULD OTHERWISE TAKE 8 YRS TO ACHIEVE.

Abstract: LOAN FINANCES 13 NEW MOBILE DISPENSARY UNITS FOR PANAMA'S RURAL MOBILE HEALTH PROGRAM (PUMAR) EQUIPPING NEW UNITS WITH DRUGS, MEDICINES, SUPPLIES & SPARE PARTS OVER 3 YEARS. VACCINES AND DRUGS TO TREAT COMMON COMMUNICABLE DISEASES; WATER-BORNE & GASTRO-INTESTINAL DISEASES; RESPIRATORY, SKIN, & OTHER INFECTIONS; PARASITIC INFESTATION; & ANEMIAS PROVIDED. UNITS SERVE ISOLATED AREAS USING BOATS & 4-WHEEL DRIVE AMBULANCES. EACH UNIT OPERATES ON DAILY CIRCUIT, VISITING SMALL CLINICS, SUB-CENTERS & POSTS. EACH OF UNIT STAFF ATTENDS TO HIS SPECIALTY & PATIENTS NEEDING HOSPITALIZATION TRANSPORTED TO NEAREST HEALTH CENTER. HEALTH EDUC PROVIDED TO INHABITANTS & AUXILIARY NURSES SUPPLIED WITH MEDICINES ON EACH UNIT VISIT.

Abstract: AID PROVIDES GRANT TO GUATEMALA IN SUB-PROJ TO ESTABLISH PILOT SCHOOL TO IMRPOVE RURAL PRIMARY EDUCATION. TWO 6-GRADE SCHOOLS IN LADINO AREAS AND TWO 6-GRADE SCHOOLS IN INDIAN HIGHLANDS WILL BE SUPPLEMENTED WITH LAND, EQUIPMENT, AND BUILDINS AND CONVERTED INTO PILOT SCHOOLS. PILOT SCHOOLS WILL DEVELOP AND TEST CURRICULA AND TEACHING METHODS ORIENTED TO RURAL SETTING. PROG WILL ALSO DEVELOP IN-SERVICE TEACHER TRAINING AND TRAINING PROG FOR SCHOOL SUPERVISORS. LEARNING WILL BE PRACTICAL AND CONDUCTED OUTSIDE CONVENTIONAL CLASSROOM SETTING. PILOT SCHOOLS WILL INVOLVE PARENTS AND GENERAL COMMUNITY THROUGH EVENING CLASSES AND AGRICULTURAL DEMONSTRATIONS. INSTRUCTION WILL INCLUDE AGRICULTURE, HEALTH, NUTRITION, HOME ECONOMICS AND INDUSTRIAL ARTS FOR WHICH LOW-COST TEXTS WILL BE DEVELOPED USING NEWSPRINT BOOKLET FORMAT. STUDENTS WILL RETAIN TEXTS. TECHNICIANS IN CORRESPONDING AREAS WILL BE PROVIDED BY GOG AND PARTIALLY FINANCED BY AID GRANT. GOG WILL ALSO SUPPLY GENERAL SUPERVISOR AND EDITORIAL STAFF FOR TEXTBOOK PREPARATION, CURRICULUM DEVELOPMENT, TEACHER TRNG  AND CONFERENCES. TO EVALUATE PILOT SCHOOL PROG, 2 TYPES OF CONTROL SCHOOLS WILL BE DESIGNATED AND MATCHED WITH PILOTS. FIRST SET OF CONTROLS WILL CONSIST OF TWO 6-GRADE SCHOOLS WITH TECH  SERVICES, BUT NO SPECIALLY CONSTRUCTED FACILITIES. SECOND SET OF CONTROLS WILL INVOLVE TWO 6-GRADE SCHOOLS WITH NO CHANGES INTRODUCED, ATTENDANCE, DROP-OUT RATES, COMMUNITY INTEREST AND STUDENT ACHIEVEMENT WILL BE MONITORED AND COMPARED. AID AND MINISTRY OF EDUCATION WILL JOINTLY SUPERVISE PROJ. PILOT SCHOOLS WILL SERVE AS MODELS FOR REGIONAL SCHOOLS IN RELATED LOAN SUB-PROJ (520019202).  PILOT SCHOOLS WILL PRECEDE REGIONAL SCHOOLS BY 2-3 YRS. UPON IMPLEMENTATION, GRANT SUB-PROJ SPLIT OFF TO BECOME PROJ 5200193 AND LATER 528019801.

Abstract: LOAN AND TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE PROVIDED TO THE GOVERNMENT OFTHE DOMINICAN REPUBLIC (GODR) TO ESTABLISH INFRASTRUCTURE FOR A MATERNAL/INFANT CARE SERVICE, INCLUDING FAMILY PLANNING (MIC/FP) IN AREAS OF THE COUNTRY WHERE SUCH A SERVICE IS MOST CRITICALLY NEEDED. PROJECT IS DESIGNED TO REDUCE POPULATION GROWTH, STIMULATE THE POPULACE'S DESIRE FOR FAMILY PLANNING AND INCREASE GODR COMMITMENT TO PUBLIC HEALTH SERVICES. PROJECT ACTIVITIES INCLUDE CONSTRUCTING AND/OR REMODELING OF 132 HEALTH FACILITIES INCLUDING 16 HOSPITALS, 27 SUB-CENTERSAND 89 RURAL CLINICS; PROVIDING EQUIPMENT FOR ALL FACILITIESPLUS VEHICLES; TRAINING 3085 MEDICAL AND PARAMEDICAL PERSONNEL TO MEET MANPOWER NEEDS; AND PROVIDING SHORT-TERM CONSULTANTS IN NURSING, BUILDING MAINTENANCE HEALTH ADMINISTRATION AND HEALTH PERSONNEL. IN ADDITION, THE PROJECT WILL FINANCE COSTS OTHER THAN FOR TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE FOR CONTINUOUS EVALUATION OF THE FP PROGRAM, THE ADMINISTRATIVE ORGANIZATION OF THE SECRETARIAT AND THE REGIONAL HOSPITAL SYSTEM. THE PROJECT WILL ALSO PROVIDE FOR A MASS MEDIA CAMPAIGN TO DEVELOP AND MAINTAIN POSITIVE ATTITUDES TOWARDS FAMILY PLANNING. BENEFICIARIES INCLUDE GODR HEALTH EMPLOYEES AND THE RURAL POPULACE. USAID PROJECT COMMITTEE WILL IMPLEMENT THIS PROJECT AND BE INVOLVED WITH THE HOST COUNTRY'S SECRETARIAT OF HEALTH. USAID CONTRIBUTES FINANCIAL AND TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE FOR CONSTRUCTION, EQUIPMENT, EDUCATION AND TRAINING, SPECIALISTS, SPECIAL STUDIES AND THE MASS MEDIA PROGRAM. FINAL EVALUATION IS EXPECTED IN 1976. OTHER DONORS: UNITED NATIONS FUND FOR POPULATION ACTIVITIES (UNFPA) AND THE POPULATION COUNCIL OF NEW YORK.

Abstract: LOAN & TECH ADVISORY ASSISTANCE ARE PROVIDED TO CAMPANHIA ESTADUAL DE ENERGIA ELECTRICA (CEEE) A STATE-OWNED POWER COMPANY, FOR CONSTRUCTION OF A NEW POWER PLANT TO ASSURE THE STATE OF RIO GRANDE DO SOL IN BRAZIL OF AN ADEQUATE ELECTRICAL POWER SUPPLY. CEEE WILL IMPLEMENT PROJECT WITH US ENGINEERING ASSISTANCE. THE PASSO REAL DAM & POWER PLANT WILL BE CONSTRUCTED ON THE RIVER JACUI. THE FILL-TYPE DAM WILL IMPOUND A RESERVOIR WITH A STORAGE CAPACITY OF APPROXIMATELY 2300 MILLION CUBIC METERS OF USABLE WATER. ITS POWER HOUSE WILL HAVE A TOTAL CAPACITY OF 125 MW. PROJ WILL ALSO INCLUDE CONSTRUCTION OF A TRANSMITTING SUBSTATION AS WELL AS EXPANSION & IMPROVEMENT OF EXISTING TRANSMISSION & DISTRIBUTION FACILITIES. PASSO REAL WILL BE SITUATED ABOUT 15 KILOMETERS UPSTREAM FROM THE JACQUI DAM. THE 2 PLANTS WILL BE OPERATED AS A SINGLE PLANT WITH THE MAIN STORAGE FOR BOTH PROVIDED BY THE PASSO REAL RESERVOIR. A US ENGINEERING FIRM WILL DETAIL THE CURRENT PLANT DESIGN AND PROVIDE ENGINEERING PROCUREMENT, INSPECTION & TRNG FOR CEEE PERSONNEL. CONSTRUCTION WILL BE PERFORMED BY BRAZILIAN CONTRACTORS. BULK OF THE LABOR FORCE WILL BE RECRUITED WITHIN THE STATE OF RIO GRANDE DO SUL, WITH APPROX HALF OF THE TECHNICAL PERSONNEL COMING FROM OTHER AREAS. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT AN AVERAGE WORK FORCE OF 800 MEN (WITH A POSSIBLE PEAK OF 1000) WILL BE REQUIRED FOR CONSTRUCTION OF THE PLANT. EQUIPMENT INSTALLATION SERVICES WILL BE CONTRACTED SEPARATELY. SUPPLIERS OF MAJOR EQUIPMENT ARE EXPECTED TO PROVIDE ERECTION SPECIALISTS TO SUPERVISE WORK DONE BY THE EQUIPMENT INSTALLATION CONTRACTOR AND ASSIST IN THE INITIAL STAGES OF TESTING & OPERATION. USAID WILL FINANCE IMPORTED MATERIALS UNAVAILABLE THROUGH BRAZILIAN SOURCES AS WELL AS THE COMPONENTS OF BRAZILIAN MADE TURBINES, GENERATORS & OTHER EQUIPMENT. HOST COUNTRY WILL PROVIDE PERSONNEL & LONG-TERM MAINTENANCE. PRIMARY BENEFICIARIES ARE THE RESIDENTS OF THE STATE OF RIO GRANDE DO SUL FOR WHOM AN INCREASED SUPPLY OF ELECTRICAL POWER IS PROVIDED

Abstract: PROJECT CONSTITUTES A CONTINUATION/EXPANSION OF AID/IRI RESEARCH INSTITUTE PROGRAM OF TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE TO ESTABLISH A NATIONWIDE AGRICULTURAL RESEARCH/EXTENSION CAPABILITY AIMED AT AGRICULTURAL SELF-SUFFICIENCY FOR BRAZIL. IRI WILL CONTINUE THIS EFFORT WITH ASSISTANCE TO EPE TO IMPROVE ITS CAPACITY TO PLAN/EXECUTE A NATIONAL RESEARCH PROGRAM BY INCREASING STAFF & STAFF RESEARCH CAPACITY, TRAINING RESEARCH PROFESSIONALS & PROVIDING RESEARCH EQUIPMENT/COMMODITIES/SERVICES. CNPQ WILL EXPAND THE GRADUATE TRAINING PROGRAM IN AGRICULTURAL RESEARCH,THUS INCREASING AGRICULTURAL RESEARCH/EXTENSION MANPOWER, SCHOLARSHIPS/BONUSES/SALARY INCREASES WILL BE USED TO ATTRACT AND RETAIN CAPABLE AGRICULTURE SCHOOL GRADUATES.

Abstract: LOAN IS EXTENDED TO GOVT OF NICARAGUA TO FINANCE THE ORGANIZATION AND CONSTRUCTION OF THREE ELECTRIC COOPERATIVES. THIS  IS BOTH AN INSTITUTION BUILDING AND PHYSICAL CONSTRUCTION PROJECT. LOAN FUNDS ARE SUBLENT TO COOPERATIVES TO CONSTRUCT DISTRIBUTION AND TRANSMISSION FACILITIES. IN ADDITION, THE LOAN FINANCES TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE TO ENALUF, A GOVERNMENT OWNED POWER COMPANY,TO STRENGTHEN ITS RURAL ELECTRIFICATION SECTION TO ENABLE ENALUF TO PROVIDE THE NECESSARY TECHNICAL SERVICES TO DEVELOP AND MONITOR THESE AS WELL AS FUTURE ELECTRIC COOPERATIVES. IN ADDITION TO ELECTRICAL DISTRIBUTION THE COOPERATIVES SERVE AS CENTERS FOR OTHER COMMUNITY ACTIVITIES AND ACT AS CATALYTIC AGENTS FOR OTHER DEVELOPMENT PROGRAMS.

Abstract: NICARAGUAN GOVERNMENT RECEIVES LOAN TO FINANCE AGRICULTURAL PROGRAM. BULK OF LOAN IS USED FOR IMPORTATION OF FERTILIZER AND PESTICIDES, WHILE A PORTION IS USED TO TRAIN SMALL FARMERS IN MODERN FARMING PRACTICES. INCREASED AMOUNT OF CREDIT IS EXTENDED TO SMALL FARMERS THROUGH THE NATIONAL BANK OF NICARAGUA THAT THEY MAY PURCHASE FERTILIZER AND PESTICIDES NEEDED TO INCREASE PRODUCTIVITY.

Abstract: Pilot project to initiate a rural electrification program in the Philippines by installing two 2,000-KW generators and substantially expanding the distribution system of the Victorias Rural Electric Service Cooperative in Negros Occidentale Province.  The project will provide electric power to an estimated 7,000 families (about 40,000 persons) in the municipalities of Victorias, Manapla, and Cadiz.  The National Power Corporation of the Philippines will supervise the project's design, construction, and initial operating phases.  This is the first of two planned USAID demonstration projects; the second will install power for a new cooperative, MORESCO, in Misamis Oriental Province in Mindanao.  USAID will also finance TA from the National Rural Electrification Cooperative Association (NRECA).

Abstract: Project to provide guidelines for evaluating family planning (FP) programs worldwide.  The project will yield a rigorous yet simple FP program cost-benefit model applicable to economies at all levels of development, identify data needs for FP program analysis, generate FP program costs per unit of performance, and provide suggestions for future FP cost-benefit research.  The project strategy involves detailed analysis of existing data on selected LDC FP programs.

Abstract: 1968. IRAN ASSUMED MORE ADMINISTRATIVE AND FINANCIAL RESPONSIBILITY OFR PULSE PROJECT. EARLY IN 1968, DECISION WAS MADE TO PHASE OUT REGIONAL PULSE PROJECT IN IRAN, BUT PART OF AMERICAN TEAM WOULD PROBABLY REMAIN FOR SOME TIME. LACK FO FACILITIES HAMPERED PROJECT ACTIVITIES IN INDIA, AS LAND AND LABS AT INDIAN AGRICULTURAL RESEARCH INSTITUTE ARE TOTALLY INADEQUATE. OUT OF 5 CROP SEASONS SINCE 1966, PULSE PROJECT HAS SEEN 4 COMPLETE OR NEAR COMPLETE FAILURES. DELIVERY OF ESSENTIAL ANALYTICAL EQUIPMENT WAS DELAYED OVER A YEAR. FUNCTION OF TEAM AS REGIONAL RESEARCH TEAM OR COUNTRY SUPPORT TEAM WAS UNCERTAIN. HOWEVER, ALL INDIA COORDINATED PULSE PROJECT MADE SIGNIFICANT PROGRESS. MORE PEOPLE ARE NOW WORKING SPECIFICALLY ON PULSES THAN EVER BEFORE. 1968 CROP SEASONS SHOWED THAT PULSE CROP PRODUCTION IS LIMITED BY UNEXPECTED AND UNAVOIDABLE FACTORS: WEATHER, NEMATODE INFESTATIONS, FLOODING ... RESULTS OF EXPERIMENTS CONDUCTED AT BOTH SITES IN PLANT BREEDING, SOIL AND CROP MANAGEMENT, ENTOMOLOGY, PLANT PATHOLOGY ARE DISCUSSED. RELEVANT PUBLICATIONS ARE CITED.

Abstract: CREATION OF (FECOAGROH) ALLOWED FOR THE ORGANIZATION OF HONDURAN FARMERS INTO MRKTNG, SUPPLY, PROD, AND SERVICE COOPS. FECOAGROH'S MAJOR FUNCTIONS WERE: 1.ASSESS DIFFERENT COMMUNITIES FOR POSSIBLE COOP ORGANIZATIONS 2.INTRODUCE THE BASIC TENETS OF COOPS TO GROUPS OF FARMERS EXPLORING PROBLEMS, ASPIRATIONS AND OPPORTUNITIES 3.ORGANIZE PRE-COOP ACTIVITIES IN ORDER TO DEMO THE EFFECTIVENESS OF COOPS 4.LEAD FORMAL ORGANIZATIONAL PROCEEDINGS TO ADOPT BY-LAWS AND ELECT DIRECTORS. 5. PARTICIPATE IN DECISION-MAKING PROCESS IN BASIC INVESTMENTS, DESIGN OF SERVICES, CONTRACT ARRANGEMENTS AND CREDIT. 6. TRAINING IN MANAGEMENT, ACCOUTNG, PLANNG, AND TECH OPERATIONS TECHNIQUES 7.LINK VARIOUS SRVC ORGANZATNS AND LOCAL GOVTS.

Abstract: GRANT TO THE GOVT OF HONDURAS DEVELOPS THE PERSONNEL RESOURCES AND ASSISTS IN THE PRELIMINARY PLANNING NECESSARY FOR THE IMPLEMENTATION OF A PROPOSED PULP AND PAPER  (P & P)  INDUSTRY DEVELOPMENT PROJECT IN THE OLANCHO FOREST RESERVE.SPECIFICALLY THE GRANT PROVIDES: 1)APPROX 10 PARTICIPANT TRAINING SCHOLARSHIPS/YR (BS-LEVEL)FOR FORESTRY TRNG AT A US UNIVERSITY.RECIPIENTS ARE INTENDED FOR VITAL POSITIONS IN THE GOH FORESTRY DEPARTMENT AND IN HONDURAS' PRIVATE WOOD PRODUCTS INDUSTRY. 2)A FORESTRY TECHNICIAN TO: ADVISE THE GOH MINISTRY OF NATURAL RESOURCES (MNR), SUPERIOR ECONOMIC PLANNING COUNCIL (SEPC), PULP AND PAPER COMMITTEE, THE AID MISSION, AND OTHER ORGANIZATIONS ON THE ACTIVITIES OF THE PROPOSED P & P PROJECT (AID LOAN TO PROVIDE THE INFRASTRUCTURE FOR THE P & P INDUSTRY); ADVISE ON THE ESTABLISHMENT OF A NEW FORESTRY ADMINISTRATION; INFLUENCE & COORDINATE ACTIVITIES CONDUCTED BY OTHER INTERNATL TECH ASSISTANCE ORGANIZATIONS AND OTHER PROJS RELATED TO HONDURAN FORESTS; COORDINATE THE ABOVE PARTIC TRNG COMPONENT WITH THE MNR & SEPC; ASSIST IN PROMOTING A CADASTRAL SURVEY IN THE OLANCHO FOREST RESERVE; AND ASSIST WITH THE REVISING & MODERNIZING OF HONDURAS' FORESTRY LAWS. PRO AG(12/16/69 INDICATES THAT FUNDING WILL ALSO BE USED TO ASSIST THE MNR PULP AND PAPER FORESTRY OFFICE WITH THE DESIGN OF AN OPERATIONS & MGMT TRAINING PROGRAM FOR ITS ADMIN PERSONNEL. PROP REVISION(12/18/70)NOTES THAT THE PARTICULAR P & P INDUSTRY ANTICIPATED TO INVEST IN THE OLANCHO FOREST AREA HAS WITHDRAWN.AS A RESULT,PROJ HAS BEEN REDIRECTED TOWARDS HELPING THE GOH DESIGN A 10-YR,NATIONWIDE,INTEGRATED FOREST DEVEL ACTION PROGRAM.PARTIC TRNG WILL CONTINUE BUT AID WILL ADDITIONALLY FINANCE A PASA WITH THE US FOREST SERVICE FOR A TEAM OF FORESTRY EXPERTS TO STUDY PAST & PRESENT FOREST ACCOMPLISHMENTS IN HONDURAS AND THE NEEDS & REQUIREMENTS FOR ADEQUATE PROTECTION,ADMINISTRATION,AND COMMERCIAL USE OF ITS FOREST RESOURCES.USING THE RESULTS OF THIS STUDY,A TASK FORCE CONSISTING OF THESE ADVISORS AND,POSSIBLY,OTHERS FROM SUCH AGENCIES AS THE FAO,OAS,OR IDB WILL DEVELOP RECOMMENDATIONS(ACTION PLAN)BY WHICH THE 10-YR DEVEL PROGRAM CAN BE IMPLEMENTED.

Abstract: 4 CORE AGR SECTOR INSTITUTIONS STRENGTHENED IN 5 CRITICAL AREAS: RESEARCH & EXTENSION; AGR DELIVERY SYSTEM; FORMATION OF FARMER ORGANIZATIONS; SOIL & WATER CONSERVATION & SANITATION; AGRARIAN REFORM. TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE TRANSFERS SKILLS IN MANAGEMENT & ORGANIZATIONAL DEVELOPMENT; SHORT & LONGTERM TRAINING FILL SECTOR STAFFING NEEDS. AGR SECTOR ANALYSIS PROVIDES INFORMATION TO REFINE AND DEVELOP NEW RURAL DEVELOPMENT STRATEGIES. STRONG CORE INSTITUTIONS PERMIT COORDINATION OF DEVELOPMENT EFFORTS, A REQUIREMENT FOR SUCCESS. AFTER 1 YEAR OF PROJECT, FARM FISH POND COMPONENT ADDED TO INCREASE USE OF LAND, PROVIDE EMPLOYMENT, PROTEIN, AND POTENTIAL FOR CASH INCOME. FORMERLY 522003606-PROJECT NUMBER CHANGED.

Abstract: THE ASIAN-AMERICAN FREE LABOR INSTITUTE  (AAFLI) , AN AGENCY OF THE AFL-CIO, IS CONTRACTED TO ASSIST IN THE DEVELOPMENT OF ASIAN LABOR UNIONS AND COOPERATIVES. THIS ASSISTANCE WILL BE FOCUSED ON THE COUNTRIES OF KOREA, SOUTH VIETNAM, TURKEY, AND THE PHILIPPINES. AFFLI WILL SUB-CONTRACT WITH SEVERAL US UNION AFFILIATES OF THE INTERNATIONAL TRADE SECRETARIATS FOR SHORT-TERM, IN-COUNTRY WORKSHOPS TO BE HELD WITH THE COOPERATION OF INDIGENOUS LABOR UNIONS AND COOPERATIVES. WORKSHOPS WILL ENCOMPASS LABOR LEADERSHIP TRAINING AND COOPERATIVE DEVELOPMENT TRAINING FOR UNION & COOP ADMINISTRATORS AND SKILLS TRAINING FOR UNION & COOP MEMBERS AND/OR PROSPECTIVE MEMBERS. COURSES WILL BE PROVIDED IN SUBJECTS SUCH AS ORGANIZING & COLLECTIVE BARGAINING, EQUIPMENT/VEHICLE/MACHINARY OPERATION, MAINTENANCE & REPAIR, UNION ADMINISTRATIVE PROCEDURES, ECONOMICS, TEACHING & COMMUNICATION AND WORKER SAFETY. ADDITIONAL ASSISTANCE TO VIETNAMESE LABOR UNIONS WILL CONSIST OF THE PROVISION OF RELEVANT EQUIPMENT, MACHINARY, OR VEHICLES, EG, TRACTORS, MOTORS, FISHING NETS, ECT, WHICH WILL BE RESOLD TO UNION/COOP MEMBERS. PROCEEDS WILL BE USED TO PURCHASE ADDITIONAL EQUIPMENT AND VEHICLES. THE AAFLI WILL ALSO SPONSOR 30-45 KEY ASIAN UNION/COOP PERSONNEL PER YEAR FOR TRAINING IN THE US AND EUROPE. THIS TRAINING WILL BE PROVIDED AT UNIVERSITIES WITH ACCREDITED LABOR EDUCATION DEPARTMENTS, NATIONAL & INTERNATIONAL INSTITUTES FOR LABOR/SKILLS TRAINING, AND NATIONAL & INTERNATIONAL TRADE FEDERATIONS (EG, AFL-CIO, ILO, AND THE WORLD CONFEDERATION OF LABOR) . IT WILL BE OF A SHORT-TERM OBSERVATIONAL OR LONGER-TERM FORMALIZED TYPE.

Abstract: PROJECT EXPANDS POTABLE WATER SUPPLY FACILITIES ALONG EAST BANK DEMERARA INSTALLING SERVICE CONNECTIONS AND WATER METERS, PRODUCTION/TREATMENT FACILITIES INCLUDING WELLS AND PUMPS, AERATION/CHLORINATION/FILTRATION, GROUND STORAGE, BOOSTER PUMPING STATION AND EMERGENCY POWER GENERATOR, DISTRIBUTION SYSTEM INCLUDING PIPELINES AND ELEVATED TANKS, AND MAIN EXTENSION. A COURSE IN PUBLIC HEALTH (SANITARY) ENGINERING AT UNIVERSITY OF GUYANA TRAINS TECHNICIANS FOR SERVICE IN GUYANA NATIONAL WATER AUTHORITY, WHICH, IF AND WHEN ESTABLISHED, OPERATES ALL FACILITIES.

Abstract: PROJECT TO CONSTRUCT 12 NEW WATER STORAGE TANKS AND DISTRIBUTION SYSTEMS IN SENSITIVE AREA OF NORTHEAST, REHABILITATE AND CONSTRUCT DISTRIBUTION SYSTEM FOR 9 EXISTING WATER STORAGE TANKS, AND INSTITUTE A PROGRAM FOR PROPER UTILIZATION OF WATER. PROJECT ADMINISTERED BY ROYAL IRRIGATION DEPARTMENT (RID), MINISTRY OF NATIONAL DEVELOPMENT IN COOPERATION WITH MINISTRY OF AGRICULTURE. US CONTRIBUTES BULK OF IMPORTED EQUIPMENT EMPHASIZING LABOR-INTENSIVE METHODS. US TRAINS FARMERS IN EFFICIENT WATER UTILIZATION AND FARM MANAGEMENT PRACTICES. ADVANCED PARTICIPANT TRAINING IN IRRIGATION ENGINEERING IN US AND SHORT-TERM TECHNICIAN TRAINING IN TAIWAN.

Abstract: RESEARCH REPORT  (JUNE 1968) ON THE FACTORS AFFECTING DROPOUT AND REPETITION IN BRAZILIAN PRIMARY EDUCATION AS PREPARED BY AN ON-SITE SUB-PROJECT CONTRACT TEAM FROM THE STATE UNIVERSITY OF NEW YORK  (SUNY). THIS SUB-PROJECT WAS INTENDED TO UPGRADE BRAZILIAN ELEMENTARY AND BASIC EDUCATION BY RESEARCHING PROBLEM AREAS IN EDUCATION AND ASSISTING INDIVIDUAL STATES WITH THE DEVELOPMENT AND IMPLEMENTATION OF CORRECTIVE PROGRAMS. THIS EVALUATION WAS CONDUCTED BY EXAMINING MINISTRY OF EDUCATION RECORDS AND DISTRIBUTING A QUESTIONAIRE AMONG A SAMPLING OF ONE-ROOM AND MULTI-ROOM PRIVATE, COUNTY, AND STATE PRIMARY SCHOOLS. SOME OF THE FINDINGS OF THIS STUDY ARE AS FOLLOWS: 1) PROMOTION RATES TEND TO BE HIGHEST IN PRIVATE SCHOOLS, LOWEST IN COUNTY SCHOOLS. 2) THERE IS NO CONSISTENT PATTERN IN PROMOTION RATES AMONG 1, 2, 3AND 4-SHIFT SCHOOLS. THIS CONTRDICTS THE EXPECTATION THAT RATES WOULD BE LOWER FOR MULTI-SHIFT SCHOOLS. ONE POSSIBLE EXPLANATION IS THAT SCHOOLS OFFERING HIGHER QUALITY EDUCATION ATTRACTED A GREATER NUMBER OF STUDENTS. THESE SCHOOLS WERE CONSEQUENTLY FORCED TO OPERATE ON A MULTI-SHIFT SYSTEM TO ACCOMMODATE THE ELEVATED ENROLLMENT. 3) PROMOTION RATES WERE HIGHER FOR MULTI-ROOM SCHOOLS. 4) PROMOTION RATES WERE HIGHER IN SCHOOLS WHICH HAD LOWER PERCENTAGES OF QUALIFIED TEACHERS, POSSIBLY DUE TO THE LOWER STANDARDS OF WORK ALLOWED BY LESS QUALIFIED TEACHERS. 5) MOST SCHOOL OPERATED ON ONLY ONE SHIFT BUT THE MULTI-SHIFT SCHOOLS ENROLLED A DISPROPORTIONATELY LARGE NUMBER OF STUDENTS. THIS REPORT CONTAINS AN APPENDIX WHICH CONSISTS OF TABULATIONS OF THE DATA USED TO GENERATE THE ABOVE FINDINGS.

Abstract: EVALUATES PROJECT PERFORMANCE FROM 1964 TO 1968 IN BRAZIL. PROJECT WAS RESPONSIBLE FOR A SCHEMATIC MAP OF THE WESTERN 2/3'S OF BRAZIL IDENTIFYING AGRICULTURAL AREAS, SOIL AND INTERPRTIVE MAPS WITH SUPPORTING TEXT, RECONNAISSANCE SOIL SURVEYS OF AREAS PROMISING FOR AGRICULTURE, AND 60 TO 100 FIELD TECHNCINS FOR THE DIVISION OF PEDOLOGY AND SOIL FERTILITY (DPFS). ON-SITE EVALUATION WAS MADE. PROGRESS HAS BEEN REASONABLE  DESPITE STOPPAGES IN RECRUITMENT AND FIELD WORK DUE TO INADEQUATE FUNDING. THE RESULTING SCHEMATIC SOIL MAP AND 3 INTERPRETIVE MAPS WITH TEXT ARE EXPECTED TO HAVE A FAR-REACHING INFLUENCE ON BRAZIL'S DEVELOPMENT. THE 4 MAPS WERE USED PRIOR TO PUBLICATION OF THE TEXT TO PLAN COLONIZATION,AGRICULTURAL DEVELOPMENT,AND LOCATE HIGHWAYS INTO BRAZIL'S INTERIOR. THERE IS STILL A HIGH DEGREE OF URGENCY FOR MORE DETAILED SURVEYS,ESPECIALLY IN GOIAS AND MATO GROSSO. SETTLEMENT OF UNOCCUPPIED REGIONS WILL CONTRIBUTE TO BRAZIL'S PROGRESS AND STIMULATE ECONOMIC AND SOCIAL DEVELOPMENT. TO MEET THE DEMANDS OF THE NEXT 10 YEARS,30 MILLION HECTARES OF HIGH FERTILITY NEED TO BE LOCATED WHICH HAVE ADEQUATE ACCESS TO MARKETS,CLIMATE,VEGETATN,SURFACE WATER,ETC. UNFORTUNATELY,BUDGETARY AND PERSONNEL RESTRICTNS HAVE REDUCED THE AREAS OF LAND AVAILABLE FOR STUDY. SELECTED FARMERS IN SURVEY AREAS HAVE BEEN CONSULTED AS TO AGRICULTURAL CAPACITIES BUT THEY HAVE NOT FREELY RESPONDED TO QUESTNS. ALTHOUGH STAFFING HAS BEEN SLOWER THAN EXPECTED DUE TO INADEQUATE FUNDING,BRAZIL'S SOIL SCIENTISTS NOW HAVE ADEQUATE COMPETENCY TO HANDLE MOST PROBLEMS WITHOUT US HELP. DPFS'S STAFF IS TO BE INCREASED AND IN-SERVICE TRAINING PROVIDED FOR MORE STAFF. EVALUATOR RECOMMENDS THAT: SCHEMATIC MAPS WITH ACCOMPANING INTERPRETIVE MAPS FOR THE EASTERN 1/3 OF BRAZIL BE PREPARED WITH DPFS RESPONSIBLE FOR DEVELOPMENT,MAINTENANCE,AND COORDINATION OF THE NATIONAL SYSTEM OF SOIL CLASSIFICATN & CORRELATN; RESEARCH RESULTS OBTAINED FROM EXPERIMENTAL AREAS BE CORRELATED WITH SOIL TYPES; AND SIZE,SCOPE,AND EFFECTIVENESS OF SOIL STAFFS BE INCREASED WITHIN THE MINISTRY OF AGRICULTURE.
Ancilary Data: Evaluation period: 30 May 1964-26 May 1968

Abstract: Evaluates selected supervised agricultural credit programs funded by USAID during the period 1964-1968 in Peru.  The credit programs are designed to increase agricultural production and farm income for small and medium-sized farmers.  The report is based on interviews with a sampling of farmers and with personnel from implementing agencies, as well as loan census data and production data. The majority of loan funds are channeled through the "Plan Costa", the supervised credit program for coastal farmers administered by the National Agricultural Research and Extension Service (SIPA).  The Plan Costa increased the level of living of the farmers, if not over the long-run, at least during the time of the loan.  No production data are available for Plan Costa borrowers before they participated in the credit program; therefore, production impact of the program is difficult to judge. Success varied greatly between agencies (i.e., districts). Based on interviews with 279 farmers in 5 of SIPA's 54 agencies, crop yields among borrowers were found to be below the coastal average. This is partly due to the lack of water in certain agencies. In the future, SIPA should channel credit to the more productive agencies. The more unstable agencies need aid directed at the basic problems of water supply and soil structure before supervised agricultural credit is warranted. The mere existence of people in an area is not a sufficient basis for provision of supervised credit. At present, all loans are made solely on the basis of general crop budgets for the area. Since each farmer presents a special case, a farm plan should be prepared for the individual farmer or at least for each group of farmers that use similar inputs and have the same levels of skill. The farm plan would include the farmers's present status, where he plans to be in one or two years, and how he plans to get there. Loans thus budgeted on an individual basis will decrease the number of defaults. Report also evaluates the credit programs supervised by Nat Off of Agrarian Reforms & the Nat Forestry Serv. Several recommendations also made re improving prog admn by Agr Dev Bank.
Ancilary Data: Evaluation period: 1 Jan 1964-1 Jun 1968

Abstract: Subproject to strengthen the social science research capacity of the Federal University of Pernambuco's Institute of the Sciences of Man (ISM) in Recife, Brazil, and enable ISM to conduct research for the Superintendency for the Development of the Northeast and for other northeastern planning agencies. Vanderbilt University will provide ISM with two full-time professors, one in economic research and one in sociology research, who will:  assist ISM faculty in research planning, teach formal classes, advise on library acquisitions, and help in selecting candidates for U.S. graduate training.

Abstract: SUBPROJECT TO SUPPORT U.S. PARTICIPANT TRAINING OF KEY BRAZILIAN PERSONNEL IN GOVERNMENT, INDUSTRY, AND PRIVATE INSTITUTIONS. ANNUAL SCHOLARSHIPS WILL PROVIDE LONG-TERM GRADUATE AND POSTGRADUATE TRAINING CENTRAL TO ECONOMIC, SOCIAL, AND POLITICAL DEVELOPMENT.  TRAINING FIELDS WILL INCLUDE ECONOMICS, LAW, SCIENCE, AND TECHNOLOGY, EDUCATION AND UNIVERSITY ADMINISTRATION, PUBLIC ADMINISTRATION, PUBLIC HEALTH, URBAN PLANNING, AND MANAGEMENT OF ENGINEERING OPERATIONS. ADVANCED STUDY IN SCIENCE AND ENGINEERING MAY BE CONSIDERED WHERE LINKED TO BROAD DEVELOPMENT OBJECTIVES SUCH AS ADMINISTRATION OF RESEARCH PROJECTS. SELECTION OF CANDIDATES FOR LONG-TERM TRAINING WILL INCLUDE THE FOLLOWING CRITERIA:  1.TRAINING NOT AVAILABLE IN BRAZIL; 2.ENGLISH LANGUAGE PROFICIENCY; 3.UNDER 45 YEARS OF AGE AND EMPLOYED BY SPONSORING INSTITUTION FOR AT LEAST 2 YEARS; 4.SALARY CONTINUATION DURING STUDIES AND UTILIZATION UPON RETURN TO BRAZIL GUARANTEED BY SPONSORING INSTITUTION.  IN SELECTED CASES, SHORT-TERM COURSES AND OBSERVATION TOURS WILL BE CONSIDERED FOR MORE MATURE INDIVIDUALS ALREADY IN, OR ASSURED OF, LEADERSHIP POSITIONS. GRANTS WILL CONTINUE FOR TECHNICAL TRAINING RELATED TO TERMINATING PROJECTS AND TO PROVIDE SHORT-TERM YOUTH TRAINING. YOUTH TRAINING WILL CONSIST OF 4-WEEK ANNUAL PROGRAM FOR 75-85 SELECTED STUDENTS; SEMINAR TO INTRODUCE THEM TO U.S. ECONOMIC AND POLITICAL THEORIES AND PRACTICES (SAGE PROJECT). PROGRAM INCLUDES 2-WEEK SEMINAR ON DEVELOPMENT AT HOWARD UNIVERSITY & CONSULTATIONS IN WASHINGTON AND NEW YORK WITH GOVERNMENT AND BUSINESS LEADERS. ENGLISH-LANGUAGE TRAINING AND INTERNATIONAL TRAVEL PROVIDED FROM BRAZILIAN-OWNED COUNTERPART TRUST FUND.

Abstract: Project to help the Government of Turkey (GOT) implement a program to control and eventually eliminate poppy cultivation and encourage crop substitution.  The project will finance agricultural research equipment and vehicles for the Ministry of Agriculture (MOA), police equipment and training for the Ministry of Interior (MOI), and TA. To help promote crop substitution, the project will finance laboratory equipment for the MOA's Ankara Research Center and at least three provincial research centers.  Most of the equipment will be used for research on:  (1) seeds for substitute crops such as wheat, barley, potato, peanut, safflower, and mixed vegetables; (2) animal feed or fodder crops such as alfalfa,and meat and dairy livestock products; and (3) edible oils, which could be produced by a variety of substitute crops.  Seed varieties, cultivation equipment, and pick-up trucks and power megaphones for extensionists will be funded as well. The project will also finance equipment needed by the MOI to enforce prohibitions against illegal poppy cultivation and illicit trafficking in poppy.  Specifically, the project will equip the planned 420-person narcotics control unit of the National Police and the planned 330-person narcotics control force of the Jandarma.  Items will range from revolvers and flashlights to investigative equipment to vehicles, including support vehicles for the Jandarma's narcotics control air unit. TA and training will include:  (1) a U.S. Bureau of Narcotics technician to serve as consultant to both ministries; (2) the short-term services of U.S. experts; and (3) attendance at a 3-month training program at the U.S. Narcotics Bureau for 5 senior officers each from the National Police and the Jandarma.

Abstract: Loan to the Corporacion Costarricense de Financiamiento Industrial, S.A. (COFISA), a private development bank, to provide financing for the creation and expansion of agricultural and industrial enterprises in Costa Rica and member countries of the Central American Common Market (CACM).  Both subloans and equity financing will be funded.  Emphasis will be moving COFISA beyond industrial lending (to which it was largely restricted in its formation phase under a previous A.I.D. loan) and into agriculture. A reduction of the ratio between loan funds and increases in COFISA's equity will increase the mobilization of Costa Rican funds for local cost financing, which is essential in agriculture.  The project also provides COFISA the incentive to make more equity investments to overcome the undercapitalization typical of Costa Rican firms and to begin the creation of a capital market.  It is recommended that loan funds be prohibited for industries in the C category of the CACM Industrial Incentives Treaty (primarily, assembly or packaging operations).

Abstract: TECHNICAL SUPPORT PROVIDED TO NEPAL (GON) IS TO UPGRADE THEGON EDUCATIONAL SYSTEM AND PREPARE STUDENTS TO ENTER THE JOBMARKET. CONTRACT WITH SOUTHERN ILLINOIS UNIVERSITY (SIU) ANDNATIONAL EDUCATION ASSOCIATION (NEA) PROVIDES RESOURCES TO TRAIN TEACHERS AND ADMINISTRATORS, REVISE OR DEVELOP CURRICULA, PREPARE INSTRUCTIONAL MATERIALS AND ASSIST WITH EDUCATIONAL PLANNING AND RESEARCH. IN THIS JOINT PROJECT, USAID FUNDS TA AND GON PROVIDES SPACE, PERSONNEL AND TRAVEL ALLOWANCE.GON'S NATIONAL EDUCATION SYSTEM PLAN INCLUDES FIVE RELATED ACTIVITIES: 1. VOCATIONAL EDUCATION. 2. TEACHER EDUCATION. 3.EDUCATIONAL MATERIALS. 4. SECONDARY AND MULTIPURPOSE EDUCATION. 5. PRIMARY EDUCATION. THE USAID-SPONSORED EFFORT FOCUSES ON ASSISTANCE TO THE FOLLOWING GON INSTITUTIONS: THE NATIONAL VOCATIONAL TRAINING CENTER (NVTC), DEMONSTRATION MULTIPURPOSE HIGH SCHOOL, COLLEGE OF EDUCATION AND ITS AFFILIATED LABORATORY SCHOOL, AND FIVE PRIMARY TEACHER TRAINING CENTERS.CONTRACT TEACHERS ALSO ASSIST WITH THE WRITING, EDITING, PRINTING AND PUBLISHING OF EDUCATIONAL MATERIALS, FUNCTIONS OF THE JANEK EDUCATION MATERIALS ORGANIZATION (JEMO) AND WITH BOOK DISTRIBUTION TO ALL PRIMARY AND SECONDARY SCHOOLS. IN THE OVERALL EDUCATION ASSISTANCE PROGRAM, EMPHASIS IS GIVEN TO PARTICIPANT TRAINING. CONTRACT TEACHERS ASSIST WITH PROGRAMS ON THE PRE-PRIMARY LEVEL, AND PRIMARY LEVELS FOR HANDICAPPED CHILDREN, LANGUAGE ARTS, SCIENCE AND MATHEMATICS, PHYSICAL EDUCATION AND HEALTH. ON THE SECONDARY LEVEL, CONTRACTORS ASSIST WITH BUSINESS EDUCATION, AGRICULTURAL EDUCATION, AND THE SCIENCE TEACHING ENRICHMENT PROGRAM (STEP). THEY COOPERATE WITH THE PEACE CORPS ON MANUAL WRITING AND AID IN DESIGNING TESTS FOR SOCIAL STUDIES, SCIENCE AND ENGLISH. VOCATIONAL EDUCATION IS EMPHASIZED THROUGH TA TO THE NATIONAL VOCATIONAL TRAINING CENTER WHERE COURSES ARE TAUGHT IN AGR EDUCATION, BIOLOGY, MATH, PHYSICS, CHEMISTRY AND BUSINESS EDUCATION. A DEMONSTRATION MULTIPURPOSE HIGH SCHOOL FOCUSES ON MODERN SCIENCE, TECHNOLOGY AND VOCATIONAL SKILLS. AT THE COLLEGEOF EDUCATION FOR TEACHER TRAINING, TA ASSISTS WITH PRIME, AN EXPERIMENTAL PROGRAM IN MATH FOR HIGH SCHOOL TEACHERS, GRAD

Abstract: Project to establish a population planning program in the Philippines.  Activities will include:  health personnel training; demographic research; intensive family planning (FP) pilot programs; evaluation of the rhythm as well as new contraceptive methods; surveys to measure pregnancy prevalence and incidence of induced abortion; and investigation of the effects of FP on neonatal mortality and economic development. REVISED PROP (1972) TO SUPPORT THE PHILIPPINES' NATIONAL POPULATION PLANNING PROGRAM. BY FY 76, 1,870 GOVERNMENT AND PRIVATE CLINICS WILL BE PROVIDING FP SERVICES.  EACH CLINIC WILL HAVE 2 TO 3 MEDICAL PERSONNEL (1 DOCTOR PLUS NURSES OR MIDWIVES) AND 1 OR 2 LAY FIELDWORKERS. CLINICS WILL OPERATE HALF-DAYS, MINIMUM. FIELD WORKERS OR "MOTIVATORS" WILL MAKE HOUSE-TO-HOUSE VISITS TO PROMOTE FP. CLINIC NURSES AND/OR MIDWIVES WILL ALSO SPEND HALF OF THEIR TIME MAKING HOUSE-TO-HOUSE VISITS. SHORT IN-SERVICE AND PRE-SERVICE TRAINING IN CONTRACEPTIVE METHODOLOGY WILL BE PROVIDED TO 2,660 DOCTORS, 5,680 NURSES AND MIDWIVES, AND 3,950 MOTIVATORS. ADMINISTRATIVE TRAINING AND OTHER PARTICIPANT TRAINING RELATED TO POPULATION PLANNING WILL BE PROVIDED FOR THE HEADQUARTER STAFFS OF THE POPULATION COMMISSION, DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH, AND SOME 30 OTHER PUBLIC AND PRIVATE AGENCIES INVOLVED WITH PROJECT IMPLEMENTATION. MASS EDUCATION ACTIVITIES WILL INCLUDE PAMPHLETS WRITTEN IN LOCAL DIALECTS, RADIO, TV, FILMS, AND ROVING LECTURE TEAMS. USAID WILL FINANCE LOCAL OPERATING COSTS, CLINIC EQUIPMENT AND SUPPLIES, CONTRACEPTIVES, MOTIVATIONAL SUPPLIES, PLUS LOCAL AND PARTICIPANT TRAINING. USAID WILL ALSO SUPPLY CONTRACT TECHNICAL ADVISORS AND SUPPORT DEOMGRAPHIC FIELD RESEARCH. (PD-AAD-495-A1) PRO AG 11-15-71 STIPULATES THAT GOP SHALL BEGIN TO SHARE IN LOCAL PROJECT COSTS. USAID WILL FUND CONSTRUCTION OF A POPULATION CENTER. PROP 4-5-76 OVERHAULS ENTIRE POPULATION PROGRAM. A NEW "NATIONAL FAMILY PLANNING OUTREACH" PROGRAM WILL REPLACE THE 2,300 PRESENT- LY PART-TIME AND TOWN-BASED FP MOTIVATORS WITH FULL-TIME STAFF RECRUITED FROM OUTLYING RURAL AREAS WHERE THEY WILL ACTUALLY WORK. AFTER TRAINING. 3,100 FULL-TIME MOTIVATORS WILL BE DEPLOYED (1 FOR EVERY 2,000 MARRIED COUPLES OF REPRODUCTIVE AGE). THEY WILL BE GIVEN OPERATING AND TRAVEL FUNDS (THEY HAD NONE BEFORE), AND EACH WILL ESTABLISH AND MANAGE AN AVERAGE OF 10 VILLAGE OR NEIGHBORHOOD CONTRACEPTIVE SUPPLY POINTS WHERE FREE PILLS AND CONDOMS WILL BE DISTRIBUTED. USAID WILL SUPPORT STERILIZATION THROUGH TRAINING, EQUIPMENT, AND OPERATING ROOM COSTS.

Abstract: AN INFORMAL COMMITTEE WITHIN USAID REVIEWS EACH NON-PROJECT TRAINING PROPOSAL RECEIVED FROM RTG. WHEN APPROVED, PROPOSALS ARE REFERRED TO USOM TRAINING DIVISION. EACH PARTICIPANT MUST MEET USUAL REQUIREMENTS FOR ENGLISH COMPETENCE AND PHYSICAL FITNESS. PARTICIPANTS MUST AGREE TO EMPLOYMENT IN THAILAND ON THEIR RETURN FOR AT LEAST ONE YEAR OR TWICE TAE PERIODOF TRAINING, WHICHEVER IS GREATER. IN FY 69 SPECIAL TRAINING WAS PROPOSED IN SUCH AREAS AS BIOCHEMISTRY, PEDIATRICS, ELECTRICAL ENGINEERING, ECONOMICS, COMMUNICATIONS, PRODUCTION TECHNIQUES AND PERSONNEL AND BUDGET MANAGEMENT.

Abstract: GRANT TO THE GOVT OF COSTA RICA TO SUPPORT A MULTI-AGENCY POPULATION CONTROL/FAMILY PLANNING (FP)PROGRAM.THE SPECIFIC AGENCIES & THEIR RESPECTIVE ACTIVITIES FUNDED ARE: 1.COSTA RICAN DEMOGRAPHIC ASSOC (CRDA)-A.BACKSTOPPING OVER 70 PRIVATE PHYSICIANS B.SUPPLYING PHARMACIES WITH FP SUPPLIES AT NET COST C.MAKING REDUCED-COST FP POLICIES AVAILABLE TO EMPLOYERS (POLICIES PROVIDE MED EXAMS, FP SRVCS) D.FP PUBLICITY PROG (PUBLICATIONS, PRESS, TV, RADIO) E.TRAINING PROG FOR NON-MOH OFFICIALS. 2.UNIV OF COSTA RICA-A.FP TRNG FOR KEY MED & PARAMED MOH STAFF; DEMOGRAPHIC/FP TRNG FOR MED & NURSING STDNTS B. (ANTICIPATED)SENSITIVITY & DEMOG COURSES FOR COMMUNITY LEADERS. 3.LATIN AMER CNTR FOR DEMOG STUDIES-A.DEMOG RESRCH & TCHNG B.PARTIC TRNG FOR ABORTION STUDIES. 4.MOH-A.OPENING OF AN ADDIT 34 FP CLINICS (AID PROVIDES EQPMNT & COMMODS, SUPPORTS TRNG, PAYS SALARIES OF SUBSTIT PRSNNL UNITL PERMANENT STAFF CAN COMPLETE TRNG AND PER DIEM OF NURSE EDUCATORS, AND TOPS SALARIES FOR MED & POPULATION DIRECTORS). 5.TROPICAL SCIENCE CENTER-A 1-YR AERIAL GROUND RESEARCH SURVEY OF POPULATION DISTRIBUTION. AFTER 2 YRS,FP SRVCS WILL BE INTEGRATED INTO THE TOTALITY OF HEALTH SRVCS OFFERED BY ALL MOH CLINICS.THIS WILL REQUIRE THE EQUIPPING OF 50 CLINICS BY AID. PROP(8/17/70)ASSURES CONTINUING ADVISORY,TRND & COMMOD SUPPORT FOR ORIGINAL IMPLEMENTING AGENCIES PLUS SUPPORT FOR THE CENTER FOR SOCIAL & POPULATION STUDIES(CESPO).CESPO WILL INTRODUCE SEX EDUC PROGS INTO THE SECONDARY SCHL CURRIC,COORDINATE THE RESRCH & TRNG PROGS UNDERWAY,AND CONDUCT EVAL STUDIES. PROP(10/25/73)EXTENDS PROJ THRU FY76 AND INITIATES A REORGNZTN OF THE FP PROG INTO A JOINT EFFORT BY THE MOH AND THE NATL COORDINATING COMMITTEE FOR POP & SEX EDUC(CONAPO).CONAPO MEMBRSHP:CRDA,CESPO,CNTR FOR FAMILY INTEGRATION,CNTR FOR FAM ORIENTATN,SOCIAL SECURITY INST(CCSS),MOE,AND MIN OF PUBLIC HLTH.PROJ AT THIS POINT BECOMES A BROADER-BASED RUR HLTH PROG WITH FP BEING A MAJOR ELEMENT.AID CONCENTRATES SUPPORT ON EFFORTS TO UTILIZE PARAMEDS MORE EXTENSIVELY IN RUR HLTH DELIV SRVCS & ADMIN TRNG. PROP(3/13/74)AUTHORIZES ASSISTANCE TO THE CCSS FOR THE TRNG OF WOMEN'S HLTH CARE SPECIALISTS(PARAMEDS).

Abstract: UNIVERSITY OF BOTSWANA, LESOTHO, AND SWAZILAND (UBLS), SUPPORTED BY USAID AND BLS GOVERNMENTS UNDER OFFICE OF SOUTHERN AFRICA REGIONAL ACTIVITIES COORDINATION (OSARAC), IS PRODUCING MORE, BETTER-TRAINED GRADUATES QUALIFIED TO FILL SENIOR POSITIONS IN EDUCATION, GOVERNMENT, LAW, AGRICULTURE AND PUBLIC SERVICES. TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE FROM CALIFORNIA STATE POLYTECHNIC AND TRANSCENTURY CORPORATION. AFTER 6 YEARS, ENROLLMENT TRIPLED; AGRICULTURE, EDUCATION, HUMANITIES AND SPECIAL PROJECTS DEPARTMENTS INCREASED; PHYSICAL PLANNING UNDERWAY; $100000 OF SCIENCE EQUIPMENT AVAILABLE FOR STUDENTS. 9 OF 14 PARTICIPANT-TRAINEES REPLACED U.S. TEACHERS. 2 NEW CAMPUSES-BOTSWANA AND SWAZILAND-FULLY OPERATIONAL 1974-75. OTHER DONORS: CANADA AND UNITED KINGDOM. OVERALL PLANNING BY THE UNIVERSITY INCLUDES: 1. 200-300 PRIMARY SCHOOL HEADMASTERS STUDY LEADERSHIP WORKSHOP TRAINING FOR ONE MONTH. 2. AUDIO-VISUAL CENTER AT ROMA INTRODUCES A/V METHODS INTO UBLS INSTRUCTIONAL PROCEDURES AND PROVIDES IN-SERVICE TRAINING IN ALL TEACHER TRAINING COLLEGES AS WELL AS IN MANY SECONDARY SCHOOLS AND SOME PRIMARY SCHOOLS IN THE 3 COUNTRIES. 3. 300 STUDENTS STUDY ANIMAL HUSBANDRY AND SOIL CONSERVATION FOR DIPLOMA. 4. 60 PRIMARY SCHOOL HEADMASTERS AND TEACHERS QUALIFY FOR ADVANCED CERTIFICATES OF EDUCATION, FORMING A LEADERSHIP CADRE IN EACH COUNTRY TO EXPAND THE DEVELOPMENT OF CURRICULUM TO REACH OTHER SCHOOLS NOT REACHED BY THE PROJECT. 5. TEACHERS OFFER THE TEACHING OF ENGLISH AS A FOREIGN LANGUAGE FROM THE MIDDLE PRIMARY GRADES THROUGH UNIVERSITY. 6. LOCAL EXPERTS REPLACE AID SPECIALISTS. PROBLEMS WITH CONTRACTOR INCLUDE NO BACKSTOPPING TO PERSONNEL ON-BOARD, LETTERS UNANSWERED AND CONTRACT AMENDMENTS DELAYED. UBLS IS COOPERATIVE WHEN RESPONDING TO OSARAC REQUESTS BUT HAS PROBLEMS IN MANAGEMENT AND COST-EFFECTIVENESS ADMINISTRATION. OSARAC FOCUSES LESS ON PROVIDING INSTRUCTORS AND INSTRUCTIONAL MATERIALS TO CONCENTRATING ON ADMINISTRATION AND FINANCES. UBLS AND MINISTRIES OF EDUCATION RECEIVE ASSISTANCE FROM OTHER DONORS ON PROJECTS WHICH ARE COMPLEMENTARY AND NOT DUPLICATIVE TO AID PROJECT INPUTS: AMONG THESE ARE: 1. EDUCATION PLANNERS IN LESOTHO AND SWAZILAND; 2. PRIMARY SCHOOL CURRICULUM SPECIALIST IN SWAZILAND; 3. SECONDARY SCHOOL SCIENCE AND MATH SPECIALISTS IN ALL 3 COUNTRIES; 4. AFRICAN SOCIAL STUDIES WORKSHOP IN BOTSWANA.

Abstract: AS OF 12/31/68. WORK BEGAN 3/66 WITH ASSIGNMENT OF TEAM LEADER AND MOBILE AUDIT TRAINING TEAM TO GIVE BASIC TRAINING TO ALL TAX AUDITORS. FULL-TIME AUDIT ADVISOR ALSO ASSIGNED. AUDIT DEPT DEVELOPED CAPACITY FOR ORGANIZING AND GIVING IN-SERVICE TRAINING. REGULATIONS ARE BEING WRITTEN FOR INCOME TAX LAW BY OAS/IDB MISSION. ALL INTERNAL INDIRECT TAXES, EXCEPT ALCOHOL AND TOBACCO,WERE INTEGRATED WITH DIRECT TAXES 1/1/68. HONDURAS TAX OFFICIALS SUPPORTED PROJECT AND IN MOST CASES WELCOMED RECOMMENDATIONS. HOWEVER, TOO MUCH FOLLOW-UP ON PART OF TAX TEAM WAS NECESSARY FOR RECOMMENDATIONS TO ACTUALLY BE ADOPTED. PAY AND ALLOWANCE PROBLEMS RESULTED IN DEPARTURES OF A NUMBER OF AUDITORS AND OTHER TECHNICAL PERSONNEL. INCOME TAX REVENUES INCREASED FROM $8,314,000 IN 1965 TO $19,000,000 IN 1968. PAR REPORTS THAT TO A LARGE EXTENT THIS WAS ATTRIBUTABLE TO HIGHER PROFITS IN BANANA INDUSTRY, BUT CONSIDERABLE PART WAS ALSO ATTRIBUTABLE TO BROADENED AUDIT PROGRAM AND THE ADDITION OF NEW TAXPAYERS.

Abstract: EVALUATES PROJECT FROM ITS COMMENCEMENT THROUGH 12/68. PROJECT PROCEEDED AS PLANNED WITH THE PERFORMANCE OF THE MAJOR CONTRACTOR, THE INTERNATIONAL RICE RESEARCH INSTITUTE (IRRI), BEING HIGHLY SATISFACTORY. ONE FAVORABLE RESULT, UNANTICIPATED AT THIS STAGE OF THE PROJECT, WAS THE DEVELOPMENT AND RELEASE OF TWO NEW HIGH-YIELDING RICE VARIETIES. PROBLEMS WHICH AROSE DURING THIS PERIOD WERE DELAYS IN THE PROCUREMENT OF COMMODITIES, AND A SHORTAGE OF TRAINING CANDIDATES UNDERGOING TRAINING AT THE IRRI. IT APPEARED THAT THE MULTI-DISCIPLINARY AND CONCENTRATED APPROACH TAKEN BY THIS PROJECT TO SOLVE RESEARCH PROBLEMS WAS A VIABLE ONE.

Abstract: DOCUMENT DESCRIBES DESIGN OF RESEARCH STUDY TO ASSESS PROGRESS IN AID-FUNDED PROJECT (AID-DLCP-738) TO IMPROVE AND MODERNIZE PRIMARY AND SECONDARY EDUCATIONAL SYSTEMS IN EL SALVADOR THROUGH CURRICULAR REVISION, RETRAINING OF TEACHERS, AND INTRODUCTION OF CLASSROOM TELEVISION. PRIMARY RESEARCH OBJECTIVES ARE: 1)TO ASCERTAIN AS FULLY AS POSSIBLE THE EFFECTS OFINSTRUCTIONAL TELEVISION (ITV) USE IN EL SALVADOR; 2)TO DERIVE PRINCIPLES AND GUIDELINES APPLICABLE TO OTHERS INTERESTED IN THE USE OF ITV AS A CLASSROOM AID; 3)TO CONTRIBUTE TO THE EFFICIENCY OF THE EL SALVADOR PROJECT. THIS DOCUMENT DISCUSSES POSSIBLE MEANS OF MEETING THESE OBJECTIVES WITHIN EXISTING LIMITATIONS OF TIME AND FUNDS. A FIRST YEAR RESEARCH STRATEGY IS PRESENTED, ALONG WITH PREDICTIONS OF FUTURE RESEARCH TRENDS.

Abstract: PROJECT PROVIDES IN-SERVICE TRAINING IN MATERNAL-CHILD HEALTH (MCH), FAMILY HEALTH SERVICES FOR 50 (200 PROPOSED INITIALLY) NURSES, MIDWIVES, PARAMEDICS. PROJECT IS COORDINATED WITH EXISTING TRAINING PROGRAMS OF MCH DIVISION ASSISTED BY UNICEF.

Abstract: LOAN CONTINUES FINANCING OF ON-GOING COMMUNITY DEVELOPMENT (CD) PROGRAM AND INTRODUCES CD ACTIVITIES IN AGRARIAN REFORM. PROGRAM CONTRIBUTES TO LEARNING PROCESS BY PROVIDING MATERIAL, TECHNICAL RESOURCES TO VILLAGES WHICH HAVE ORGANIZED TO OBTAIN SMALL DEVELOPMENT PROJECTS (POTABLE WATER, ACCESS ROADS, MEDICAL CENTERS, SCHOOLS). PROJECTS ARE CATALYSTS FOR CREATION OF VILLAGE INSTITUTIONS THROUGH WHICH CAMPESINO CAN LEARN VALUE OF SELF-HELP ACTIVITY, AS COMMUNITY PROVIDES AT LEAST 50% PROJECT COST. PROJECT SPEEDS DISTRIBUTION OF LAND TITLES UNDER AGRARIAN REFORM LAW BY IDENTIFYING PRACTICAL PROBLEMS AND SOLUTIONS. 511048201 IS ALSO ON LINE. THIS IS NOT BASKET PROJECT. 2 UNRELATED PROJS WERE ASSIGNED SAME NUMBER.

Abstract: LOAN TO IMPERIAL ETHIOPIAN GOVERNMENT (IEG) PROVIDES DESIGN SERVICES AND PROCUREMENT OF MATERIALS EQUIPMENT FOR ADDITIONS TO UNIVERSITY OF HAILE SELASSIE (HSIU) (PHASE I). PHASE 2 INCLUDES FUNDS FOR CONSTRUCTION AND EQUIPMENT OF PHASE 1 DESIGNS FOR DORMITORIES FOR 2500 STUDENTS FOR CAFETERIA-AUDITORIUM AT ADDIS ABABA CAMPUS OF HSIU AND A 500-STUDENT DORMITORY AND CLASSROOM BUILDING AT ALEMAYA CAMPUS OF HSIU. IEG PROVIDES 25% OF COSTS. HSIU ESTABLISHED IN 1961 WITH 7 COLLEGES AND FACULTIES AND AN ENROLLMENT OF 948 STUDENTS, BY 1970/71 HAD REACHED AN ENROLLMENT OF 4,500 REGULAR STUDENTS AND 2,200 EXTENSION STUDENTS. MEANWHILE IEG'S THIRD FIVE YEAR PLAN (1968-73) FORECAST A NEED OF 7,800 HIGH-LEVEL TRAINED MANPOWER (ADMINISTRATORS, MANAGERS, PROFESSIONAL AND SCIENTIFIC PERSONNEL) WHILE THE OUTPUT OF INSTITUTIONS OF HIGHER EDUCATION DURING THE SAME PERIOD WOULD BE ONLY 3,000. IEG AND HSIU OFFICIALS SEE BULK OF MANPOWER NEED CONCENTRATED IN EDUCATION, AGRICULTURE, ENGINEERING, SCIENCE. TO MEET PROJECTED EXPANSION IN ENROLLMENTS, HSIU NEEDS ADDITIONAL FACILITIES AT ADDIS ABABA, ALEMAYA AND GONDAR CAMPUSES. (GONDAR CAMPUS PLANS, HOWEVER, MUST AWAIT NEW LAND.) CONTRACTS FOR EXPANSION SERVICES AT HSIU GO TO DALTON-DALTON-LITTLE AND NEWPORT, AN ARCHITECTURAL ENGINEERING FIRM, AND TO AFRO-AMERICAN PURCHASING CENTER (AAPC) FOR COMMODITIES. KEY BOOK AGENCY WAS TO ACQUIRE NEEDED BOOKS. OTHER DONORS OF CAPITAL ASSISTANCE FOR HSIU: SWEDEN, GERMANY, UN (UNDP, UNICEF, UNESCO, WHO) AND SEVERAL BILATERAL DONORS (UK, BELGIUM, FRANCE, ITALY, ISRAEL, NETHERLANDS -- ALSO GERMANY, SWEDEN) AND SEVERAL PRIVATE SOURCES (FORD FOUNDATION, WELCOME FOUNDATION).

Abstract: LOAN TO GOVERNMENT OF MALAWI WILL SUPPORT FOREIGN EXCHANGE COSTS OF MATERIALS AND SERVICES AND A PORTION OF THE LOCAL COSTS INVOLVED IN CONSTRUCTION OF TWO MAJOR ROAD LINKS (126 MILES) ALONG THE WESTERN SHORE OF LAKE MALAWI. PROJECT FORMS PART OF A LARGER SCHEME TO LINK ZOMBA IN THE SOUTH WITH THE NORTHERN PART OF THE COUNTRY VIA A LAKE SHORE ROUTE. WORLD BANK AND FEDERAL REPUBLIC OF GERMANY ARE FINANCING OTHER SEGMENTS. 90 MILE BALAKA-SELIMA ROAD WILL RUN NORTH-SOUTH, PARALLEL TO AND WEST OF THE EXISTING RAILROAD. CONSTRUCTION WILL REPLACE SUB-STANDARD SEASONAL ROAD WITH AN ENGINEERED ALL -WEATHER ROAD. CONSTRUCTION WILL BE TO MALAWI CLASS I DESIGN STANDARDS, CONSISTING OF A 38 FOOT EMBANKMENT WITH A SIX INCH GRAVEL WEARING SURFACE AND A 22 FOOT CARRIAGEWAY. ROAD WILL BE ADAPTABLE TO RESURFACING AT A LATER DATE TO PROVIDE A HARD SURFACE CARRIAGEWAY WITH TWO FIVE FOOT SHOULDERS. ROAD WIL REQUIRE 9 TWO-LANE BRIDGES OVER 20 FEET IN LENGTH. MUA MISSION-MONKEY BAY SECTION (36 MILES) WILL EXTEND FROM MUA, ON THE BALAKA-SALIMA ROAD, TO A JUNCTION 10 MILES SOUTH OF MONKEY BAY ON THE MONKEY BAY-FT JOHNSON ROAD. EXCEPT FOR A 12 MILE STRETCH, BETWEEN MUA AND SOSOLU, ROAD WILL REPLACE LOW QUALITY DISTRICT ROADS. DESIGN IS TO MALAWI CLASS III STANDARDS, CONSISTING OF A 30 FOOT EMBANKMENT WITH A SIX INCH GRAVEL WEARING SURFACE AND TWO THREE-FOOT SHOULDERS. TWO MAJOR BRIDGES WILL BE REQUIRED. CONSTRUCTION, IF BIDS FALL WITHIN COST ESTIMATES, WILL BE PERFORMED BY A QUALIFIED US FIRM. IF NO RESPONSIVE BIDS ARE RECEIVED. CONSTRUCTION BY FORCE ACCOUNT(IE, BY THE GOM'S MINISTRY OF PUBLIC WORKS, UTILIZING ITS OWN PERSONNEL) WILL BE CONSIDERED.IN THE LATTER CASE, EXTERNAL ASSISTANCE WILL BE REQUIRED TO PROVIDE EQUIPMENT, MATERIALS, AND SUPERVISORY PERSONNEL. IN ADDITION TO LINKING NORTHERNAND SOUTHERN MALAWI, PROJECT WILL HAVE THE EFFECT OF INCREASING ACCESS TO A 3200 SQUARE MILE AREA WHICH IS CURRENTLY UNDERPOPULATED AND LITTLE FARMED (ONLY 20% OF ARABLE LAND UNDER CULTIVATION). IN ADDITION, ROAD LINK TO MONKEY BAY IS EXPECTED TO BOOST TOURISM IN THAT AREA.

Abstract: This is a revision to a pamphlet issued on "United States Aid to Laos" in May, 1966.  It brings up to date the developments in the United States aid program to Laos since that time.  Where no substantial change has occurred in the aid program or activities, sections of the previous pamphlet have been reprinted largely without alteration.  The main change during the past two years has been the greater concentration of aid efforts on the development program.  This emphasis is consistent with the objectives and desires of the Royal Lao Government (a) to achieve economic independence as a nation, and (b) to improve the living conditions of the Lao people.  (Author abstract)

Abstract: Compares the economic feasibilities and technological capabilities of manual and mechanical irrigation pump units in India. The study concluded that the cost of labor must be reduced by nearly 90% in order to reduce the costs for the manual-powered unit to the costs of the engine-driven unit for water lifting from typical wells. Although the total investment and installation costs for an engine-driven unit are the highest, its performance characteristics are better and it requires both the lowest per acre investment and operating costs. Also, man-powered pumping units are only adequate in lifting water 5-10 feet from canals, whereas the use of well water requires a mechanical pumping system such as an engine capable of lifting water 40 feet or more, or bullock power adequate in lifting water up to 25 feet. Electrically-driven units, normally considered less expensive than diesel-powered units, were not considered in this study. It was suggested that farmers owning less than 10 acres should either sell water or share pump costs with others to make their irrigation economically feasible. Thus, economics of scale are found to apply to the problem of pumping irrigation water.

Abstract: THE FORMAT OF A ONE-YEAR RESEARCH PROJECT CONCERNING EL SALVADOR'S EDUCATIONAL REFORM. ITS PURPOSES ARE: 1) TO ASCERTAIN THE EFFECTS OF INSTRUCTIONAL TELEVISION (ITV); 2) TO DERIVE PRINCIPLES AND GUIDELINES FROM EL SALVADOR'S REFORM FOR USE IN OTHER COUNTRIES; AND 3) TO CONTRIBUTE, BY MEANS OF COMMUNICATION RESEARCH, TO THE REFORM'S EFFICIENCY. THE REPORT THEN ELABORATES ON THE TYPES OF RESEARCH TO BE DONE: 1) ON ATTITUDES OF, AND COGNITIVE AND BEHAVIORAL CHANGES IN PUPILS, TEACHERS, AND SCHOOL ADMINISTRATORS; 2) AN "ADMINISTRATIVE RECORD" AND ON POTENTIAL PROBLEMS IN ADMINISTRATIVE RELATIONSHIPS AND POLICY-MAKING PROCEDURES; AND 3) APPLICATION OF RESEARCH TO INCREASE THE REFORM'S EFFICIENCY. NECESSARY LIMITATIONS OF TIME AND FACILITIES ALSO ARE RECOGNIZED AND DISCUSSED.

Abstract: TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE GIVEN TO GOP TO CONTINUE PROGRAM TO ERADICATE MALARIA BEGUN IN 1953. NOW LIMITED TO RURAL & NEWLY SETTLED AREAS WHERE MALARIA STILL REMAINS, PROGRAM INVOLVES CYCLICAL INSECTICIDAL SPRAYING COUPLED WITH HOUSE-TO-HOUSE & CLINICAL SCREENING & TREATMENT OF VICTIMS. FORMERLY DECENTRALIZED PROGRAM NOW CENTRALLY ADMINISTERED BY MALARIA ERADICATION SERVICE CONDUCTING OPERATIONS IN DELIMITED MALARIOUS AREAS. EACH AREA MONITORS ENDEMIC LEVEL TO DETERMINE INTENSITY OF ERADICATION EFFORT NECESSARY WITHIN, RESULTING FINALLY IN AREA HEALTH DEPTS ASSUMING CONTROL WHEN PROPER LEVEL ACHIEVED. FULL SUPERVISION CONFERRED ON PROVINCIAL HEALTH DEPTS & GOP BY 1974. ADDITIONALLY FUNDED & ASSISTED BY WHO & GOP.
Secondary Descriptors: Disease detection|Epidemiology|Rural areas

Abstract: GRANT AND TECHNICAL SERVICES PROVIDED TO GOVERNMENT OF JORDAN (GOJ) TO TRAIN PLANNERS, ANALYSTS AND MANAGERS NEEDED TO DETERMINE POLICY AND IMPLEMENT DEVELOPMENT PROJECTS. THREE-YEAR TRAINING PROGRAM IMPLEMENTED FOR BOTH GOVERNMENTAL AND NON-GOVERNMENTAL PERSONNEL. TRAINING CONDUCTED IN UAR AND U.S. INCLUDES SHORT-TERM COURSES, AND DIRECTLY BENEFITS GOVERNMENT, EDUCATORS, BUSINESSES; AND INDIRECTLY THE PEOPLE IN URBAN AND RURAL AREAS AS GOVERNMENTAL PROCESSES BECOME MORE EFFICIENT, AND AS BUSINESS, AGRICULTURE, HEALTH FACILITIES AND TOURISM ARE IMPROVED. PROJECT ACTIVITIES INCLUDE: 1)ADVANCED DEGREE TRAINING IN DEVELOPMENT ECONOMICS, ADMINISTRATION AND PUBLIC ADMINISTRATION FOR YOUNG GOJ EMPLOYEES; 2)ADVANCED DEGREE TRAINING FOR GRADUATE INSTRUCTORS AND ASSISTANT PROFESSORS AT THE UNIV OF JORDAN; 3)TRAINING FOR FAMILY PLANNERS IN U.D.; 4)TECHNICAL SKILL TRAINING FOR PERSONNEL IN THE CENTRAL BANK, DEPARTMENT OF STATISTICS, TOURISM AND ANTIQUITIES, THE AQABA CUSTOMS LABORATORY; 5)SHORT COUSES BY EXPERTS IN MANAGEMENT AT THE UNIVERSITY OF JORDAN; 6)ACADEMIC AND TECHNICAL TRAINING IN UAR FOR MINISTRY OF EDUCATION TEACHERS AND TECHNICAL PERSONNEL. HOST COUNTRY PROVIDES ONLY THE PARTICIPANTS. JORDAN DEVELOPMENT BOARD IS OPERATING AGENCY FOR RECRUITING CANDIDATES AND IMPLEMENTING PROJECT.

Abstract: TRAINING PROVIDED TO CHILEAN LABOR LEADERS AND ADVISORS THRU COUNTERPART UNIONS IN U.S, AND PUERTO RICO AS STRATEGY FOR DEVELOPING DEMOCRATIC, RESPONSIBLE LABOR MOVEMENT IN CHILE. PROJECT GOALS ARE: 1. TO WORK WITH EXISTING FREE LABOR GROUPS TO STRENGTHEN THEM AGAINST EXTREMIST POLITICAL FORCES AND INCREASE THEIR INFLUENCE IN LABOR MOVEMENT; 2. TO WORK WITH UNION GROUPS OUTSIDE FREE LABOR MOVEMENT TO REDUCE POLITICAL CONTROL EXERTED BY LEFT WING GROUPS; 3. SUPPORT CHILEAN LABOR GROUPS TO ESTABLISH NATIONAL CONFEDERATION OF FREE TRADE UNIONS; 4. TO NEUTRALIZE MARXIST PROPAGANDA AIMED AT LABOR MOVEMENT AND TO CHANGE ATTITUDES OF MARXIST LABOR UNION LEADERS TOWARDS THE US. GOAL WILL BE ACHIEVED THRU: 1. PROVISION OF TRAINING IN U.S. OR PUERTO RICO FOR SELECTED UNION LEADERS; 2. PROVISION OF IN-COUNTRY TRAINING EACH YEAR FOR ABOUT 1,000 OFFICIALS AND UNION MEMBERS THRU THE AMERICAN INSTITUTE FOR FREE LABOR DEVELOPMENT (AIFLD); 3. ASSISTANCE IN DEVELOPING LABOR UNION HOUSING PROJECTS, AND; 4. ASSISTANCE WITH FINANCING SMALL PROJECTS OF SPECIAL SOCIAL, POLITICAL, OR ECONOMIC SIGNIFICANCE ORGANIZED BY LABOR GROUPS.  AIFLD EDUCATION PROGRAM CONSISTS OF SEMINARS AND COURSES OF VARYING DURATION. INCLUDES MATERIALS ON COLLECTIVE BARGAINING; UNION ORGANIZATION, ADMINISTRATION, AND FINANCE; CHILEAN LABOR CODE; AND INTERNATIONAL LABOR MOVEMENTS.  SPECIAL SUBJECTS INCLUDE COOPERATIVISM AND WORK MEASUREMENT SYSTEMS. AIFLD ADDITIONALLY SUPPLIES TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE AND MODEST FINANCIAL ASSISTANCE FROM AFL-CIO FUND OR THRU SPECIAL ACTIVITIES GRANT FROM THE MISSION.

Abstract: The Turkish Health Manpower Study begun in 1963, has two sets of objectives. Turkish planners and educators were interested in how the health needs of Turkey could best be met. There was discussion of the need for radically altering medical and nursing education. This study attempted to: define the numbers and classifications of health personnel; identify imbalances in geographical, rural/urban, or social distributions of personnel; study utilization patterns of health services and determine present demand. It also analyzes economic factors controlling the potential expansion of health services; studies educational trends; explores various possibilities of improving the quality and efficiency of health services; and evaluates the pilot projects of the national health services and made suggestions for improving the national plan. The second set of objectives was to achieve technical sophistication and imagination in methodological innovation to measure and project both effective demand and supply of health manpower. Specific studies were conducted to gather data in the following areas: tracing and identifying the supply of professionals, defining major difficulties of medical practice and doctor utilization, and identifying the major professional problems of nurses. Data was also gathered on estimating cost of medical services and doctors' income, determining problems of rural health services, evaluating medical education, and estimating unmet demand for health services. Two generalizations come from this analysis. Manpower availability can be increased more efficiently and rapidly by improving utilization of personnel already available. The most important qualitative considerations in educational planning relate to the development of the service values and attitudes which determine the ultimate productivity, effectiveness, and quality of all personnel.
Personal Author: Taylor, Carl E.|Dirican, Rahmi|Deuschle, K. W.

Abstract: APPLIED RESEARCH WILL INCREASE EFFICIENCY OF AGRICULTURAL PRODUCTION AND ACCELERATE RURAL DEVELOPMENT THROUGH EFFECTIVE USE OF EXISTING RESOURCES; IT WILL SUPPORT FORMULATION OF SOUND POLICY AS WELL. GON WILL APPOINT A HIGH LEVEL MARKETING ADVISORY BOARD WITH RESPONSIBILITY FOR COORDINATION AND FUNDING. PROGRAMS ARE NEEDED FOR TRANSMISSION OF DATA, PRICE STABILIZATION & SOUND MARKETING POLICY. A CRITICAL NEED EXISTS FOR ANALYSIS OF A TWO-CROP EXPORT-ORIENTED AGRICULTURE TO HELP RAISE FARMERS ABOVE SUBSISTENCE FARMING IF RURAL LIFE IS TO BE IMPROVED. GON, WITH AID TECHNOLOGICAL HELP, WILL ATTEMPT TO CREATE THE CORRECT TOTAL PACKAGE FOR MAXIMUM USE OF SOIL, WATER AND HUMAN RESOURCES.

Abstract: THE CREDIT UNION DEVELOPMENT ACTIVITIES IN TANZANIA WILL BE CONTINUED ON A BILATERAL BASIS FOR TWO YEARS, OR UNTIL A REGIONAL APPROACH CAN BE DEVELOPED. THE US WILL CONTINUE THE CUNA CONTRACT ADVISORY SERVICES OF TWO TECHNICIANS. US WILL PROVIDE PARTICIPANT TRAINING IN SUPERVISION AND INSPECTION OF CREDIT UNIONS THROUGHOUT THE 17 REGIONS OF TANZANIA. TANZAN-IAN GOVT WILL INSURE ADEQUATE BUDGET ALLOCATIONS AND PROVIDE QUALIFIED COUNTERPARTS FOR EACH OF THE TWO CUNA TECHNICIANS. AN ADDITIONAL 284 CREDIT UNIONS WILL BE ESTABLISHED BY THE TANZANIAN GOVERNMENT TO COMPLETE THE PROJECT GOAL OF 400 CREDIT UNIONS.

Abstract: GENERAL TECHNICAL SERVICES AGREEMENT (GTSA) WITH NATIONAL EDUCATION ASSOCATION (NEA) FACILITATES IMPLEMENTATION OF PRESIDENTIAL DIRECTIVE TO AID (CONTAINED IN MESSAGE TO CONGRESS ON INTERNATIONAL EDUCATION AND HEALTH) TO DOUBLE THE NUMBER OF PARTICIPANTS IN THE SUMMER TEACH CORPS PROGRAM. NEA HAS ALREADY CONDUCTED SEVERAL TEACH CORPS PROGRAMS UNDER DIRECT CONTRACTS WITH INDIVIDUAL MISSIONS. GTSA PROVIDES STAFFING SUPPORT AND A CONTRACTUAL DEVISE AGAINST WHICH USAIDS CAN PLACE TASK ORDERS AS NEEDED. COUNTRY ACTIVITIES ARE FINANCED BY MISSION FUNDS. OPERATIONAL TARGET OF PROJECT IS ESTABLISHMENT OF A SMALL STAFF WITHIN NEA EQUIPPED TO RECRUIT TEACHER AND EDUCATION SPECIALISTS FOR WORKSHOPS ABROAD, MAKE EFFECTIVE PREPARATIONS, AND EVALUATE ACTIVITIES. THROUGH ACTIVITIES OF TEACH CORPS, EXPERT EDUCATORS AT ELEMENTARY AND SECONDARY LEVELS ASSIST MINISTRIES OF EDUCATION IN DEVELOPING NATIONS TO PROVIDE SHORT-TERM, IN-SERVICE WORKSHOPS. WORKSHOPS STRESS BASIC LEARNING PRINCIPLES, TEACHING METHODS, AND TEACHING AIDS, AND PROVIDE MINISTRIES WITH MODELS FOR SUBSEQUENT IN-SERVICE PROGRAMS. TEACH CORPS ACTIVITIES HAVE BEEN CONDUCTED IN COSTA RICA, COLOMBIA, DOMINICAN REPUBLIC, EL SALVADOR, HONDURAS, VENEZUELA, JAMAICA, SIERRA LEONE, TANZANIA, KENYA, AND NEPAL. PROJECT SHOULD DIRECTLY BENEFIT TEACHERS RECEIVING TRAINING, AND, LESS DIRECTLY, BENEFIT THEIR STUDENTS.

Abstract: AUDIT REPORT FOR 9/1/64-9/30/67 PERIOD OF OPERATION BROTHERHOOD SUBACTIVITY OF 1963-1975 PUBLIC HEALTH DVLP PROJ IN LAOS. IN OPERATION SINCE 1957,WITH USAID FUNDING OF CONTRACT SERVICES SINCE 1963, SUBACTIVITY SUPPORTS THE OPERATION OF A VIENTIANE HOSIPTAL & TRAINING CENTER AND 7 PROVINCIAL HOSPITALS AND VARIOUS DISPENSARIES UNDER THE DIRECTION OF OPERATION BROTHERHOOD INTERNATIONAL (OBI) OF MANILA. FROM 1957 THROUGH 9/30/67,DOLLAR OBLIGATIONS TOTALED $6.6 MILLION,LOCAL CURRENCY OBLIGATIONS AN EQUIVALENT $2.49 MILLION. STAFFING AS OF 9/67 INCLUDED AN AMERICAN PROJ ADVISOR,122 FILIPINOS & 380 LOCAL PERSONNEL. AUDIT CONDUCTED TO EVALUATE OBI PERFORMANCE,COMPLIANCE WITH CONTRACT PROVISIONS & PROPRIETY OF COSTS CHARGED TO CONTRACT. AUDITORS EXAMINED PROJ DOCUMENTS AND RECORDS,INSPECTED PROPERTY AND SUPPLY MGMT RECORDS & EXAMINED PURCHASE RECORDS. AUDITORS FOUND THAT ACCOUNTABILITY RECORDS WERE NOT BEING MAINTANED FOR IN-USE,NON EXPENDABLE PROPERTY.  OBI INVENTORIES MAKE NO DISTINCTION BETWEEN GOVT-FURNISHED & CONTRACTOR-OWNED PROPERTY. OF A SAMPLING OF 274 ITEMS GOVT-FURNISHED PROPERTY,27% WERE UNLOCATABLE. 84% OF SAMPLE OF AID-FINANCED COMMODITIES WERE NOT PROPERLY MARKED WITH AID EMBLEM AS REQUIRED. THESE AREAS OF NON-COMPLIANCE HAD BEEN CITED IN A PREVIOUS AUDIT. AUDITORS RECOMMEND THAT USAID PUBLIC HEALTH DIVISION(PHD) REQUIRE OBI TO ACCOUNT FOR ALL ITEMS OF MISSING GOVT PROPERTY; TO ESTABLISH & MAINTAIN ACCOUNTABILITY RECORDS;AND TO ASSURE THAT CURRENT & FUTURE NON-EXPENDABLE ITEMS ARE AFFIXED WITH AID EMBLEM. OTHER RECOMMENDATIONS RELATE TO ADDITONAL IRREGULARITIES OBSERVED: OBI SHOULD PROMPT LY INVENTORY SUPPLIES;ESTABLISH 90 DAY STOCK LEVELS AT FIELDHOSIPTALS,TURNING OVER STOCKPILED & OBSOLETE SUPPLIES TO PHD;AND ESTABLISH TIMELY,ACCURATE FIELD SUPPLY MGMT REPORTING PROCEDURES. OBI SHOULD MAINTAIN ADEQUATE TIME RECORDS AND ENSURE THAT ALL EMPLOYEES WORK 40-HR WORKWEEKS. COLLECTION PROCEDURES SHOULD BE IMPROVED AT VIENTIANE HOSIPTAL;INITIATED AT FIELD HOSIPTALS. MANILA OBI ADMIN EXPENSES,INCLUDING SUBSCRIPTION COSTS,NOT TO BE CHARGED TO CONTRACT. CORRECTIVE ACTION TAKEN TO REDUCE EXCESSIVE PURCHASE AT OBI TRAINEES' MESS.
Ancilary Data: Evaluation period: 1 Sep 1964-30 Sep 1967

Abstract: Subproject to help Nicaragua's Ministry of Agriculture (MOA) expand and upgrade the quality of its applied research activities which focus on the production of major food crops and animal products.  The subproject will utilize existing experiment stations and local farms to study the production of rice, corn, sorghum, pork, milk, and forage. Research will also be carried out on new agricultural products for which there is an active demand in Nicaragua and Central America.  The MOA will receive TA from a U.S. university.

Abstract: PRESENTS, THROUGH THE PERIOD ENDING 1/31/68, RESEARCH RESULTS OF A UNIVERSITY OF WISCONSIN CONTRACT TEAM IN A PROJECT TO CONDUCT RESEARCH ON THE PROBABLE BENEFITS OF INCREASED ECONOMIC COOPERATION AMONG SOUTH AND SOUTHEASTERN ASIAN COUNTRIES AND THE CONDITIONS REQUIRED TO REALIZE THESE BENEFITS. PRESENTATION IS IN THE FORM OF 2 AIRGRAMS, BOTH DATED 1/31/68. FIRST AIRGRAM NOTES THE FORMS IN WHICH RESEARCH RESULTS HAVE APPEARED: RESEARCH PAPERS (RP'S), SUITABLE IN SCOPE AND CONTENT TO WARRANT PUBLICATION IN PROFESSIONAL JOURNALS; CONFERENCE PAPERS (CP'S), SIMILAR IN FORM AND SUBSTANCE TO RP'S, BUT LISTED (AND TO BE PUBLISHED) SEPARATELY, BECAUSE SPECIFIICALLY PREPARED FOR THE UNIVERSITY OF WISCONSIN-AID CONFERENCE ON ECONOMIC INTERDEPENDENCE IN SOUTHEAST ASIA HELD IN BANGKOK IN 1/67; BACKGROUND PAPERS PREPARED IN CONNECTION WITH CONTRACT OBJECTIVES. MAIN BODY OF THE AIRGRAM PROVIDES DETAILED DISCUSSION (WITH REFERENCES TO SPECIFIC RESEARCH DOCUMENTS, OF THE PRINCIPAL RESEARCH RESULTS ALREADY OUTLINED IN AIRGRAM OF 10/28/67 (DOCID: B9310402007301). Abstract: The methodology of a study designed to analyze agricultural development problems at the farm level in southern Brazil.  The research areas include: (1) the role of capital in agricultural development; (2) the relationship of type of farm and farm size to labor and power requirements on farms; and (3) the relationship of management level to capital use intensity and productivity. Descriptive data on 954 farms representing a cross section of types of farming regions in southern Brazil are presented in this report. The data show that individual farms vary widely in several thousands of hectares. Technology levels on neighboring farms may vary from hand methods to the most modern of mechanized power units. Differences in the level of use of other forms of technology are equally apparent. Market orientation varies from subsistence-oriented farming to highly commercialized agricultural production units. Farm investment and income patterns show similar differences. External sources of capital use by farm operators are principally government oriented.  This indicates a dependence of farmers on government for investment capital. Thus government may be able to introduce desired changes in the capital structure of agriculture. However, the fact that government credit is closely tied to subsidized interest rates may indicate a general lack of profitability of additional capital in agriculture.

Abstract: A description of a study designed to evaluate various methods of producing coarse flour (atta) and maiking unleavened bread (chapatis) from it, using several kinds of U.S. and Pakistani wheats. Chapatis made from atta is common food in Pakistan and India.  Attas of 80% and 95% extraction were common food in Pakistan and India.  Attas of 80% and 95% extraction were prepared from Hard Red Winter, Hard Red Spring, Durum, White club, soft Red Winter, and Pakistani wheats.  The particle size distribution of experimental attas were in the range of that of typical Pakistani attas.  The composition and doughy characteristics of the experimental attas were experimentally varied.  The chapatis made from the attas was evaluated in terms of its sight, aroma, and taste appeal by a panel of experienced chapatis-eaters, using a scoring system devised for the experienced chapatis-eaters, using a scoring system devised for the purpose. All attas except those produced from Durum wheat yeilded satisfactory chapatis.  color is apparently a major factor in determining accepatability; the White Club and Pakistani wheat products were judged significantly more acceptable than those made from any red wheat.

Abstract: The methods and results of a study of the comparative nutritional value of various wheat flours (attas) and unleavened breads (chapatis) fed to rats during an eight-week trial period.  Rats were fed attas of 80% and 95% extraction, and chapatis made from them, with and without vitamin and mineral supplementation, and with lysine at two levels of supplementation.  Growth rates and protein efficiency rations (PER) were evaluated weekly for eight weeks.  The PER values were higher for chapatis than for theattas from which they were prepared.  Vitamin and mineral supplements resulted in an increase in PER during the eight weeks.  Diets with lysine-supplemented diets had lower moisture content and higher content than those of rats on other diets. The results tend to show that fortification of cereal products with lysine, without concurrent fortification with vitamins and minerals, may not be of value when the products form essentially the only article of diet, as is often true in developing countries.

Abstract: THE PROBLEM OF CHOICE WHICH CONFRONT RURAL DEVELOPMENT AGENCIES IN WORKING OUT THE BROADER ASPECTS OF PROGRAM CONTENT AND APPROACH AS WELL AS THEIR IMPLEMENTATION, SUGGEST VARIOUS ACTIONS THAT SOCIAL SCIENTISTS OF ALL KINDS COULD TAKE TO HELP OFFICIALS AND TECHNICIANS MAKE MORE EFFECTIVE DECISIONS. IN EXPLORING THESE PROBLEMS, THE FOLLOWING TOPICS ARE CONSIDERED: CHANGE-AGENCY DECISIONS AS RESOURCE ALLOCATION, MAKING PROGRAM CHOICES, OPERATIONAL STEPS FOR EVALUATING PROGRAM ALTERNATIVES, CLARIFYING AND WEIGHING PROGRAM OBJECTIVES, THE IMPORTANCE OF CONSIDERING HUMAN RESPONSES, SOME COMPLICATING REALITIES, AND PUTTING PLANS INTO ACTION. IT WAS FOUND THAT MORE RESEARCH IS NEEDED TO DETERMINE THE SUCCESS OR FAILURE OF RURAL DEVELOPMENT PROGRAMS ALREADY UNDERTAKEN, AND A STUDY OF WAYS FOR PROFESSIONAL ADVISORS, PLANNERS, AND RESEARCHERS TO BE OF MORE EFFECTIVE HELP TO ACTION PROGRAMS WOULD BE VERY WORTHWHILE. THERE ALSO NEEDS TO BE BETTER COMMUNICATION OF RESEARCH FINDINGS AND SIMPLIFICATION OF DECISION-MAKING CONCEPTS FOR USE BY THE RESEARCH DEVELOPMENT STAFF, AND NATIONAL PLANNERS AND POLICYMAKERS MUST PERCEIVE MORE CLEARLY THE REALITIES OF PROGRAM DESIGN AT OPERATIONAL LEVELS.

Abstract: AUDIT REPORT OF 7/1/63-6/30/67 PERIOD OF LIVESTOCK SUBACTIVITY OF AGRIC DVLP PROJ IN LAOS. SUBACTIVITY DESIGNED TO IMPROVE PRODUCTION & MGMT OF LIVESTOCK THROUGH PROGRAMS IN SWINE, CHICKEN, & DUCK PRODUCTION, A FORAGE PROGRAM, PREVENTIVE MEDICINE, LABORATORY DVLP, AND TRAINING OF VETERINARY AGENTS. LAOTIAN GOVT'S(RLG) VETERINARY SERVICE RECEIVES USAID TECH & COMMODITY ASSISTANCE AND PARTIC TRNG SUPPORT. AUDIT CONDUCTED TO DETERMINE WHETHER AID FUNDS ADEQUATELY CONTROLLED, COMMODITIES PROPERLY UTILIZED, & PROJ GOALS IMPLEMENTED. AUDITORS REVIEWED CORRESPONDENCE, FINANCIAL & PROGRESS REPORTS, COMMODITY RECORDS, & RLG VETERINARY SERVICE ACTIVITIES. AUDIT REVEALED THAT NEITHER USAID AGRIC DIVISION (AGR) NOR THE RLG VETERINARYSERVICE(VS) ARE MAINTAINING ADEQUATE RECORDS FOR CONTROL OF VACCINES AND FOR EVALUATING THEIR UTILIZATION & EFFECTIVENESS. VS CENTRAL OFFICE AND FIELD OFFICE REPORTS SHOWED WIDE DISCREPANCIES. SOME VACCINES BEING USED AFTER EXPIRATION DATES. AUDITORS DIRECT AGR TO ESTABLISH RECORD OF VACCINES ISSUED TO VS AND TO ASSIST VS ESTABLISH UTILIZATION RECORD-KEEPING AND REPORTING SYSTEM. AGR RESPONDS TO AUDITORS' RECOMMENDATION THAT LIKELIHOOD OF ESTABLISHMENT OF NEW SYSTEM IS QUESTIONABLE DUE TO STRAINED RELATIONS WILL VS AND EXPECTED PHASING-OUT OF PROGRAM. FARMERS ARE NOT BEING CHARGED FOR VACCINATIONS AS PLANNED; AUDITORS RECOMMEND IMPLEMENTATION OF CHARGING SYSTEM. VS PROPERTY RECORDS FOUND NOT TO SHOW SERIAL NUMBERS OR THE SOURCE OF FUNDING; A PHYSICAL OBSERVATION OF ITEMS REVEALED THAT 65% DID NOT HAVE AID EMBLEMS. AUDITORS RECOMMEND THAT AGR ENSURE MAINTENANCE OF COMPLETE AND ACCURATE VS PROPERTY RECORDS,AND THAT AID EMBLEMS BE AFFIXED. INVESTIGATION REVEALED AID-FINANCED REFRIGERATORS IN THE HOMES OF THE VS DIRECTOR AND FORMER CO-DIRECTOR,TWO MISSING JEEPS,VS STOCKPILING OF USAID-ISSUED GASOLINE,AND EXPENDITURES OF 1,752,130 KIP OF COUNTERPART FUNDS FOR UNAUTHORIZED PURPOSES AND 10,097,478 KIP FOR QUESTIONABLE PURPOSES. AUDITORS REQUEST INVESTIGATIONS AND DETERMINATION IF REFUND CLAIMS IN ORDER. PARTICIPANT TRAINEES ALL FOUND TO BE WORKING IN AREAS FOR WHICH THEY HAD BEEN TRAINED.

Abstract: CONSULTANT'S REPORT ON THE ADMINISTRATIVE ACCOMPLISHMENTS AND FUTURE PLANS FOR THE BRAZILIAN EATEP  (ELEMENTARY EDUCATION PLANNING TEAM) PROJECT AS OF 3/20/68.PROJECT WAS INTENDED TO UPGRADE BRAZILIAN ELEMENTARY AND BASIC EDUCATION BY RESEARCHING PROBLEM AREAS IN EDUCATION AND ASSISTING STATES WITH THE DEVELOPMENT AND IMPLEMENTATION OF CORRECTIVE PLANS. THIS REPORT WAS PREPARED BY AN ONSITE MEMBER OF EATEP FROM THE STATE UNIVERSITY OF NEW YORK  (SUNY). ACCOMPLISHMENTS TO DATE INCLUDED A REORGANIZATION OF THE TEAM AND THE COMPLETION OF THE DOCUMENTATION ALLOWING FOR AN EXTENSION OF THE SUNY CONTRACT & A GO-AHEAD ON EATEP PLANS. IN THE FUTURE,EATEP WILL ASSIST THE STATES OF ESPIRITO SANTO AND PERNAMBUCO WITH THE ESTABLISHMENT,ON A PILOT BASIS,OF THE EATEP MODEL PLAN FOR REDUCING DROPOUT AND REPETITION. A SEMINAR WILL BE HELD FOR MEMBERS OF THE PERNAMBUCO AND ESPIRITC SANTO PLANNING COMMITTEES AND EATEP TO DEVELOP SPECIFIC ACTION PROGRAMS. THE STATE OF ESPIRITO SANTO WILL BE ASSISTED WITH CONTINUING AND EXPANDING A RECENTLY-INSTITUTED PERMANENT RECORD CARD SYSTEM. THE DATA FROM THIS SYSTEM WILL BE ANALYZED TO DEVELOP INFORMATION RELATING TO DROPOUT AND REPETITION RATES. A SIMILAR SYSTEM MAY BE INSTALLED IN PERNAMBUCO. INFORMATION ABOUT THE ABOVE PILOT PROJECTS WILL BE DISSEMINATED TO OTHER BRAZILIAN STATES VIA A SERIES OF SEMINARS. PUBLICATIONS ON THE EATEP MODEL PLAN EXIST AND OTHERS WILL BE DEVELOPED RELATING TO PROBLEM ANALYSIS IN THE FIELDS OF CURRICULUM,SUPERVISION,ADMINISTRATION,AND TEACHER EDUCATION. THE FINAL PENDING RESPONSIBILITY OF EATEP WILL BE TO PROVIDE ASSISTANCE WITH THE NATIONAL TEXTBOOK PROGARAM, FOCUSSING ON PROBLEMS OF TEXTBOOK UTILIZATION AND THE DEVELOPMENT OF BEGINNING READING MATERIALS.

Abstract: AUDIT REPORT COVERS 7/1/63-9/30/67 PERIOD FOR AUDIT ON LAOTIAN VILLAGE HEALTH PROGRAM SUBACTIVITY OF 1963-1975 PUBLIC HEALTH DVLP PROJECT. SUBACTIVITY FOCUSES ON MEETING THE IMMEDIATE & MINIMUM HEALTH NEEDS OF THE VILLAGES TO WHICH THE LAOTIAN GOVT (RLG) AND USAID HAVE ACCESS. PROGRAM CONTAINS 210 MEDICAL FACILITIES OPERATED BY 392 LOCALLY-TRAINED MEDICS & NURSES UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF USAID'S PUBLIC HEALTH DIVISION (PHD) IN CONSULTATION WITH THE RLG MINISTRY OF PUBLIC HEALTH. AUDIT CONDUCTED TO DETERMINE WHETER AID FUNDS ADEQUATELY CONTROLLED, PROGRAM OBJECTIVES IMPLEMENTED,AND COMMODITIES EFFECTIVELY UTILIZED. AUDITORS REVIEWED FINANCIAL RECORDS,CORRESPONDENCE,AND PROGRESS REPORTS; SELECTIVELY TESTED COMMODITYRECORDS; AND MADE END-USE OBSERVATIONS OF SELECTED COMMODITIES AT PROJECT SITES. IN THE 4 YEARS SINCE INCEPTION OF THE VILLAGE HEALTH PROJ,DOLLAR OBLIGATIONS HAVE TOTALED $3.9 MILLION;ACCRUED EXPENDITURES $3.7 MILLION. COUNTERPART OBLIGATIONS TOTALED K124.5 MILLION;EXPENDITURES K116.3 MILLION. 73% OF THE DOLLAR EXPENDITURES HAVE BEEN FOR COMMODITIES,PRIMARILYPHARMACEUTICALS AND MEDICAL SUPPLIES. AUDITORS FOUND THAT THERE HAD NOT BEEN COMPLETE PHYSICAL INVENTORY OF MEDICAL SUPPLIES & EQUIPMENT AT VIENTIANE PHD MEDICAL WAREHOUSE FOR 14 MONTHS AND THAT BASED ON 10% SAMPLE,SOME 46% OF STOCK RECORD CARD BALANCES DID NOT AGREE WITH QUANTITIES ACTUALLY ON HAND. PHD PROMISED TO CONDUCT A WALL-TO-WALL INVENTORY TO ESTABLISH ACCURATE ACCOUNTABILITY RECORDS. AUDITORS REVEW THEIR RECOMMENDATION THAT SUCH AN INVENTORY BE COMPLETED AND REQUEST A SUMMARY REPORT OF THE INVENTORY UPON COMPLETION. SUPPLY MGMT PROCEDURES WERE FOUND TO BE GENERALLY ADEQUATE WITH THE EXCEPTION OF THE PAKSE WAREHOUSE FOR WHICH THE AUDITOR PROPOSED SOME PROCEDURAL REVISIONS. OBSERVATION REVEALED THAT MANY NON-EXPENDABLE PROPERTY MATERIALS NOT MARKED WITH AID EMBLEMS AS REQUIRED. AUDITORS RECOMMEND THAT PHD MONITOR EXISTING AND FUTURE SUPPLIES,AFFIX EMBLEMS WHERE MISSING,AND REPORT MARKING VIOLATIONS BY SUPPLIERS.
Ancilary Data: Evaluation period: 1 Jul 1963-30 Sep 1967

Abstract: EVALUATES SEMINAR ON THE HISTORY, PHILOSOPHY, OPERATION AND LONG RANGE PLANS OF THE NATIONAL WATER LOAN FUND, FOR THE PURPOSE OF ORIENTING AND UPDATING FEDERAL AND STATE PARTICIPANTS IN THIS PROGRAM DURING THE WEEK OF 1/27/69. SEMINAR WAS ATTENDED BY REPRESENTATIVES OF 7 STATES. THESE AUTHORITIES DISCUSSED AND EVALUATED THE NATIONAL AND STATE PLANS FOR FINANCING WATER SERVICES. IN ONE SESSION,MAYORS FROM CITIES THAT OBTAINED LOANS FROM THE FUND IN 1966, EXPLAINED THE PROCEDURES THEY USED. IN OTHER SESSIONS,STATE AND FEDERAL REPRESENTATIVES EXPLAINED THEIR PROGRAMS AND PROBLEMS. THE SEMINAR WAS JUDGED VALUABLE AS A MEANS FOR CLARIFYING MISUNDERSTANDINGS,EXCHANGING IDEAS, AND FOR RECOMMENDING MODIFICATIONS AND IMPROVEMENTS IN NATIONAL WATER POLICY. AS A RESULT, IT WAS RECOMMENDED THAT A MEETING OF THIS TYPE BE HELD PERIODICALLY, POSSIBLY ON AN ANNUAL OR SEMI-ANNUAL BASIS. OTHER RECOMMENDATIONS INCLUDE: 1) THE IMMEDIATE INSTALLATION OF THE NATIONAL SANITATION COUNCIL AND ITS DIRECTORS SO THAT IT MAY ESTABLISH GUIDELINES FOR THE ACTIONS OF MUNICIPAL, STATE AND FEDERAL AGENCIES IN THE FINANCING OF WATER SERVICES; 2) PREPARATION OF TECHNICAL SANITATION STANDARDS BY THE SUPERINTENDENCY OF THE SANITATION FINANCING SYSTEM FOR CONSIDERATION BY THE NATIONAL SANITARY ENGINEERING CONGRESS; 3) DEFINITION OF THE RELATIONSHIPS BETWEEN THE FEDERAL AND STATE WATER SUPPLY FINANCING AGENCIES AND; THAT THE MINISTER OF THE INTERIOR BE INFORMED OF THE RELIANCE PLACED ON HIM BY THE SEMINAR PARTICIPANTS FOR THE POSITIVE ACTION TO BE TAKEN BY THE MINISTER AND THE MINISTRY TOWARD FINDING A SOLUTION FOR THE SANITATION PROBLEMS, ESPECIALLY THROUGH THE FORMULATION OF A NATIONAL POLICY, THE INSTALLATION OF COSANE, AND THE INTER-GOVERNMENTAL COORDINATION NECESSARY FOR THE HARMONIZATION OF THE FEDERAL AGENCIES IN THIS SECTOR.

Abstract: US TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE INCREASES VEGETABLE PRODUCTION ON IRRIGATED AND UNIRRIGATED LAND. CROP ROTATION ADJUSTED TO SUPPLY HIGHEST QUALITY VEGETABLES DURING OFF-SEASONS WHEN PRICES ARE HIGH. KEY AGRICULTURAL RESEARCH PERSONNEL PARTICIPATE IN DEVELOMENT OF QUALITY STANDARDS, GRADING AND PACKING PROCEDURES, AND SOUND EXPORT PLANNING. ACTIVITIES INCLUDE IMPROVED FERTILIZER USE; PEST AND DISEASE CONTROL; WEED CONTROL; IMPROVED SEED BED PREPARATION; IMPROVED SOIL MOISTURE MANAGEMENT, EITHER IRRIGATION WATER OR RAINFALL; AND OFF-SEASON VEGETABLE PRODUCTION USING PLASTIC COVERING AND OTHER AIDS.

Abstract: SATURATION PROGRAMS WITH EXTENSION METHOD TRAINING AND DEMONSTRATION IN AT LEAST 1 COMMUNITY IN EACH OF UGANDA'S 106 COUNTIES. A TOTAL OF 6 TECHNICIANS WILL HELP ESTABLISH PROGRAMS, TRAIN EXTENSION STAFF AT WORKSHOPS AND CONFERENCES. THE PROJECT WILL BE CARRID OUT THROUGH RESULT DEMONSTRATIONS (I.E., FERTILIZERS VS NO FERTILIZERS) AND METHOD DEMONSTRATIONS, INCLUDING SKILLS IN PLANTING, CHEMICAL WEED CONTROL, ETC. IN ADDITION PROJECT INCLUDES TRAINING 5 TO 10 PARTICIPANTS IN EXTENSION SUPERVISION AND METHODS FOR NATL AND REGIONAL EXTENSION SUPERVISION POSITIONS TO REPLACE AID ADVISORS; TRAINING 5 TO 10 EXTENSION SUBJECT MATTER SPECIALISTS AND 15 PRINCIPALS OF DISTRICT FARM INSTITUTE. TOTAL US $2235000.

COMPONENTS INCLUDE: 1) INCREASED USE OF FERTILIZER 2) INTRODUCTION AND DEVELOPMENT OF HIGH YIELDING VARIETIES, ESPECIALLY DWARF MEXICAN WHEAT 3) EXPANSION OF PRODUCTION AND USE OF HIGH QUALITY SEED 4) TRAINING OF MOROCCAN WHEAT SCIENTISTS, EXTENSION TECHNICIANS AND EXTENSION AGENTS 5) TRAINING OF FARMERS THROUGH AN AGRICULTURAL EXTENSION PROGRAM AND 6) EXPANSION OF THE AGRICULTURAL CREDIT PROGRAM TO PROVIDE CREDIT TO FARMERS WHO CAN EFFECTIVELY USE FERTILIZER AND HIGH QUALITY SEED AND FOLLOW THE REQUIRED FARM PRACTICES.

Abstract: UNDER PASA BETWEEN USAID & US CUSTOMS BUREAU, ADVISORS ASSIST ETHIOPIAN CUSTOMS DEPARTMENT TO IMPROVE EFFICIENCY OF MERCHANDISE CONTROL, ENTRY EXAMINATION, VALUATION, & CLASSIFICATION; IMPROVE PREVENTION OF SMUGGLING; INCREASE IMPORT-RELATED REVENUE COLLECTIONS WHILE LOWERING RELATED ADMIN COSTS AND UPGRADING HEADQUARTERS STAFF. ADVISORS ASSIST OPERATIONS & MGMT STAFF OF ECD TO INSTALL IMPROVED MANIFEST CONTROL PROCEDURES; DEVELOP UNIFORM ENTRY PROCESSING SYSTEM; IMPROVE RAILROAD CUSTOMS AND RELATED WAREHOUSING OPERATIONS. RELATED ACTIVITIES INCLUDE THE ESTABLISHMENT OF A NATL CUSTOMS ACADEMY, TRANSLATION & ADOPTION OF BRUSSELS TARIFF NOMENCLATURE, & STRENGTHENING OF CUSTOMS ENFORCEMENT BRANCH. ADVISORS CONDUCT IN-SERVICE TRAINING IN CLASSIFICATION, VALUATION, & MERCHANDISE CONTROL AND ESTABLISH PILOT PROGRAMS TO DEMONSTRATE IMPROVED CUSTOMS PROCEDURES. USAID SUPPORTS 3RD COUNTRY TRAINING OF 15 SENIOR OFFICIALS AND US TRAINING OF 6 OTHERS.
