Abstract: CONTRACT FUNDS ARE PROVIDED TO THE AMERICAN LIBRARY ASSOCIATION (ALA) TO ESTABLISH A CENTRAL STAFF OF PROFESSIONAL AND TECHNICAL EXPERTS TO ASSIST AID IN IMPROVING AND EXPANDING ITS PROGRAM OF OVERSEAS LIBRARY DEVELOPMENT. ALA WILL ESTABLISH IN WASHINGTON A COORDINATION-LIAISON STAFF, COMPOSED OF PERSONNEL FROM ITS INTERNATIONAL RELATIONS OFFICE (ILO) - WHICH WILL BE EXPANDED - TO ASSIST AID'S REGIONAL BUREAUS AND SELECTED USAID'S IN DEVELOPING A PLANNED APPROACH TO OVERSEAS LIBRARY DEVELOPMENT. SERVICES AND EXPERTISE WILL BE PROVIDED ON A TASK ORDER BASIS, IN FULFILLMENT OF REQUESTS FROM THE BUREAUS, USAID'S, OR AID/W. SPECIFIC AREAS OF SERVICE INCLUDE THE FOLLOWING: (1) PRELIMINARY GUIDELINES FOR MISSIONS AND US ENTITIES DEALING WITH THE PROGRAM (INCLUDING THE ILO STAFF) WILL BE PREPARED AND DISTRIBUTED. (2) FRAMEWORKS WILL BE ESTABLISHED FOR INDIVIDUAL MISSION ACTIVITIES IN THE FORM OF SURVEYS AND PROJECT DESIGNS IN SHELF ENRICHMENT, IMPROVED LAYOUT, AND TRAINING. (3) TECHNICAL BACKSTOPPING WILL BE PROVIDED TO MISSION OPERATIONAL ACTIVITIES THROUGH TECHNICAL APPRAISAL AND INTRODUCTION OF IMPROVED OVERSEAS LIBRARY PRACTICE; SEMINARS/TRAINING SESSIONS ON SOUND PRACTICE; AND PLACEMENT OF OVERSEAS PARTICIPANTS IN APPROPRIATE US LOCATIONS. IN ADDITION, THERE WILL BE DEVELOPED AND MAINTAINED SPECIALIZED ROSTERS OF US EXPERTS, CONSULTANTS, SEMINAR LEADERS, AND FOCI FOR SPECIALIZED US TRAINING (SHORT, MEDIUM-TERM, AND DEGREE). ARRANGEMENT WILL BE MADE FOR THE SERVICES OF OTHER ORGANIZATIONS OR INSTITUTIONS (E.G., SELECTED UNIVERSITIES, FOUNDATIONS, THE US BOOK EXCHANGE)AS REQUIRED. (4) LIBRARY DEVELOPMENT ACTIVITIES OF DONOR ENTITIES (PUBLIC AND PRIVATE; US, OTHER GOVERNMENT, AND MULTILATERAL) WILL BE APPRAISED AND DONORS WILL BE KEPT INFORMED OF ACTUAL OR PLANNED AID LIBRARY DEVELOPMENT ACTIVITIES. TO THIS END, A NEWSLETTER WILL BE PUBLISHED PERIODICALLY ON OVERSEAS LIBRARY DEVELOPMENT, INDICATING SUCCESSES AND FAILURES AND THE REASONS THEREOF, AND PROVIDING TECHNICAL INFORMATION ON SOUND AND IMPROVED PRACTICE. OP REVISION #1 OF 4/12/71 EXTENDS PROJECT THROUGH FY 1972 IN ORDER TO ALLOW THE OFFICE OF EDUCATION AND HUMAN RESOURCES OF THE TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE BUREAU TO UNDERTAKE, WITH CONTRACTOR'S HELP, A STUDY OF THE ROLE OF LIBRARIES IN ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT; AND TO ALLOW THE CONTRACTOR TO PREPARE AN EXPANDED FINAL REPORT SPECIFYING PROBLEMS ENCOUNTERED, ASSESSING RESULTS, AND RECOMMENDING FUTURE ACTION.

Abstract: A systematic study was made of the calanoid copepods in seven plankton samples collected between Lattitude 30 Degrees 00 Minutes North and Latttitude 42 Degress 20 Minutes North along Longitude 155 Degrees West. Sixty-four species belonging to 17 families are recorded. Measurements, descriptions. and illustrations are given for most of the species. Two species, Euchirella unispina and Euchaeta wrighti, are described as new, and the hitherto unknown female of Celltropages elegalls Giesbrecht is described for the first time. Calocalannus tennis Farran is reported for the first time from the Pacific Ocean. (Author abstract, modified)

Abstract: Project to strengthen the institutional and service capacity of Dominican cooperatives.  The project, which will be implemented by the Government of the Dominican Republic's Instituto de Desarrollo y Credito Cooperativo (IDECOOP), will have three main components:  training and scholarships; a credit fund; and TA. Training courses will reach 4,000 persons per year.  The project will also fund materials, equipment, and a library for cooperative promoters; educational radio programs on cooperatives; and scholarships for promoters and managers for on-the-job training in Puerto Rico with agricultural and supermarket cooperatives. The credit fund will provide loans for cooperative production projects.  Priority will be given to agricultural loans for projects which are in keeping with the government's agricultural priorities. The TA component will assist IDECOOP in developing an effective planning and programming unit.  This component will provide four long-term advisors, in the areas of agricultural marketing, consumer operations, credit unions, and programming and planning.

Abstract: This semi-annual report presents descriptive statistical findings from exit interviews conducted by the contractor, American University's Development Education and Training Research Institute (DETRI), with 895 academic and special participants and 342 observation training team members between July 1967 and February 1968.  It includes an overview of these participants' perceptions of and reactions to their entire training program. Recommendations are made in the areas of training design, pre-departure preparation, and support services.  (Author abstract, modified)

Abstract: Project to conduct research which may lead to development of a once-a-month oral contraceptive.  The project proposes to:  isolate and chemically characterize a uterine substance (s) which causes regression of the corpus luteum in sheep; test the substance and its most active fractions in vitro and in vivo, respectively; and identify optimal means for collecting it from the sheep uterus.  The Worchester Foundation for Experimental Biology will implement the project.

Abstract: GRANT, TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE, PARTICIPANT TRAINING AND COMMODITIES PROVIDED TO INDONESIA TO ALLEVIATE SHORTAGE OF TEXTBOOKS AND WRITTEN MATERIALS IN HIGHER EDUCATION SYSTEM AND TO INCREASE CAPACITY TO DEVELOP AND PRODUCE BOOKS INDIGENOUSLY. AID WILL ASSIST THE NATIONAL ACADEMY OF SCIENCE (NAS) BOOK PROGRAM WHICH SPONSORS INDONESIAN THE INDONESIAN ACADEMY OF SCIENCE (LIPI) NATIONAL SCIENTIFIC DOCUMENTATION CENTER, PROJECT WILL SUPPLY SCIENTIFIC BOOKS TO DOCUMENTATION CENTER TO BE DISBURSED TO RESEARCH INSTITUTIONS. REPRODUCTION AND BINDING EQUIPMENT IS ALSO PROVIDED. 3-PRONGED SHELF-ENRICHMENT PROGRAM IS INSTITUTED: 1)NATIONAL DEVELOPMENT REFERENCE LIBRARIES (540 PRE-SELECTED TITLES) ARE PROVIDED TO GOVT PLANNING STAFFS, MINISTRIES AND AGENCIES INVOLVED IN ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT; 2)TEXTBOOK DEPOSITORY REFERENCE LIBRARIES ARE PROVIDED TO 4 TEACHER COLLEGES; 3)SPECIAL ALLOCATIONS OF REFERENCE BOOKS ARE PROVIDED TO 8 PEMBINA UNIVERSITIES. TOTAL PROGRAM INVOLVES 30,000 VOLUMES, AND IS ADMINISTERED JOINTLY BY DEPT OF HIGHER EDUCATION AND NATL SCIENTIFIC DOCUMENTATION CENTER. TEXTBOOK WRITING CENTER IS PLANNED TO TRAIN PERSONNEL FROM UNIVERSITIES, MOE AND BASIC EDUCATION SYSTEM. REFERENCE BOOKS, EQUIPMENT AND US PARTICIPANT TRAINING WILL ALSO BE INCLUDED. KEY US UNIVERSITY TEXTS WILL BE TRANSLATED AND PRINTED. AID WILL SUPPLY PAPER TO FORD FOUNDATION'S LANGUAGE MATERIALS DEVELOPMENT PROJECT, ENABLING IT TO PROVIDE ENGLISH TEACHING MATERIALS THROUGHOUT SECONDARY LEVEL. ASSISTANCE IN THE LIBRARY FIELD WILL FOCUS ON UPGRADING LIBRARY SCHOOL, UNIVERSITY OF INDONESIA, AND PROVIDING INCENTIVES TO ENTERING THE LIBRARY PROFESSION. BOTH LONG AND SHORT-TERM FELLOWSHIPS WILL BE PROVIDED. SHORT-TERM EXPERT WILL ASSIST IN CURRICULUM DEVELOPMENT AND DESIGN OF MOE FELLOWSHIP PROGRAM. BIBLIOGRAPHIC MATERIALS WILL BE PROVIDED TO PEMBINA UNIVERSITIES EMPLOYING A FULL-TIME LIBRARIAN. PROJECT ACTIVITIES WILL CONTAIN A PHASE-OUT ELEMENT WITH GOI GRADUALLY ASSUMING THE COSTS.

Abstract: IDAAN CONTROLS WATER & SEWAGE FUNCTIONS NATION-WIDE, REQUESTED WATER SUPPLY SYSTEM TO PROVIDE 56 MILLION GALLONS A DAY TO PANAMA CITY. SUPPLY FROM MADDEN LAKE TO AUGMENT & PARTLY REPLACE EXISTING SERVICE OF PANAMA CANAL COMPANY (PCC) WATER SYSTEM FROM MIRAFLORES LAKE. INITIAL SYSTEM, WHEN OPERATED WITH PCC SUPPLY, EXPECTED TO MEET DEMAND OF PANAMA CITY TO 1990 & ULTIMATELY MEET NEEDS FOR 2020. INCLUDED ARE SECTIONS ON ENGINEERING ANALYSIS INCLUDING MAINTENANCE, ECONOMIC ANALYSIS INCLUDING TRENDS DURING ALLIANCE PERIOD, RELATION OF PROJECT TO US ASSISTANCE STRATEGY, ANTICIPATED WATER DEMAND & ASPECTS OF WATER SUPPLY; & FINANCIAL ANALYSIS. ORIGINAL CAP: 4-30-68; REVISION OF 4-1-71 REQUESTS ADDITIONAL $5 MILLION.

Abstract: AID PROVIDES SIX LIVESTOCK AND PLANT SPECIALISTS ON A SALARY TOPPING BASIS TO FILL VACANT POSITIONS WITHIN EAST AFRICAN AGRICULTURE AND FOREST RESEARCH ORGANIZATION (EAAFRO). EAAFRO PERFORMS RESEARCH IN AGRICULTURE AND FORESTRY AIMED AT SOLVING PROBLEMS COMMON TO AT LEAST TWO MEMBER NATIONS. SPECIALISTS' FIELDS ARE: ANIMAL NUTRITION, RANGE ECOLOGY, NEMATOLOGY, PLANT PATHOLOGY, SOIL PHYSICS, SPECTROCHEMISTRY. AID PROVIDES ADVANCED DEGREE LEVEL PARTICIPANT TRAINING FOR SIX EAAFRO MEMBERS IN THE SIX AFOREMENTIONED FIELDS. TRAINEES RETURN TO EAST AFRICA FOR FURTHER TRAINING WITH SIX AID SPECIALISTS BEFORE REPLACING THEM.

Abstract: GRANT TO INDONESIA'S MINISTRY OF HEALTH TO SUPPORT ITS NATIONAL FAMILY PLANNING PROGRAM. FAMILY PLANNING INFORMATION AND SERVICES WILL BE INTRODUCED INTO THE EXISTING HEALTH CLINIC SYSTEM, INCLUDING MATERNAL AND CHILD HEALTH CLINICS AND HOSPITALS. USAID WILL PROVIDE TEMPORY DUTY FAMILY PLANNING CONSULTANTS, DIRECT-HIRE POPULATION ADVISORS, SHORT AND LONG-TERM PARTICIPANT TRAINING (PRIMARILY IN THE US) FOR HIGH LEVEL PLANNERS, AND COMMODITIES (CONTRACEPTIVES, MEDICAL INSTRUMENTS, VEHICLES, AND A-V EQUIPMENT). PROGRAM WILL FOCUS PRIMARILY ON JAVA, MADURA, AND BALI. MAXIMUM OPERATIONAL AUTHORITY WILL REST WITH THE PROVINCIAL HEALTH SERVICE DIRECTORS. THE INDONESIAN PLANNED PARENTHOOD ASSOCIATION (IPPA) WILL TRAIN FAMILY PLANNING WORKERS AT 6 PROVINCIAL TRAINING CENTERS AND ONE NATIONAL CENTER. USAID IS ONE OF MORE THAN 20 DONORS TO THE NATIONAL FAMILY PLANNING PROGRAM. OTHER MAJOR DONORS INCLUDE A COMBINED IDA/UNFPA PACKAGE, INTERNATIONAL PLANNED PARENTHOOD FEDERATION, FORD FOUNDATION, PATHFINDER FUND, AND POPULATION COUNCIL. SOME AID/W FUNDS ARE CHANNELLED THROUGH THESE DONORS. USAID WILL FOCUS ON THE CLINICAL/MEDICAL ASPECTS OF THE NATIONAL PROGRAM, PRIMARILY WORKING WITH THE DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND THE NATIONAL FAMILY PLANNING COORDINATING BOARD (BKKBN). PROP 5-13-74 EXPANDS PROGRAM INTO THE PRIVATE SECTOR TO TAKE ADVANTAGE OF COMMERCIAL DISTRIBUTION SYSTEMS FOR ORAL CONTRACEPTIVES AND CONDOMS. BY GOI FY 76/77, 2,800 FAMILY PLANNING CLINICS WILL BE OPERATING WITHIN EXISTING HEALTH CENTERS IN JAVA AND BALI; 415 WILL BE OPENED IN THE OUTER ISLANDS. 30 - 36% OF FERTILE WOMEN WILL BE PRACTICING CONTRACEPTION.

Abstract: Project to help Turkey's four public economic/commercial graduate academies, in conjunction with Michigan State University (MSU), improve their graduate programs in business administration (BA). The project will focus on curricula revision and expansion and promoting specialization, faculty training, and enhancing research capability and academic/business community cooperation. To provide each academy with the nucelus of a BA department, current curricula will be revised and/or expanded to include courses in managerial accounting and economics, marketing and market research, management and administration, business finance, and quantitative methods.  Basic BA texts will be translated into Turkish and new and modern texts written in collaboration with Turkish faculty, case materials will be developed and the case method introduced into classroom teaching, and electives developed in the third and fourth years to allow greater concentration in areas of specialization. Academy faculty will be strengthened through U.S. and in-country training.  Some 110 junior faculty members will receive 220 person-years of training in M.B.A. programs at MSU, and 30 professors and docents will receive 15 person-years of training at MSU.  In addition, in-country seminars will be held for academy faculty and for doctoral candidates and an annual summer institute will be conducted for faculty preparing for U.S. study. Academy research capabilities will be enhanced by a program in research methodology, graduate student research projects, the publication of U.S.-Turkish research, and the acquisition of 200 library volumes annually. Cooperation between the academic and business communities will be enhanced through joint meetings to discuss businesses' needs for quality academy graduates and by the creation of managerial development programs for aspiring managers. Finally, academy procedures will be made more efficient (e.g., by reducing faculty-student ratio and the time spent on examinations and by adopting the semester system), and joint planning groups will be established at each academy to design long-range institutional development plans.

Abstract: Reports on USAID assistance to the Ministry of Animal and Forest Resources (MAFR) from 7/1/60-3/31/68 to improve livestock and poultry production in Northern Nigeria.  A total of 19 direct-hire technicians, 4 contract technicians, and 12 TDY personnel were provided.  USAID commodities totaled $1.5 million. Six range areas were selected as range management demonstration units.  However, resources were spread too thinly, and the trng situation was very poor.  Only the Katsuna unit has made a start on mgmt with fire and trespass control, identification of animals, and control of grazing.  No studies have yet been done to determine actual range conditions, trends or present and future carrying capacities.  The goal of 1000 breeding cows at the Bornu Ranch was not met.  Obtaining high quality animals was difficult; and additional stock water corrals and subdivisional fencing are needed. Day-to-day problems were so numerous and insoluble that no pattern of organized dvlp & mgmt was established. At the Manchock Ranch, site the cattle fattening demonstration, 12 of 20 planned pastures were fenced and 80% of the buildings were completed. The cold meat market at Kaduna operated satisfactorily.  Poultry production units were completed at Kaduna and Jos with a combined hatching capacity of 350,000 chicks annually. A third PPU is planned. With the current price of eggs at 70-84[ a dozen, no large demand exists, however.  Although a poultry diagnostic lab was equipped and 2 US advisors provided, only limited use was made of them.  In addition to assistance to the Livestock Services Trng Center (dorms and classrooms for 60 students), 25 Nigerians received US training in livestock dvlp. 30 other participants were sent to the US for degree trng. Major problems involved delays in construction of proj facilities by the Ministry of Public Works and lack of trained mechanics, operators and storekeepers needed for the US machinery supplied under the proj. Evaluator recommends consideration of whether future emphasis should be placed upon purely technical assistance and trng rather than on the building of infrastructures.
Ancilary Data: Evaluation period: 1 JUL 1960-31 MAR 1968

Abstract: Project to strengthen the capacity of the School of Medicine at Chiengmai University in Thailand.  As project implementor, the University of Illinois will help the Chiengmai Medical School (CMS): (1) develop a medical education program that trains physicians to provide comprehensive health care; (2) adapt its curriculum to the Thai environment; (3) establish a graduate education program in the basic and clinical science departments and form a pool of qualified academic physicians and medical scientists; (4) establish residency training programs; (5) develop continuing education programs for CMS faculty; (6) support U.S. training opportunities and work to assign returning participants to the CSM faculty; (7) develop appropriate administrative and budgetary systems; (8) foster cooperative relationships between CMS faculty and other Chiengmai University teachers; and (9) promote the concepts of preventive medicine and community health in CMS's curriculum, research, and training.

Abstract: LOAN TO GOVERNMENT OF BRAZIL FINANCES MALARIA ERADICATION PROGRAM DURING PERIOD CY69-71. LOAN ALSO CONTINUES SERVICES OF 5 MALARIA TECHNICIANS UNDER PASA WITH US PUBLIC HEALTH SERVICE. RECIPIENT OF US GOODS AND SERVICES IS MALARIA ERADICATION CAMPAIGN (CEM), THE AGENCY WITHIN THE MINISTRY OF HEALTH(MOH) WITH RESPONSIBILITY FOR CARRYING OUT 4 STAGE ERADICATION PROGRAM. 4 PHASE ERADICATION PROGRAM DEVISED BY WORLD HEALTH ORGANIZATION(WHO) UTILIZED TO BREAK THE MAN-MOSQUITO-MAN TRANSMISSION CYCLE. DURING PREPARATION, GEOGRAPHICAL, ENTOMOLOGICAL AND EPIDEMIOLOGICAL SURVEYS CONDUCTED AND ALL SPRAY SITES IDENTIFIED. ATTACK PHASE DEVOTED TO SPRAYING OF ALL INHABITED BUILDINGS WITH RESIDUAL INSECTICIDES, DEVELOPMENT OF CASE DETECTION SYSTEM, AND MAINTENANCE OF STRICT MALARIA SURVEILLANCE. CONSOLIDATION PHASE MARKED BY SUSPENSION OF SPRAYING AND INTENSIFICATION OF SURVEILLANCE. MAINTENANCE PHASE ACTIVITIES INCLUDE CASE DETECTION, SURVEILLANCE, AND TREATMENT ON LESS INTENSIVE BASIS THAN EARLIER PHASES. DURING LOAN DISBURSEMENT PERIOD AND ATTACK PHASE, ACTIVITIES ALREADY UNDERWAY IN ALL MALARIOUS AREAS WILL BE SUPPORTED, WITH GOAL OF SHIFTING LARGE AREAS TO CONSOLIDATION PHASE BY 1972. LOAN ADMINISTERED BY MOH TO ASSIST CEM; ADDITIONAL ASSISTANCE PROVIDED BY PAHO IN FORM OF TECHNICAL TEAMS AND ANTIMALARIAL DRUGS. PRIMARY BENEFICIARIES OF PROJECT WILL BE RURAL RESIDENTS CURRENTLY EXPOSED TO MALARIA.

Abstract: HOUSING GUARANTY PROGRAM EXTENDED TO BRAZIL'S NATIONAL HOUSING BANK (BNH) TO FINANCE HOUSING CONSTRUCTION IN URBAN AREAS. THE GUARANTY WILL ASSURE AGAINST LOSSES OF UP TO 100% OF LOAN INVESTMENTS MADE BY US INVESTORS TO BNH. THE BNH, IN TURN, WILL PROVIDE LINES OF CREDIT FOR PILOT DEMONSTRATION, LOCAL PARTICIPATION, AND MORTGAGE CREDIT INSTITUTION HOUSING PROJECTS. THE APPROVED HOUSING PROJECTS ARE: 1) 650 SEMI-DETACHED, EXPANDABLE, TWO-BEDROOM HOUSES TO BE LOCATED IN A SUBURB OF SAO PAULO; 2) 1,150 SEMI-DETACHED EXPANDABLE TWO-BEDROOM HOUSES IN A SUBURB OF RIO DO JANEIRO; 3) 776 DETACHED, TWO AND THREE-BEDROOM HOUSES TO BE LOCATED IN A PLANNED SATELLITE COMMUNITY ON THE OUTSKIRTS OF SAO PAULO; 4) 3,067 ONE AND TWO-BEDROOM DETACHED HOUSES IN VOLTA REDONDA, SITE OF THE NATIONAL STEEL COMPANY; 5) GENERAL MORTGAGE RE-LENDING BY ECONOMIA, S.A., A CREDIT INSTITUTION IN BELO HORIZONTE; AND 6) GENERAL RE-LENDING BY MINAS OESTE, S.A., ANOTHER CREDIT INSTITUTION LOCATED IN BELO HORIZONTE. THE FIRST FOUR PROJECTS, WHICH ARE IN THE LOCAL PARTICIPATION CATEGORY, ALL HAVE UNIT SALE PRICES UNDER $6,500. THE LAST TWO CREDIT INSTITUTIONS WILL CONDUCT RE-LENDING FOR HOUSES WITHIN THE $5,000 PER UNIT LIMITATION FOR THIS CATEGORY. BENEFICIARIES INCLUDE THE URBAN LOWER-MIDDLE INCOME CLASS

Abstract: HONDURAS IS PROVIDED WITH GRANT, TECH ADVISORY ASSISTANCE AND PARTICIPANT TRNG TO CONDUCT INTENSIVE PROG OF TAX ADMINISTRATION REFORM AND PERSONNEL TRNG. TECH ASSISTANCE WILL CONSIST OF 3-MAN IRS TAX TEAM AND SHORT-TERM CONSULTANTS FOR SPECIAL PROJECTS & PROBLEMS. DIRECTORATE GENERAL OF TAXATION WILL BE REORGANIZED AND EXPANDED. ALL INTERNAL TAXES INCLUDING THOSE ON ALCOHALIC BEVERAGES WILL BE INTEGRATED WITHIN THE DIRECTORATE. AUDIT DIVISION WILL IMPLEMENT IMPROVED PROCEDURES & TECHNIQUES. AUTOMATIC DATA PROCESSING (ADP) EQUIPMENT WILL BE USED TO IMPROVE PROCESSING OF RETURNS,REVENUE ACCOUNTING AND BILLING PROCEDURES. NEW ADP SYSTEM WILL PROVIDE AUTOMATIC IDENTIFICATION OF DELINQUENT TAXPAYERS & OTHER DATA FOR USE IN MANAGING REVENUE OPERATIONS. NEW DEPT OF ADMINISTRATIVE SERVICES WILL BE ESTABLISHED AND WILL BE RESPONSIBLE FOR RECRUITING PERSONNEL AND DEVELOPING INFORMATION SYST TO SERVE MANAGEMENT NEEDS. DEPT WILL ALSO OVERSEE ADOPTION OF BUDGETARY ACCOUNTING SYST. INSPECTION UNIT WILL BE CREATED FOR ROUTINE INTERNAL AUDITS AND TO INVESTIGATE ALLEGATIONS OF EMPLOYEE MISCONDUCT. IN-SERVICE TRNG PROGS WILL BE INSTITUTED AND MANUALS PREPARED TO GUIDE EMPLOYEES IN THEIR WORK. SELECTED TOP-LEVEL PERSONNEL WILL RECEIVE 3RD COUNTRY OR US PARTICIPANT TRNG, INCLUDING INTAX SEMINARS. CURRENT TAXPAYER INFORMATION & ASSISTANCE PROG WILL BE EXPANDED. TAX LAWS ARE TO BE CODIFIED AND REGULATIONS INTERPRETING SUBSTANTIVE PROVISIONS WILL BE PUBLISHED. PROCEDURES WILL BE DEVELOPED FOR SETTLING DISPUTES BETWEEN TAXPAYERS AND DIRECTORATE. HOST-COUNTRY WILL PROVIDE LOCAL OFFICE SUPPORT AND LOCAL TRANSPORTATION COSTS. OTHER DONORS, OAS AND UN, WILL ALSO PROVIDE TECHNICAL ADVISORS. PRIMARY BENEFICIARIES ARE GOH TAX EMPLOYEES. PROJECT ELEMENT WAS LATER ADDED CONSISTING OF TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE AND TRAINING TO IMPROVE CUSTOMS TAX ADMINISTRATION.

Abstract: GRANTS TO PERMIT 3 EXISTING VENEZUELAN PRIVATE ORGS TO EXPAND & STRENGTHEN THEIR POPULATN  (POP) , FAMILY PLANNG  (FP) , MEDICAL SRVCS PROGRS. THE 3 ORGS ARE THE MATERNITY & CONCEPTN HOSP  (MCH) , VENEZUELAN FP ASSOC  (VFPA) , VENEZUELAN CNTR FOR POP & FAMILY  (CEVEPOF) . MCH WILL EXPAND ITS FP CLINIC, GYNECOLOG'L SRVCS, TRNG PROGRS FOR DOCTORS, NURSES, SOCIAL WORKRS & AIDES & LAB TECHS; THERE WILL ALSO BE PARTIC TRNG IN US, 3RD CNTRIES IN THESE DISCIPLNS. A NEWLY OPERATN'L CANCER DETCTN PROGR WILL BE EXPANDED & THE MCH LIBRARY IMPRVD. TRNG & EDUC SRVCS OF THE VFPA FOR MED'L,PARAMED'L,TECH'L PERSONNEL IN FP & ALLIED FIELDS WILL BE XPNDED & SUPPORT OF SOCIAL WORK PROJS,OPERATN OF 12 FP CNTRS,5 METROPOLITN & 7 RURAL-TOGETHR SRVNG 700 WOMEN/MONTH,WILL BE CONTINUED. VFPA WILL OPEN 5 NEW URBAN CNTRS,ESTAB RURAL FP EDUC PROGRS IN NAT'L UNIVERSITIES & MED'L SCHLS. OPERATING THRU VFPA,AID WILL INCREASE SUPPORT OF MCH'S POP DIVISION TO FURTHER ITS LIMITED PROGRS. VFPA WILL RECEIVE RADIO,VISUAL AIDS,OTHER SUPPORT SRVCS & WILL CONDUCT SEMINARS,WORKSHOPS ON FP-RELATED TOPICS. CEVEPOF WILL CONDUCT FOLLOW-UP STUDIES ON 1000 WOMEN FROM FP PROGRS. STUDIES WILL BE MADE OF POSTPARTUM MOTIVATN'L ATTITUDES & OF INDUCED ABORTION PARAMETERS. A 6-MONTH STUDY ON PROCREATION & FP KNOWLEDGE,ATTITUDES,PRACTICES OF 550 INDIVIDUALS WILL BE CONDUCTED & BASED ON FINDINGS,A PILOT CLINIC ESTAB TO INSTRUCT IN MARRIAGE COUNSELING,HOME-MAKING,INDIVIDUAL COUNSELING & OTHER FAMILY NEEDS. QUARTERLY SEMINARS ON POP,FP WILL BE DESIGNED FOR UNIVERSITY STUDENTS,PROFSSRS & FOR PERSONNEL ALREADY IN FP ACTIVS. CEVEPOF WILL EVALUATE THE FP CLINIC PILOT PROJ AFTER APPROX 18-24 MONTHS & DEVELOP AN INFO PROGR TO DISSEMINATE INFO ON PROBLEMS OF POPULATION & THE FAMILY. PROP OF 4/22/70 ADDED A PARTIC TRNG ACTIVITY IN US TO DEVEL 4 EXPERTS TO HELP ESTAB A NATIONAL FAMILY POLICY. CEVEPOF WILL ASSIST IN THE PROGR BY DEVELOPING A "FAMILY TYPOLOGY" OF CLASS,REGION,LIFE,STYLE,FAMILY SIZE,AGES,SOCIAL COMMUNITY ORGANIZATN,GODPARENT RELATNSHP,IN-FAMILY CNTRLS,ECON ORG,SOCIAL MOBILITY,FAMILY ATTITUDES ON KEY SOCIAL ISSUES. THIS 3-STAGE ACTIVITY WILL RESULT IN RECOMMENDATIONS FOR A NATIONAL FAMILY PROGRAM

Abstract: 11/15/68. THERE HAVE BEEN 2 PROBLEMS IN THE IMPLEMENTATION OF THIS PROJECT. FIRST, THE POOR QUALITY OF THE ADMINISTRATIVE LEADERSHIP IN KABUL UNIVERSITY'S FACULTY OF AGRICULTURE HAS RESULTED IN POOR LOCAL BUDGETARY SUPPORT, A POORLY ORGANIZED STRUCTURE & LOW LEVEL OF POLICY IMPLMNTATN. SECOND, THE POOR QUALITY OF THE LEADERSHIP OF THE CONTRACTOR'S FIELD TEAM HAS PRODUCED LESS THAN A FULL COMPLEMENT OF STAFF AND POOR TIMELINESS OF ADVISORY ASSISTANCE. MOST PROJECT ACTIVITIES WERE PROGRESSING AS PLANNED. THE RECRUITMENT OF UNDERGRADUATES AND GRADUATES,THE TRAINING OF STAFF AT THE M.S. DEGREE LEVEL,AND THE DEVELOPMENT OF CURRICULA IN 6 AREAS HAS BEEN GOOD. ALSO,THE COMMODITY PROCUREMENT,THE CONTINUATION OF THE RESEARCH PROGRAM,AND THE PROVISION OF FACULTY SERVICES TO OTHERS HAS BEEN GOOD. THE CONSTRUCTION OF BUILDINGS WAS BEHIND SCHEDULE BECAUSE OF THE GOVERNMENT'S PROBLEMS WITH THE CONSTRUCTION CONTRACTOR. THIS DELAY HAS HAMPERED THE STORAGE OF COMMODITIES WHICH HAVE ALREADY BEEN BOUGHT AND ARE ON-SITE. THE DEVELOPMENT OF EFFECTIVE FACULTY ADMINISTRATION HAS BEEN SLOW BECAUSE OF THE FACULTY'S LACK OF ADMINISTRATIVE AND CLERICAL SKILLS. THE RECRUITMENT OF ABLE STUDENTS HAS BEEN HAMPERED BY THE POOR QUALITY OF THE HIGH SCHOOL EDUCATION AND BY THE LOW PRESTIGE AND PAY OF AGRIC EMPLOYMNT IN AFGHANISTAN. IT WAS SUGGESTED THAT AID/W SUPPLY USAID/AFGHANISTAN WITH EXISTING LITERATURE ON AFGHAN AGRICULTURE,SINCE RESEARCH WAS HAMPERED BY THE LACK OF AGRICULTURAL DATA IN AFGHANISTAN. THE AROUND-THE-CLOCK LEVELING OF LAND FOR THE RESEARCH FARM WAS AN UNUSUALLY COOPERATIVE ACTIVITY BY THE AMERICANS AND AFGHANS. ONE IMPORTANT LESSON LEARNED WAS TO FIRST ASSESS THE HOST COUNTRY'S WILLINGNESS TO RECRUIT QUALIFIED STUDENTS BEFORE INITIAING PROJECT ACTIVITIES.

Abstract: GRANT PROVIDES TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE, COMMODITIES, AND PARTICIPANT TRAINING TO THE GOVERNMENTS OF BOTSWANA, LESOTHO, MALAWI, AND SWAZILAND TO CREATE A REGIONAL TESTING RESOURCE AND TRAINING CENTER (RTRTC). RTRTC WILL DEVELOP AND IMPLEMENT A SYSTEM OF TESTS FOR SELECTION OF SECONDARY AND TECHNICAL SCHOOL STUDENTS AND ADVISE MINISTRIES AND UNIVERSITIES ON DEVELOPMENT AND USE OF TESTING WITHIN THEIR RESPECTIVE EDUCATIONAL SYSTEMS. RTRTC HEADQUARTERS WILL BE ESTABLISHED IN MALAWI IN CONJUNCTION WITH UNIVERSITY OF MALAWI, WITH A BRANCH LOCATED IN BOTSWANA. RTRTC BOARD OF DIRECTORS TO CONSIST OF MEMBER GOVTS, AFFILIATED UNIVERSITIES, AND AID ADVISORS; ADVISORS TO BE REPLACED AS 6 LOCAL EDUCATORS COMPLETE US TRAINING (2 PHD, 4 MS) IN EDUCATIONAL AND PSYCHOLOGICAL TESTING. RTRTC WILL ALSO PROVIDE INSERVICE TRAINING SEMINARS FOR 15-20 PERSONNEL ANNUALLY. ORIGINALLY CONCEIVED AS A CENTRALIZED INSTITUTION, RTRTC CONCEPT MODIFIED BY BOARD MEETING IN JUNE 1972 TO CREATE (AS REFLECTED IN PROAG 11/16/73) A SYSTEM OF NATIONAL SUB-CENTERS WHICH DETERMINE THEIR OWN PROJECTS AND PRIORITIES. MAIN CENTER CONTINUES TO PROVIDE TECHNICAL TEST DEVELOPMENT, RESEARCH, AND DATA PROCESSING SERVICES, AND MAINTAINS AN ADVISORY RELATIONSHIP WITH SUB-CENTERS. RTRTC SERVES AS A REGIONAL FORUM FOR RESEARCH AND TECHNICAL DATA AND PROVIDES BOTH FORMAL AND ON THE JOB TRAINING FOR AFRICAN EDUCATORS. PRIMARY BENEFICIARIES OF PROJECT WILL BE SECONDARY AND TECHNICAL SCHOOL CANDIDATES IN THE 4 COOPERATING COUNTRIES WHO WILL BE SELECTED AND GUIDED BY RTRTC TESTING PROGRAMS.

Abstract: TECHNICAL ADVISORY ASSISTANCE PROVIDED TO THE GOVERNMENT OF BOLIVIA TO ESTABLISH CENAFA (CENTRO LNATIONAL DE FAMILIA) ASEMI-AUTONOMOUS GOVERNMENT AGENCY CAPABLE OF CONDUCTING RESEARCH IN POPULATION DYNAMICS AND DISSEMINATING RESULTS TO DECISION MAKERS. PROVIDES BASELINE DATA FOR RESPONSIBLE PARENTHOOD PROGRAM THRU MATERNAL CHILD HEALTH DEPARTMENT WITHIN THE MINISTRY OF SOCIAL WELFARE AND PUBLIC HEALTH. PROJECT OBJECTIVES ARE TO INTEGRATE PROGRAMS IN POPULATION, FAMILY CARE AND NUTRITION INTO MATERNAL AND CHILD HEALTH PROGRAMS AND EXTEND HEALTH SERVICES TO 56% OF THE READILY ACCESSIBLE AND 15% OF THE RURAL POPULATION BY 1974. USAID EFFORTS CONCENTRATED IN DEVELOPMENT OF MINISTRY OF HEALTH'S (MOH) CAPABILITY TO EDUCATE HEALTH PERSONNEL AND ESTABLISH AN EFFECTIVE, FUNCTIONING NATIONAL ADVISORY BODY ON POPULATION POLICY AND FAMILY HEALTH MATTERS. THREE TYPES OF TARGETS: 1. SERVICE-STAFFING OF FAMILY PROTECTION DEPARTMENT WITHIN MOH SO THAT IT MAY PLAN, ESTABLISH AND ADMINISTER MATERNAL CHILD HEALTH AND FAMILY CARE SERVICES AND EXTEND SERVICES THRU MOBLE HEALTH TEAMS; 2. TRAINING-INCLUDES ESTABLISHING DEPARTMENT OF COMMUNITY MEDICINE IN 3 MEDICAL FACILITIES. WILL IDENTIFY TECHNICAL DISCIPLINES AND COURSES FOR PREPARATION OF GRADUATES TO WORK IN FIELD OF FAMILY PLANNING AND PREVENTIVE MEDICINE, AND; 3.PROVIDE INSERVICE TRAINING FOR MINISTRY MEDICAL AND PARAMEDICAL PERSONNEL THRU CONFERENCES, LECTURES, SEMINARS AND WORKSHOPS. PROJECT ESTABLISHES FAMILY PLANNING CLINICS TO DISSEMIONATE FAMILY PLANNING INFORMATION, & CONTRACEPTIVE SERVICES. PRIMARY BENEFICIARIES OF PROJECT ARE MOTHERS AND CHILDREN RECEIVING MATERNAL CHILD HEALTH AND FAMILY PLANNING SERVICES. SECONDARY BENEFICIARIES ARE ADMNISTRATORS, PHYSICIANS, PARAMEDICAL PERSONNEL TRAINED TO DELIVER FAMILY PLANNING AND PREVENTIVE MEDICAL SERVICES.

Document Title: Turkey's financial structure : money, banking, policy, and capital markets

Abstract: TECH ASSIST & COMMODITIES ARE PROVIDED TO THE EAST AFR AGRI & FORESTRY RESEARCH ORG (EAAFRO), A SUBSIDARY OF THE EAST AFR COMMUNITY, TO IMPLEMENT A VARIETAL RESEARCH PROG TO INCREASE FOOD PRODUCTION IN EASTERN & SOUTHERN AFR. THIS PROJ IS A BREAK-AWAY FROM AN EARLIER WHO-FUNDED AFR-WIDE MAJOR CEREALS RESEARCH PROJ AND WILL EMPHASIZE DEVLPMNT & TESTING OF IMPROVED GENETIC VARIETIES OF CEREALS & LEGUMES SPECIFICALLY SUITED TO CLIMATIC & ECOLOGICAL CONDITIONS OF EASTERN-SOUTHERN AFR. PROJ WILL CONTINUE RESEARCH ON HIGH-YEILDING VARIETIES OF MAIZE,MILLET,SORGHUM & SOYBEANS & OTHER LEGUMES. COMPLEMENTARY PACKAGE OF IMPROVED CROP HUSBANDRY,FERTILIZATION,AND DISEASE & PEST CONTROL PRACTICES WILL ALSO BE DEVLPED. IN ADDITION,EAAFRO WILL EXPAND ITS FIELD TESTING OF THE NEWLY DEVLPED PLANT VARIETIES. PLANTING MATERIALS & TECH ASSIST WILL BE PROVIDED TO PARTICIPATING COUNTRIES FOR TRIAL CULTIVATIONS TO IDENTIFY THOSE VARIETIES BEST-ADAPTED TO LOCAL CONDITIONS AS WELL AS TO SELECT THE MOST EFFECTIVE CROP HUSBANDRY PRACTICES. THE NEXT STEP WILL CONSIST OF DEMONSTRATIONS BY SMALL FARMERS TO ENSURE THAT THEY ARE CAPABLE OF FINANCING & IMPLEMENTING THE NEW CROP/CULTIVATION PACKAGE & THAT INCREASED CROP PRODUCTION OCCURS. A TRNG PROG WILL BE INSTITUTED FOR HOST-COUNTRY AGRI PERSONNEL PARTICIPATING IN THE FIELD TESTING PROG. REGIONAL SEMINARS WILL BE CONDUCTED IN KENYA FOR TOP & MID LEVEL PERSONNEL AND SHORT-COURSES WILL BE INSTITUTED FOR FEILD INSPECTORS & EQUIP OPERATORS. EAAFRO WILL ASLO ESTABLISH A SMALL-SCALE MILLING LAB TO STUDY THE MILLING QUALITY OF VARIOUS CEREALS ESP SORGHUM. OTHER ACTIVITIES WILL INCLUDE DEVLPING RECIPES(USING SORGHUM) SUITED TO EAST AFR TASTES,DEVLPING SIMPLIFIED PROCESSING PEOCEDURES & PROVIDING RESEARCH RESULTS TO SORGHUM BREEDERS. US TECH SERVICES PROVIDED TO THE EARLIER PROJ -- A BIOCHEMIST,A GENETICIST,AN AGRONOMIST, AN ENTOMOLOGIST & A SOIL SCIENTIST -- WILL BE CONTINUED. 2 ADDITIONAL US AGRONOMISTS WILL ASSIST WIITH FIELD TESTING& A PLANT BREEDER WILL ASSIST IN SOYBEAN RESEARCH. USAID WILL ALSO PROVIDE SOME SPECIALIZED EQUIP. EAAFRO AND HOST-COUNTRIES WILL PROVIDE PERSONNEL AND FACILITIES.

Abstract: TECH ASSISTANCE PROVIDED TO REORGANIZE THE ADMIN OPERATIONS AND THEREBY INCREASE THE COLLECTED REVENUES OF THE FOLLOWING GOVT OF ARGENTINA REVENUE-PRODUCING AGENCIES: TAX ADMINISTRATION (TA), CUSTOMS ADMIN (CA), TAX & FISCAL ADMIN-PROVINCE OF BUENOS AIRES (TFA), PROVINCIAL ADMIN (PA), SOCIAL SECURITY ADMIN (SSA), AND BUDGETING & ACCOUNTING (BA). Abstract: GRANT PROVIDED TO GOVERNMENT OF HONDURAS TO PROMOTE CITIZEN PARTICIPATION IN THE PLANNING AND EXECUTION OF GOVERNMENT PROJECTS. PROJECT COMPONENTS INCLUDE: 1)STRENGTHENING OF THE ACCION CULTURAL POPULAR HONDURENA'S RADIO-PHONICS SCHOOL THROUGH TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE; 2)SELECTION OF REGIONS TO CONDUCT THE CIVIC LEADERSHIP PROGRAM; 3)US-PARTICIPANT TRAINING OF HONDURAN LEADERS; 4)ESTABLISHMENT OF COMMUNITY COUNCILS TO PLAN AND EXECUTE SOCIO-ECONOMIC PROJECTS AND THE JOINING OF LOCAL COUNCILS ON A REGIONAL LEVEL; 5)DISCUSSION OF THE PROGRAM WITH MUNICIPAL OFFICIALS; AND 6)MEETINGS WITH ORGANIZATIONS CONCERNED WITH CIVIC DEVELOPMENT TO COORDINATE A PLAN FOR IMPLEMENTATION OF THE PROGRAM AND TO ESTABLISH A COUNCIL FOR CIVIC DEVELOPMENT COMPOSED OF MEMBERS OF THESE CONCERNED ORGANIZATIONS. PROP REVISION OF 12/71 EXTENDS PROJECT FOR 10 YEARS AND CHANGES ITS SCOPE. CENTRO COOPERATIVO TECNICO INDUSTRIAL (CCTI) AND DEVELOPMENT EDUCATION CORPORATION WERE RECIPIENTS OF GRANTS TO CONDUCT A NATIONAL CIVIC DEVELOPMENT COUNCIL (NCDC) CIVIC LEADERSHIP TRAINING PROGRAM. CCTI, WITH THE TECHNICAL ADVISORY ASSISTANCE OF DEVELOPMENT EDUCATION CORPORATION, CONDUCTS FUND-RAISING CAMPAIGNS, INCREASES THE NUMBER OF NCDC'S FIELD STAFF, AND ESTABLISHES AN ADVISORY BOARD TO ADMINISTER NCDG'S PROGRAM. LOCAL, RURAL AND URBAN LEADERS ARE TRAINED IN CIVIC LEADERSHIP BY CCTI. MUNICIPAL AUTHORITIES ARE TAUGHT CIVIC DEVELOPMENT AND MUNICIPAL ADMINISTRATION THROUGH SEMINARS. CCTI IS COMPLETING 80 SOCIO-ECONOMIC PROFILES OF SELECTED MUNICIPALITIES, AND IS ALSO PROVIDING TRAINING, ADVISORY SERVICES AND SUPERVISION FOR THE DISTRITO CENTRAL'S COMMUNITY DEVELOPMENT STAFF. COMMUNITY COUNCILS ARE ORGANIZED AND LOCAL MUNICIPALITIES ARE ENCOURAGED TO BUDGET FOR THEIR OWN STAFF'S TRAINING. AN INCREASE IN THE NUMBER OF RADIO SCHOOLS, THE NUMBER OF STUDENTS ENROLLED, THE CONDUCTING OF FUND-RAISING CAMPAIGNS AND THE PROGRAM'S FINANCIAL AND TECHNICAL SELF-SUFFICIENCY, STRENGTHEN THE RADIO-PHONICS SCHOOL PROGRAM. HOST COUNTRY PROVIDES MONEY, FACILITIES, PERSONNEL, & SERVICES WHILE AID PROVIDES TECHNICAL ADVISORY ASSISTANCE, VEHICLES, RADIO EQUIPMENT, TAPES, & BUDGET SUPPORT FOR PROGRAM STAFF.

Abstract: REPORTS ON EXPERIMENTS DESIGNED TO ASSESS THE BEST MEANS OF IMMUNIZING CALVES AGAINST ANAPLASMA MARGINALE INFECTION. TWENTY CALVES THREE MONTHS OLD WERE DIVIDED INTO FOUR GROUPS. GROUP I WAS INOCULATED WITH AN ATTENUATED ANAPLASMA MARGINALE, GROUP II WITH A. MARGINALE ADJUVANT VACCINE. GROUP III WAS INFECTED WITH VIRULENT A. MARGINALE FOLLOWED BY TREATMENT, AND GROUP IV REMAINED AS UNVACCINATED CONTROLS. ALL ANIMALS WERE MOVED INTO AN ANAPLASMA ENDEMIC ZONE THREE MONTHS LATER AND ALLOWED TO UNDERGO NATURAL FIELD CHALLENGE. EVIDENCE OF ACUTE SEVERE ANAPLASMOSIS WAS OBSERVED IN ALL CALVES EXCEPT THOSE PREMUNIZED BY VIRULENT A. MARGINALE. IN A SECOND EXPERIMENT, HEMATOLOGIC RESPONSE TO VIRULENT, ATTENUATED, AND KILLED A. MARGINALE VACCINES WAS MEASURED IN 18 MATURE CATTLE DIVIDED INTO THREE GROUPS. AN EXPERIMENTAL CHALLENGE WAS ADMINISTERED 8 WEEKS LATER TO CATTLE THAT RECEIVED THAT ATTENUATED AND ADJUVANT VACCINES. AN UNVACCINATED CONTROL GROUP WAS ALSO ADMINISTERED THE CHALLENGE. ALL OF THE CONTROL ANIMALS DEVELOPED ACUTE ANAPLASMOSIS. CATTLE THAT RECEIVED THE ATTENUATED VACCINE RESISTED THE CHALLENGE. CATTLE THAT RECEIVED THE ADJUVANT VACCINE REACTED TO THE CHALLENGE, BUT LESS SEVERELY THAN DID THE CONTROL ANIMALS.

Abstract: TECHNICAL ADVISORY ASSISTANCE PROVIDED TO THE GOVERNMENT OF COSTA RICA (GOCR) TO IMPROVE THE QUALITY OF ELEMENTARY EDUCATION BY DEVELOPING INSTITUTIONAL EXPERTISE IN SCHOOL ADMINISTRATION AND SUPERVISION, CURRICULUM EVALUATION AND DEVELOPMENT, AND INSTRUCTIONAL MATERIALS SELECTION, PREPARATION AND USE. PROJECT ACTIVITIES INCLUDE: 1)ELEMENTARY TEXTBOOK DEVELOPMENT AND PRODUCTION; 2)NORMAL SCHOOL IMPROVEMENT; 3)SUPERVISION AND IMPROVEMENT OF INSTRUCTION AND; 4)ADMINISTRATIVE AND SUPERVISORY REFORMS AND REFINEMENTS. USAID FURNISHES SERVICES OF ONE DIRECT-HIRE HIGHER EDUCATION DEVELOPMENT OFFICER AND TWO SHORT TERM CONTRACT CONSULTANTS FOR THE ADMINISTRATION OF THE TEXTBOOK PROGRAM AND TWO PARTICIPANT TRAINING GRANTS FOR STUDY IN U.S. HOST GOVERNMENT ASSUMES COSTS OF REPRINTING; PROVIDES PERSONNEL SERVICES FOR CONTROL AND DISTRIBUTION OF TEXTBOOKS; ORIENTATION OF TEACHERS; AND PROVIDES STORAGE FACILITIES AND TRANSPORTATION FOR DISTRIBUTION OF TEXTS. TEXTBOOKS FOR GRADES 1-6 ARE IN SUBJECT ARES OF SCIENCE, SOCIAL STUDIES, MATHEMATICS AND LANGUAGE. PROP 7/27/70 EXTENDS PROJECT IMPLEMENTATION ONE YEAR DUE TO DELAYS IN PRINTING SCHEDULE. INDICATES THAT AID FUNDING IS NO LONGER CRITICAL TO CONTINUED DEVELOPMENT OF COSTA RICAN EDUCATION, AND PROJECT HAS BEEN PHASED TO ONE ACTIVITY, TEXTBOOK DEVELOPMENT AND PRODUCTION.

Abstract: GRANT TO THE GOVERNMENT OF THE PHILIPPINES TO CONDUCT FOLLOW-UP AND EVALUATION OF RETURNED PARTICIPANTS AND TO PROVIDE PARTICIPANT TRAINING IN AREAS OUTSIDE EXISTING USAID PROJECTS. USAID AND THE PHILIPPINE GOVERNMENT WILL SUPPORT AND EXPAND THE "PHILIPPINE FELLOWS ASSOCIATION (FOA)." FOA IS THE CHIEF SOURCE OF CONTROL FOR RETURNEES; ITS CONFERENCES AND SEMINARS ENCOURAGE MORE ACTIVE PARTICIPATION ON THE PART OF ITS 1,191 MEMBERS IN GOVERNMENT DEVELOPMENT PROGRAMS. USAID WILL: 1) MONITOR THE CURRENT LOCATION, EMPLOYMENT STATUS AND TRAINING UTILIZATION OF RETURNED PARTICIPANTS; 2) PUBLISH ANNUALLY A DIRECTORY OF ALL RETURNED PARTICIPANTS; 3) PROCURE TECHNICAL JOURNALS, BOOKS, FILMS, AND MEMBERSHIPS IN AMERICAN PROFESSIONAL SOCIETIES TO KEEP PARTICIPANTS UP-TO-DATE IN THEIR RESPECTIVE FIELDS; 4) EDIT AND PUBLISH A NEWSLETTER AND A JOURNAL FOR ALL RETURNEES; 5) IN CONJUNCTION WITH FILIPINO AND US TECHNICAL PERSONNEL AND THE FOA, PLAN AND ENCOURAGE MEETINGS, SEMINARS, AND WORKSHOPS FOR GROUPS OF RETURNED PA RTICIPANTS; 6) PROVIDE GUIDANCE TO RECENTLY RETURNED PARTICIPANTS DURING THE CRUCIAL PERIOD OF JOB RE-ENTRY; AND 7) CONDUCT CEREMONIES FOR PRESENTATION OF USAID'S "CERTIFICATE OF ACHIEVEMENT" AWARDS TO RETURNED PARTICIPANTS. MOST OF THESE ACTIVITIES WILL BE TAKEN OVER AND FUNDED BY THE PHILIPPINE CIVIL SERVICE COMMISSION AND THE FOA. THE GOP WILL BEAR THE COSTS OF TRANSPORTATION, PER DIEM, SALARIES, CONFERENCE FEES, AND OTHER COSTS OF HOLDING THE CONVENTIONS, WORKSHOPS, AND SEMINARS.

Abstract: Evaluates present rice drying, storage, and milling practices in Laos. Report is based on observatns. Laos does not have sufficient rice productn to satisfy consumer needs. New rice varieties requiring less growing time & responsive to fertilizer have been developed. When irrigatn is possible these new varieties allow farmers to grow 2 crops/yr on the same land. Problems which result with increased rice productn include the following: 1) the harvest gathered at the beginning of the wet season is difficult to dry by traditional methods; 2) rice storage space is inadequate; 3) Laos transportatn does not allow movemt of grain to markets; and 4) milling quality is inadequate. Since current milling techniques often break grains, evaluator recommends utilizatn of larger, more efficient rice mills; and training of millers in proper milling procedures through an outreach program. Many farmers have been convinced in using new rice varieties that agr techniques can be improved with effort but the educatnal level of farmers, along with poor transportatn, and small farm size will require the developmt of simple procedures. Mission should provide a technician to assist Laos devel improved drying, storage, and milling. The research to improve agr techniques could be conducted at the Salakham Rice Exp Sta. Recommendatns include the following: 1) farmers should continue to use traditional sun drying techniques until artificial drying is available through well administered cooperative systems, 2) storage capacity should be increased and grain quality encouraged by having the Govt of Laos (GOL) establish rice grain standards based on Thailand's system, 3) research work on harvesting, drying, and milling of rice should be started; 4) farmers should establish grading procedures for rice mrtg; and 6) when adequate rice production is realized the GOL should investigate potentials for production of other crops.
Ancilary Data: Evaluation period: 15 Sep 1968-28 Sep 1968

Abstract: Project Appraisal Report as of 10/15/68 assesses status of the Agricultural Education Project at the Federal University of Rio Grande do Sul (UFRGS). The Univ of Wisconsin (UW) provides personnel & participant training under AID contract.  Proj aims to establish a successful UFRGS post-graduate agric program, to upgrade & update agric research leading to increased productivity, & to remove hindrances to Brazil's agric progress in the areas of manpower preparation, teaching, research & extensn. UFRGS is being helped to modernize its approach to agric educ through integration of academic & practically-oriented community service thrusts.  Mission reports outstanding success and discernible progress in (l) placing better qualified personnel in key agricultural positions; (2) an increase in reform-oriented, trained manpower; (3) a firm institutional base for curriculum extension & improvement at UFRGS; & (4) positive farmer response to School for Agric services.  1967 extension efforts included 14 short courses for farmers, 32 research reports/papers published, & 20 research studies completed with 64 continuing into 1968.  UW contract personnel have assisted in (1) upgrading UFRGS staff through academic & short-term partic trng, (2) upgrading instructional & research programs; (3) furthering extension activities & dvlp of the UFRGS experimental farm; & (4) directing post-grad area dvlp in advanced agric & farm mgmt fields.  UW was faulted for not providing analytical, evaluative reports of proj activities. Proj shortcomings include inability to date of emerging grad school of agric to achieve official recognition within the Univ and under Brazilian law, lack of English proficiency of some partic trainees, & delays in receipt of equipment and materials due to burdensome Brazilian regulations.  The University, as well as a host of Brazilian agencies, now appear committed to future funding of extensive project-oriented teaching & research. USAID intends to continue project, now in 5th year, through its FY1972 phase out date.  An in-depth evaluation of all 4 Brazilian university agric educ projects is planned for 1969.

Abstract: Project to develop simple, reversible sterilization techniques.  The University of North Carolina, working with the Institute of Rural Health and Family Planning in Gandhigram, India, will conduct human and animal research to test, particularly in males, the psychological and physical effects and ease of application of the tantalum clip and of a plastic occluding device; and will evaluate laparascopy under sedation or local anesthesia as a way of simplifying tubal occlusion in females.

Abstract: Project to upgrade Bolivia's civil air transport system, mainly by improving facilities at Bolivia's four major airports - El Alto (La Paz), Cochabamba, El Trampillo (Santa Cruz), and Trinidad.  The Airports and Auxiliary Air Navigation Services Administration (AASANA) will implement the project. El Alto airport will be expanded to include an international air cargo storage building and a cargo loading area with aircraft apron, as well as an adequate water supply for its new terminal building. Cochabamba airport will be improved with newly paved and lighted taxiways and aircraft apron and with terrain warning lights.  El Trompillo and Trinidad airports will be improved with paved and lighted runways, taxiways, and parking apron. Communications equipment and navigation aids, as well as ground support/maintenance equipment, will be provided to assist airport operations. A.I.D. will also finance technical assistance (170 person/months) to AASANA and to Lloyd Aereo Boliviana (LAB), the national airline; the latter assistance will be in the areas of flight operations, maintenance, dispatching, and ground handling.  A total of 115 person/months of training will be provided to 25 participants in the United States and third countries for AASANA and National Civil Aviation Agency personnel.  Training will be offered in radio maintenance and installation, airport maintenance and operation, air traffic control, communications operations, aircraft maintenance inspection, and accident investigation. The Export-Import Bank will fund the purchase of one Boeing 727 aircraft and two Fairchild-Hiller F-27K turbo-prop aircraft for LAB's air fleet, along with spare parts necessary for their maintenance.

Abstract: SUBPROJECT PROVIDES TA AND PARTICIPANT TRAINING TO IMPROVE ADMINISTRATION IN BRAZILIAN UNIVERSITIES.  APPROXIMATELY 24 UNIVERSITIES WILL BE HELPED TO IMPROVE OPERATIONS IN THE AREAS OF ORGANIZATION, ACADEMIC ADMINISTRATION, FLEXIBLE ACADEMIC SYSTEMS, ACADEMIC CREDITS, FINANCIAL MANAGEMENT, BUDGETING, CENTRALIZED ACCOUNTING, STUDENT RECORDS, ENTRANCE REQUIREMENTS, CAMPUS PLANNING, AND DEVELOPMENT AND PLANT MAINTENANCE.  OTHER UNIVERSITIES WILL BE REACHED THROUGH SEMINARS AND ADMINISTRATIVE MANUALS. THE BRAZILIAN COUNCIL OF UNIVERSITY RECTORS WILL MANAGE THE PROJECT. THE COUNCIL WILL CONTRACT THE UNIVERSITY OF HOUSTON TO: 1.PROVIDE HIGHER EDUCATION ADMINISTRATION CONSULTANTS TO THE COUNCIL AND TO UNIVERSITIES REQUESTING SUCH ASSISTANCE; 2.CONDUCT 4-WEEK DEMONSTRATION COURSES IN HOUSTON FOR BRAZILIAN ADMINISTRATORS. 3.PROVIDE 3-MONTH IN-SERVICE TRAINING IN THE UNITED STATES; AND, 4.ASSIST THE COUNCIL IN CONDUCTING SEMINARS IN BRAZIL AND IN PREPARING MANUALS AND GUIDELINES ON ADMINISTRATION.  IN ADDITION, UP TO 10 UNIVERSITY ADMINISTRATORS WILL RECEIVE U.S. GRADUATE TRAINING.

Abstract: MICHIGAN STATE UNIVERSITY (MSU) CONTRACTED TO DEVELOP A LAND GRANT-TYPE UNIVERSITY IN NIGERIA'S EASTERN REGION BY PROVIDING ACADEMIC STAFFING, ADMINISTRATION, TRAINING.  THIS INSTITUTION BUILDING EFFORT CREATED A 6,000 STUDENT UNIVERSITY FROM 1960-1967, WHEN NIGERIAN CIVIL WAR MADE FURTHER ASSISTANCE IMPOSSIBLE. 90% OF INITIAL PROJECT TARGETS WERE MET.  IN 1967, THE UNIVERSITY OF NIGERIA AT NSUKKA AND ENUGU HAD 3,100 STUDENTS, AND 80% OF 448 FACULTY MEMBERS WERE NIGERIAN.  61 PARTICIPANTS WERE TRAINED IN US.  ENROLLMENT PLANNED FOR 1972 WAS 6,000.  12 OF 22 PLANNED FACULTIES WERE ESTABLISHED.  MAIN CAMPUS WAS CONSTRUCTED AT NSUKKA WITH SECONDARY AT ENUGU.  THE UNIVERSITY USED INDIGENOUS MATERIALS AND DESIGN WHERE POSSIBLE IN SETTING UP INFRASTRUCTURE: WATER SYSTM, SEWAGE DISPOSAL, ELECTRICITY, ROADS, BUILDINGS. US GRANT INCLUDED DESIGN AND CONSTRUCTION OF CONTINUING EDUCATION CENTER, COMMODITIES FOR FACULTIES OF AGRICULTURE AND ENGINEERING. CONTRACT WITH MSU PROVIDED 35 PROFESSORS, BACKSTOPPING, PARTICIPANT TRAINING.  SPECIALISTS WERE EVACUATED AFTER WAR BEGAN AND CONTRACT WAS PHASED DOWN TO MINIMUM ADMINISTRATIVE SERVICES. BEGINNING IN EARLY 1970, AID WILL FIELD A TEAM OF SIX ADVISORS TO PREPARE FOR THE RE-OPENING OF THE UNIVERSITY BY SERVING IN THE FOLLOWING CAPACITIES:  ADMINISTRATIVE ADVISOR TO THE VICE-CHANCELLOR; UNIVERSITY BUSINESS MANAGER; AND DEPARTMENT HEADS/FACULTY DEANS OF EDUCATION, ENGINEERING, ARTS & SCIENCES, AND CONTINUING EDUCATION.  THESE PERSONNEL WILL BE SUPPLEMENTED BY NINE ADDITIONAL FACULTY MEMBERS IN ARTS & SCIENCES AND NINE IN AGRICULTURE.  SUBSTANTIAL AMOUNTS OF COMMODITY FUNDING TO RESTORE TEACHING AND RESEARCH FACILITIES, AS WELL AS PARTICIPANT TRAINING, WILL ALSO BE FUNDED.

Abstract: EVALUATES THE PERFORMANCE OF THE BRAZILIAN ELEM & BASIC EDUC PROJECT AS IMPLEMENTED IN THE STATE OF RIO GRANDE DO NORTE FOR THE PERIOD 1/1/65-6/30/68. PURPOSE OF PROJECT WAS TO UPGRADE SCHOOL FACILITIES AND THE TEACHING & SUPERVISORY PROGRAMS. EVAL WAS CONDUCTED BY EXAMINING USAID/B & SECERN  (SERVICO COOPERATIVA DE EDUCACAO DO RIO GRANDE DO NORTE) RECORDS AND HOLDING DISCUSSIONS WITH USAID/B/NEAO OFFICIALS & THE STATE SECRETARY OF EDUC. LARGE-SCALE OBJECTIVES SET FORTH IN THE ORIGINAL PROAG COULD NOT BE MET DUE TO HIGH INFLATION, INADEQUATE CONTRACTOR CAPABILITY FOR TIMELY COMPLETION OF CONSTRUCTION, SECERN'S INADEQUACY FOR ADMINISTERING A PROGRAM OF THIS SIZE, AND DELAYS IN STATE FINANCIAL CONTRIBUTIONS. SUBSEQUENT REVISIONS TO PROAG PARED DOWN PROJ TARGETS TO ACHIEVABLE LEVELS. AT TIME OF EVAL, 4 BLDGS (SR NORMAL SCHL, ELEM SCHL, INDUSTRIAL ARTS SHOP, PHYSICS/BIOL LAB)OF THE JOHN F KENNEDY INST OF EDUC AND 119 SCHLS HAD BEEN COMPLETED. BLDGS NOT COMPLETED INCLUDED A KINDERGARTEN AT THE JFK INST -- STOPPED AFTER BEING 40% CONSTRUCTED DUE TO LACK OF FUNDS, AND 29 SCHLS WHICH HAD NOT PROGRESSED BEYOND THEIR FOUNDATIONS. THE STATE DIVERTED A LARGE AMT OF USAID FUNDING AWAY FROM CONSTRCTN TO PAY FOR ITS ADMIN COSTS. ALSO, AS SUDENE (THE LOAN ADMINISTRATOR)FAILED TO KEEP ACCURATE RECORDS OF CONSTRCTN INVOICES, IT WAS IMPOSSIBLE TO DETERMINE IF ALL CONTRACTOR FUNDING REQUESTS WERE LEGITIMATE. DUE TO POOR ROAD CONDITIONS,END-USE CHECKS COULD ONLY BE MADE ON 2 SCHLS. BOTH APPEARED ADEQUATELY PLANNED BUT POORLY CONSTRCTD & MAINTAINED. INDOOR SANITARY FACILS WERE INOPERABLE AS WATER PUMPS HAD NEVER BEEN CONNECTED. ACCORDING TO SUDENE,OF ALL THE COMPLETED SCHLS,6 WERE NOT BEING USED. THE JFK INST WAS WELL-UTILIZED EXCEPT FOR ITS LAB WHICH LACKED EQPMNT. THE JFK INST ALSO APPEARED TO BE WELL CONSTRCTD. ALTHOUGH THERE WAS NO MAINT PROG FOR THE SCHLS,SUCH A PROG WAS SUPPOSEDLY BEING DEVELOPED. THE CLASSROOM RECONSTRCTN PROG WAS TERMINATED. PROJ TRNG COMPONENT FOLLOWED REVISED GUIDELINES. AT TIME OF EVAL,2550 LAY TCHRS,300 ADULT EDUC INSTRCTRS,4 TCHR SUPRVSRS & 36 SUPRVRS HAD BEEN TRND.  THE ADULT EDUC PROG REMAINED TERMINATED.
Ancilary Data: Evaluation period: 1 Jan1965-30 Jun1968

Abstract: EVALUATES PROJECT PERFORMANCE FROM 1959 TO 1966 IN BURMA. PROJECT ASSISTS THE GOVT OF THE UNION OF BURMA (GUB) TO RAISE THE ACADEMIC STANDARDS OF RANGOON UNIV (RU) BY PROVIDING FUNDS FOR THE EXPANSION OF PHYSICAL FACILITIES AND ESTABLISHMT OF A LIBERAL ARTS COLLEGE. EXAMINATN MADE BY USAID CONTROLLER BASED ON PROJ DOCS CONCERNING PROPERTY DATA,REPORTING ADHERENCE TO AID MARKETING REQUIREMTS,UTILIZATN OF EQUIPMT,CONTRIBUTNS OF GUB,AND END-USE ONSITE VISITS. LACK OF UNIV TRAINING HAS BEEN ONE OF GUB'S MOST SERIOUS PROBS IMPARING HER POLITICAL AND ECONOMIC FUTURE. GUB ATTEMPTED TO HANDLE HER STUDENT BODY,WHICH HAD QUADRUPLED SINCE 1948,BY ESTABLISHING A SERIES OF INTERMEDIATE JUNIOR COLLEGES IN MAJOR GEOGRAPHICA1 AREAS. AFTER UNSUCCESSFUL ATTEMPTS AT ESTABLISHING 2 JUNIOR COLLEGES IN RAGOON DUE TO INADEQUATE HOUSING AND OVER CROWDING ILL-EQUIPPED CLASSROOMS,GUB COMBINED THESE SCHOOLS INTO A PART OF RU WITH THE CONSTRUCTN OF DORMITORIES,CLASSROOMS,AND AUXILLARY FACILITES TO HOUSE 6,000 STUDENTS. MISPLACEMT OR LOSS OF PROJECT REGISTER CLAIMS CAUSED EVALUATOR TO RECOMMEND THAT NEW CLAIM REGISTERS BE ESTABLISHED, GUB HAS SUBMITTED REPORTS ON ITS CONTRIBUTNS AND EVALUATOR FEELS THE PUBIIC WORKS CROP (PWC) SHOULD SUBMIT A REPORT OF SUCH CONTRIBUTIONS FROM PROJECT'S INCEPTION. QUARTERLY PROGRESS REPORTS NOT RECIEVED FROM PWC SHOULD BE SUBMITTED BEGINNING FY1969. EXAMINATION OF PAYMENTS TO CONTRACTORS IN MISSION BOOKS WERE IN ACCORDANCE WITH TERMS OF CONTRACTS,10 PIO/C'S WERE ESTABLISHED FOR PROCUREMENT OF COMMODITIES RECORDS OF EQUIPMENT AT RU STORYARD;WAREHOUSES WERE WELL MAINTAINED;ALL AID FINANCED COMMODITIES & EQUIPMT WERE PROPERLY STORED;AND ALL MARKETING REQUESTS HAVE BEEN MET. ALTHOUGH NO REPORTS OF FINANCIAL CONTRIBUTNS HAVE BEEN FURNISHED,GUB HAS AGREED TO: PROVIDE FUNDS NECESSARY TO COMPLETE PROJ IN ADDITN TO THOSE SUPPLIED BY AID;ADEQUATELY STAFF THE PWC CONSTRUCTN IMPLEMENTATN DIV;PROVIDE UNENCUMBERED TITLE AND ACESS TO PROJECT SITE & SURV EYING INFORMATION; PROVIDE STAFF,LAB EQUIPMT,LIBRARY BOOKS AND EQUIPMT,GYMNASIUM & HOSPITAL EQUIP TO ENABLE PROPER UTILIZATN;AND BUDGET & PROVIDE MAINTENANCE FOR THE FACILITIES.

Abstract: AS OF 11/30/68.  PROGRESS: 1.PRODUCTION GOAL ACHIEVED OF 2.5 MILLION FINGERLINGS PER YEAR FROM 3 HATCHERIES; 2.A FISH HATCHERY, FINGERLING CULTURE POND AND FISH CULTURE POND CONSTRUCTED. PROBLEMS: 1.LOW SURVIVAL RATE FROM SACK FRY TO FINGERLINGS, HIGH WATER ACIDITY IN HATCHERIES; 2.SECURITY LIMITS FINGERLINGS DISTRIBUTION; 3.ACCOUNTING SYSTEM INADEQUATE FOR SALE OF FINGERLINGS, MARKET FISH, REVENUE EXPENDITURE; 4.LACK OF QUALIFIED PARTICIPANTS, STATISTICAL DATA AND MAINTENANCE. PAR RECOMMENDATIONS: 1.CONDUCT A COORDINATING SURVEY OF FISH CULTURING IN LAOS, THAILAND, CAMBODIA, VIETNAM TO PERMIT BETTER USE OF MEKONG FISH RESOURCES; 2.INCREASE EMPHASIS ON ADMINISTRATION; 3.CONSTRUCT HOLDING TANKS IN SELECTED AREAS TO REPLACE DISTRIBUTION DIRECTLY FROM HATCHERIES; 4.AID/W SHOULD ENCOURAGE RESEARCH BY INTERNATIONAL GROUPS ON THE MEKONG'S FISH RESOURCES. LESSONS LEARNED: ASSISTANCE IN PROVIDING BETTER FISHING GEAR, NEW BOATS, TRAINING, REGULATION OF FISHING, TRANSPORTATION STORAGE, REFRIGERATION AND MARKETING MAY HAVE PROVIDED GREATER IMMEDIATE RETURNS AND HELP TO THE BELEAGUERED LAO ECONOMY THAN PLACING EMPHASIS ON FISH CULTURE FOR WHICH THERE WAS LITTLE OR NO TRADITION AMONG LAO.

Abstract: July 1967 suspension of loan disbursements occasions USAID Status Report (as of 9/5/68) on Minas Gerais Highway Maintenance Program. Project entails $15 million A.I.D. loan with $21.4 million local currency support to finance the purchase of equipment and technical services to develop the state's highway department and maintain roads. The State of Minas Gerais is judged to be seriously delinquent in meeting its financial obligations undertaken in connection with the loan.  Decreased revenues and a 33% reduction in the states' share of fuels tax earmarked for the national highway fund rendered the state insolvent and unable to honor its commitment to support the maintenance operations of its State Highway Department (DER/MG).  A proposed state-levied compensating circulation tax on fuels and lubricants was postponed for a year by federal decree.  An AID-sponsored study of DER/MG's financial situation in mid 1967 prompted a meeting with the state's governor to seek a solution.  Despite governor's guarantee, it was soon evident that funds would not be forthcoming. Maintenance operations were cut back and USAID suspended disbursements. Short-term loan from Bank of Brazil did not ease situation.  Another meeting with governor in 2/68 resulted in another agreement to utilize proposed state vehicle registration tax with other required funds to be appropriated from state's budget.  Tax receipts and budget allocations have not yet been deposited, and the Mission must conclude that Minas Gerais has not demonstrated capacity to mobilize funds. DER/MG has not yet instituted a number of agreed-upon administrative and organizational changes: cost accounting and warehouse control systems; an equipment replacement schedule; equipment standardization; and reformulation of an in-service manual and organizational pattern. USAID has ordered comprehensive audit of DER/MG's operations and finances and has notified DER/MG of its possible withdrawal from the project, thereby placing the loan in default.  A loan in support of the State's secondary education system is being withheld pending resolution of the DER situation.

Abstract: Evaluates performance of the Industrial Development Center (IDC) as of 8/68. IDC, located at Zaria, provides management and technical assistance to small entrepreneurs in Northern Nigeria engaged in woodworking, metals, automotive, leather, or other manufacturing. In the past, this project has experienced numerous difficulties in construction, recruitment of US personnel, equipment procurement and installation, and GONN recruitment of counterpart staff. These have now been solved. During 1967, management workshops were conducted, both at IDC and in the field, for 300 participants.  IDC provided consultation to 125 small establishments and prepared formal feasibility studies as required. During the past 6 months, IDC conducted 9 woodworking demonstrations for 54 supervisory personnel and 5 metalworking demonstrations for 37 personnel, IDC also regularly provided on-the-spot, extension-type demonstrations from mobile equipped carryalls of woodworking, metals, and automotive equipment. IDC now provides technical advice to the Small Industry Credit Scheme (SIC) in assessing loan applications and monitoring subsequent implementation. As a result of IDC's own activity and of the joint IDC/SIC activities, 27 firms have been established or expanded as of 6/30/68, with a total new investment of $504,560 and 465 additional employees. The major remaining problem is the present operation of IDC under the umbrella of the Interim Common Services Agency, which is scheduled to phase out by 3/69. It is essential that IDC be transferred to the Federal Ministry of Industries. Evaluator recommends that USAID request Peace Corps Volunteers for IDC assignment throughout the 6 Northern states as industrial specialists. Also, the present USAID support should be continued until project termination in 6/70.

Abstract: Provides a master plan for the growth and development of the Asian Institute of Technology (AIT) in Bangkok, Thailand, through 1977.  AIT is a graduate engineering institution offering a Masters degree in Civil Engineering with options in hydraulics, transportation, structures, soils, and public health engineering.  Enrollment has grown from 19 in 1959 to 167 in 1967.  Students represent 9 asian countries. The master plan calls for both horizontal and vertical expansion of AIT's academic program. Horizontal expansion would include the addition of masters programs in mechanical engineering, electrical engineering, and one other, as yet unspecified field. Vertical expansion would include the addition of a 3-year doctoral program in Civil Engineering by the 1971-72 school year. The plan projects an enrollment of 684 by 1977.  Enrollment in special, non-degree programs is expected to increase from 330 to 2,914 by 1972.  These consist mainly of conference attendees. To accommodate the above changes, the plan presents specifications for a new campus and recommendations for enlarging faculty and administrative staff.  The cost implications of AIT's proposed development are discussed and a fund-raising program is proposed. The study also contains a history of AIT, an examination of the needs of Asia for high-level manpower, and a review of Asian requirements for engineers.

Abstract: MANPOWR PLANNING AND DEVELOPMENT UTILIZATION PROJECT IN NICARAGUA, 1964-1978, IS TRAINING LESS THAN 5% OF UNION AND NON-UNION WORKERS IN THE PROCESSES OF DEMOCRATIC AND EFFECTIVE TRADE UNION PRACTICES. USAID CONTRACTED WITH AMERICAN INSTITUTE FOR FREE LABOR DEVELOPMENT  (AIFLD) . PROJECT SUPPORT ALSO COMES FROM AFL/CIO AND MEMBER UNIONS,INTERNATIONAL TRADE UNION ORGANIZATIONS,U.S. COMPANIES AND EDUCATIONAL INSTITUTIONS,NICARAGUAN GOVT,AND CERTAIN NICARAGUAN EMPLOYER ORGAINZATIONS. LABOR UNION TRAINING FOR UNION OFFICERS, OTHER WORKERS,WILL RESULT IN BETTER WORKING CONDITIONS,BETTER WAGES,JOB SECURITY,EMPLOYER-EMPLOYEE IMPROVED RELATIONS,OVERALL BETTER LIVING CONDITIONS. FROM APR 1964 - MAR 1974,PROJECT WILL HAVE PROVIDED BASIC TRAINING IN TRADE UNIONISM FOR 3.2% OF THE ORGANIZED AND POTENTIALLY ORGANIZABLE WORKERS IN NICARAGUA. THIS ESTIMATE INCLUDES TRADE UNION OFFICERS WHO HAVE COMPLETED ADVANCED LABOR RELATIONS SEMINARS,AND TRADE UNIONS WHO HAVE UNDERTAKEN SOCIO-ECONOMIC SERVICE PROJECTS FOR THEIR MEMBERSHIP. TRAINING MORE THAN A SMALL CADRE OF LABOR LEADERS WOULD BE COUNTER-PRODUCTIVE IN THE POLITICALLY SENSITIVE CLIMATE OF NICARAGUA. TRAINING TARGETS INCLUDE: 1)TWO SEMINARS ON THE OBJECTIVES OF A FREE LABOR MOVEMENT FOR ABOUT 70 NICARGUANS WHO ARE NOT MEMBERS OF A LABOR UNION; 2)TEN COURSES ON COLLECTIVE BARGAINING,ORGANIZATION AND OTHER RELATED LABOR SUBJECTS FOR 25% NICARAGUAN TRADE UNION OFFICERS; 3)TWENTY SPECIAL-COURSE-WORK SEMINARS ON UNION ORGANIZING ACTIVITIES FOR 300 NICARAGUAN LABOR UNION MEMBERS; 4)A RESIDENTIAL COURSE (64-80 CLASSROOM HOURS)ON LABOR SUBJECTS EMPHASING DUES COLLECTN METHODS & PROCEDURES FOR 30 NICARAGUAN UNION LEADERS; 5)TWELVE MAN-MONTHS OF ADVANCED TRAINING IN TRADE UNIONISM FOR 4-8 NICARAGUAN UNION LEADERS; 6)SIXTEEN MAN-MONTHS TRAINING IN LABOR ECONOMICS FOR TWO NICARAGUAN UNION LEADERS; 7)ONE FOUR-WEEK RESIDENTIAL COURSE FOR RURAL WORKERS; 8)TEN ONE-WEEK RURAL WORKER BASIC COURSES. MINISTRY OF LABOR TO PROVIDE BOTH ITS MORAL SUPPORT AND THE USE OF ITS CLASSROOM/MEETING HALL FACILITIES FOR IN-COUNTRY TRAINING.
Ancilary Data: Evaluation period: 1970-1973

Abstract: THE INTERNATIONAL VOLUNTARY SERVICES ORGANIZATION (IVS) WILL PROVIDE VOLUNTEERS ON A CONTRCT BASIS TO WORK WITH ZAIRE CONTERPARTS AT THE FIELD LEVEL AND TO TRAIN THEM IN THE TECHNIQUES OF FARM PLANNING AND LOAN PROCESSING. A FULL-TIME SENIOR AGRICULTURE CREDIT ADVISOR WILL BE RECRUITED TO ASSIST GOVT OFFICIALS TO DEVELOP PROJECT PROCEDURES. THE GOVERNING BODY WILL BE CENTRAL CREDIT COMMITTEE. THE EXISTING LOCAL BANK FACILITIES WILL BE UTILIZED FOR LOAN OPERATIONS. THIS CREDIT PROGRAM WILL CATER TO THOSE FARMERS WHO POSSESS THE BASIC ECONOMIC FACTORS OF PRODUCTION. CREDIT WILL NOT BE LIMITED TO PRODUCTION LOANS BUT WILL ALSO BE AVAILABLE TO FARMERS' SERVICE ORGANIZATION. I

Abstract: GOT CENTRALIZES FOOD/NUTRITION ACTIVITIES IN FINANCIALLY AUTONOMOUS NATIONAL INSTITUTE OF NUTRITION AND FOOD TECHNOLOGY, FORMED BY CONSOLIDATING VARIOUS EXISTING AGENCIES. 4 MAJOR TECHNICAL DIVISIONS ESTABLISH PROGRAMS, RESEARCH IN NUTRITION, FOOD TECHNOLOGY, FOOD ECONOMICS, NUTRITION EDUCATION/EXTENSION. RESEARCH, SURVEYS ARE CONDUCTED ON DISEASES, AMINO ACID FORTIFICATION, CONSUMPTION PATTERNS. DIVISIONS ASSIST FEEDING PROGRAMS, IMPROVE FOOD HANDLING AND PROCESSING, UPGRADE INSTRUCTION AND EXTENSION, ADVISE ON NATIONAL FOOD POLICY. SURVEY DETERMINES NUTRITIONAL STATUS, FOOD AVAILABILITY, POTENTIAL SOLUTIONS. GOT ASSUMES FULL EXPENSE IN 1977, WHEN ALLPARTICIPANTS TRAINED, SURVEY COMPLETED, NUTRITION PLAN BEGUN

Abstract: Grant is provided to the Government of the Philppines (GOP) to improve the quality of its law enforcement personnel.  The GOP's Police Commission will implement the project. Ten regional training academies (RTA) will be established to provide a 3-month basic police science course to present patrolmen and new recruits. Independent training will continue at five other centers. RTA's will also offer a 1-month administration course to police supervisors; special training in investigation and record keeping for 4,000 police; and advanced, in-service training in traffic accident/crime scene reporting, police photography, first line supervision, radio maintenance, and laboratory techniques.  RTA instructors will be locally recruited and 72 will be trained in instructional methods at A.I.D.'s International Police Academy in Washington.  The GOP will construct RTA facilities and USAID will supply each with a reference library, audiovisual equipment, guns, ammunition, and riot control equipment. A Law Enforcement Communication Service (LECS) combining all national police radio networks will be established to improve law enforcement communication between Manila and the provinces, and 55 provincial networks will be developed to provide better communication between province and municipality and between and within municipalities.  To facilitate this, computerized fingerprint, crime reporting, and police selection and employment data systems will be created and assistance will be given in fingerprinting and evidence collection. A roll call procedure will be instituted in each municipality to provide daily supervisor/officer discussions of police problems. USAID will provide battery-operated, 150 megacycle VHF-FM radios, low-power SSB units, and tactical "walkie-talkie" type units. Under a Police Improvement Program, 25 police departments will receive professional assistance in administration, investigation, criminalistics, telecommunications, traffic management, and tactical operations.  Full use of RTA training opportunities will be encouraged. These police departments will, in turn, serve as models for surrounding areas.

Abstract: Evaluates performance of University of Minnesota on a project to assist the govt of Tunisia in building effective institutions for agricultural economic research and planning, and to assist the University of Tunis in economics and related subjects.  Evaluation is based on a review of files and discussions with project personnel. Univ of Minnesota has not provided personnel as scheduled.  No production economist was assigned during the first year or the first 3 months of the second year.  Only 1 of 2 scheduled assistant economists was assigned during the first year, and the full complement of 3 assistant economists is not expected until the fall of 1968. The creation of an independent facility for the contract team limited its day-to-day contact with the Ministry of Agriculture, and kept it out of operational and policy-making activities.  This problem was aggravated by the team's limited knowledge of French. The type of studies undertaken by the team appear to have originated with USAID.  As a result, full acceptance of the group will take longer than usual. Non-assignment of professional-level trainees by govt of Tunisia has also hindered progress.  Govt of Tunisia attributed the situation to a lack of funds.  In response, a PIO/T was signed on 5/23/68 authorizing up to 4 economic trainees under the Dinar Trust Fund. It was learned that when activities are initiated by US and are separated from host country offices, full and instant recognition should not be expected. It is recommended that future project leaders be fluent in French.

Abstract: LIBERIA IS PROVIDED WITH GRANT, TECH ADVISORY ASSIST AND COMMODITIES TO ESTABLISH SELF-SUSTAINING AND EFFICIENT TELECOMMUNICATIONS SYST. SEMI-AUTONOMOUS TELECOMMUNICATIONS AUTHORITY WILL BE ESTABLISHED. U.S. ASSISTANCE IN FORM OF MANAGERIAL AND TECH PERSONNEL WILL MANAGE THE AUTHORITY UNTIL LIBERIAN STAFF CAN BE TRAINED. U.S. PERSONNEL WILL OPERATE UNDER GENERAL DIRECTION OF A BOARD OF DIRECTORS APPOINTED BY GOL. THESE PERSONNEL WILL WORK TO INSTITUTE TECH, FINANCIAL AND OPERATIONAL PROCEDURES IN ACCORDANCE WITH SOUND BUSINESS PRACTICES. PROJ WILL FOCUS ON EFFECTING MAXIMUM UTILIZATION OF EXISTING TELECOM FACILITIES, AS WELL AS DEVELOPING PLANS FOR ORDERLY EXPANSION OF SYST WHERE ECONOMICALLY FEASIBLE. POSITIONS TO BE FILLED BY U.S. PERSONNEL IN ACCOMPLISHING THESE TASKS INCLUDE GENERAL MANAGER, COMPTROLLER, TRAFFIC MANAGER-RESPONSIBLE FOR QUALITY OF SERVICES-,PLANT OPERATIONS ENGINEER,AND A TRNG AND PERSONNEL MANAGER. REMAINING 5 POSITIONS ARE TECHNICALLY ORIENTED AND WILL BE SUBORDINATE TO MGMT POSITIONS. TRNG AND PERSONNEL MANAGER WILL BE RESPONSIBLE FOR IN-SERVICE TRNG PROG FOR COUNTERPARTS.IT WILL INCLUDE THEORY AND PRACTICES IN BASIC ELECTRICITY AND ELECTRONICS, LECTURES,AND ON-JOB TRNG ON SPECIFIC TELECOM EQUIPMENT SUCH AS DEISEL PLANTS, TELEPHONE SWITCHING EQUIPMENT, HIGH FREQUENCY RADIO SYSTS, MICRO-WAVE AND CARRIER TRANSMISSION SYST, AND TELEPRINTER FOR TELEX. USAID WILL ALSO PROVIDE TRNG SUPPLIES. GOL WILL FINANCE BASE SALARY FOR 10 U.S. OPERATIONAL PERSONNEL AND PROVIDE SUPPORTING STAFF, FACILITIES AND EQUIPMENT, PRIMARY BENEFICIARIES ARE GOL AND TELECOM AUTHORITY PERSONNEL. PROP (8/21/70) EXPANDS PERSONNEL TO 16 AND ADDS PARTICIPANT TRNG ELEMENT FOR TOTAL OF 27 TOP-LEVEL PERSONNEL. FINANCIAL, ECONOMIC AND TECH ANALYSES WERE ADDED AS PRELIMINARY TO IMPLEMENTATION OF USAID-LOAN FINANCED REPAIR AND EXPANSION PROG.LOAN (669-H-021) WILL PROVIDE FOR ENGRG DESIGN AND SUPERVISION OF EXPANSION, PROCUREMENT AND INSTALLATION OF EQUIPMENT AND MATERIALS, AS WELL AS LIMITED PERIOD OF MAINTENANCE AND OPERATIONS TRNG AFTER INSTALLATION. PRESENT CONTRACT FOR MGMT AND TRNG ASSISTANCE WILL ALSO BE EXTENDED.

Abstract: SHORT AND LONG-TERM PARTICIPANT TRAINING IS PROVIDED TO CHILE TO IMPROVE ADMINISTRATIVE/MANAGERIAL CAPABILITIES IN BOTH PRIVATE AND PUBLIC SECTORS. PROFESSIONALS FROM CHILEAN GOVT INSTITUTIONS, UNIVERSITIES AND PRIVATE ORGANIZATIONS WILL RECEIVE ADVANCED TRAINING IN A VARIETY OF DISCIPLINES. HOWEVER, FIELDS OF ECONOMICS AND PUBLIC ADMINISTRATION WILL RECEIVE PRIORITY. TRAINING PROGRAMS WILL BE CONDUCTED IN US OR PUERTO RICO. ACADEMIC PARTICIPANTS WILL RECEIVE TRAINING FOR 12-18 MONTHS AT GRADUATE SCHOOLS OF U.S. UNIVERSITIES. SHORT-TERM PARTICIPANTS WILL ATTEND SEMINARS, CONFERENCES OR OBSERVATION PROGRAMS. ALL CANDIDATES WILL BE REQUIRED TO GIVE ASSURANCE OF A POSITION AT THE SAME OR HIGHER LEVEL WITH THEIR SPONSORING AGENCY UPON RETURN. TWENTY LONG-TERM AND 5 SHORT-TERM PARTICIPANT GRANTS ARE ANTICIPATED EACH YEAR FOR AN INDEFINITE PERIOD. CANDIDATES WILL SUBMIT THEIR APPLICATION THROUGH THE NATIONAL PLANNING OFFICE OF THE PRESIDENCY. A SELECTION COMMITTEE WILL BE ESTABLISHED INCLUDING 4 REPRESENTATIVES FROM GOC AGENCIES, UNIVERSITIES, THE PRIVATE SECTOR AND A REPRESENTATIVE FROM THE NATIONAL PLANNING OFFICE. COMMITTEE WILL STUDY, SCREEN AND SUBMIT NAMES OF BEST QUALIFIED APPLICANTS TO THE MISSION. HOST-COUNTRY WILL PROVIDE PERSONNEL AND INSTITUTIONAL SUPPORT. PRIMARY BENEFICIARIES ARE PROFESSIONAL-LEVEL PERSONNEL FROM CHILEAN PUBLIC AND PRIVATE SECTORS AND THEIR SUPPORTING INSTITUIONS. PROP (11/19/70) CHANGED PROJECT'S GENERAL OBJECTIVE TO THE PROVISION OF SHORT-TERM NON-ACADEMIC SOCIAL AND  CIVIC DEVELOPMENT TRAINING. PROJECT WAS ALTERED BECAUSE OF PROPOSED HUMAN RESOURCES DEVELOPMENT LOAN (513-L-044) WHICH WILL CONTAIN A SUBSTANTIAL PARTICIPANT TRAINING ELEMENT.

Abstract: AID PROVIDES TECHNICAL AND ADVISORY ASSISTANCE TO THE GOVERNMENT OF HONDURAS, MINISTRY OF EDUCATION FOR THE PREPARATION,PUBLICATION AND NATIONAL DISTRIBUTION OF MODERN TEXTBOOKS AND TEACHERS GUIDES TO PUBLIC PRIMARY SCHOOLS AND TEACHERS. PROJUCT COMPONENTS INCLUDE THE DESIGN AND IMPLEMENTATION OF A COMPUTERIZED INVENTORY AND DISTRIBUTION MECHANISM; INSERVICETRAINING FOR TEACHERS IN THE USE OF NEW TEXTBOOKS; AND THE TRAINING OF MANAGEMENT LEVEL PERSONNEL IN ASPECTS OF TEXTBOOKPREPARATION (DESIGN, WRITING, PRINTING, ETC.). PROJECT MANAGEMENT AND TRAINING PROVIDED THRU THE CENTER FOR MATERIALS PRODUCTION (CMPE). PROJECT BEGAN IN 1960 AS PROJECT CONCERNED WITH THE TRAINING OF LOCAL WRITERS FOR A NATIONAL TEXTBOOK PROGRAM. SHORTLY AFTER THE ALLIANCE FOR PROGRESS EMPHASIS SWITCHED TO REGIONAL COOPERATION LEADING TO REGIONAL TEXTBOOK PROJECT. REGIONAL CENTER IN SAN SALVADOR PREPARED MANUSCRIPTSAND SENT NEGATIVES TO HONDURAS. USAID ASSISTANCE INCLUDES COOPERATION OF 37 PEACE CORPS VOLUNTEERS IN TEACHER TRAINING AND ADVISORY SERVICES IN TEXTBOOK PUBLICATION AND ADMINISTRATION. MINISTRY OF EDUCATION BUDGETS FOR COUNTERPART PERSONNELAND TEACHER TRAINING. UNESCO PROVIDES ADVISORY SERVICES AND ASSISTANCE WITH TEACHER TRAINING. PROP REVISION 12/18/70 EXPLAINS CONTINUATION OF THE PROJECT, REVISES ESTIMATES OF PROJECT TIMING, INPUTS AND OUTPUTS. PROJECT EMPHASIS SWITCHES FROM TEXTBOOK PRODUCTION TO TEACHER TRAINING AND EVALUATION OFACTIVITY EFFECTS ON QUALITY OF PRIMARY EDUCATION. USAID/H PLANS EDUCATIONAL SECTOR EVALUATION FOR JANUARY/FEBRUARY 1971.

Abstract: CONTRACTED WEST VIRGINIA UNIVERSITY (WVU) TO PROVIDE STAFF AND SOME EQUIPMENT TO UPGRADE AGRICULTURAL EDUCATION AT BUKALASA AND ARAPAI AGRICULTURAL COLLEGES AND AT VETERINARY TRAINING INSTITUTE. THESE SCHOOLS TRAIN ADMINISTRATORS AND FIELD WORKERS FOR UGANDA'S AGRICULTURAL EXTENSION PROGRAM. WVU FILLED 14 REGULAR TEACHING POSITIONS AND HELPED IN CURRICULAR REFORM AT THE 3 SCHOOLS, WHILE COUNTERPARTS WERE TRAINED IN US AND UGANDA. AT THE END OF THE PROJECT, TEACHING STAFFS HAD INCREASED FROM 21 TO 55 TOTAL, AND 51 OF THESE INSTRUCTORS WERE UGANDAN. ENROLLMENT GREW FROM 109 TO 519, AND ANNUAL GRADUATES INCREASED CORRESPONDINGLY. USAID AND THE GOVERNMENT OF UGANDA PROVIDED FUNDS FOR THE EXPANSION OF CLASSROOMS, LABS, LIBRARY FACILITIES, AND HOUSING TO HANDLE THE ENLARGED ENROLLMENT. COURSES WERE OFFERED IN FARM MANAGEMENT, ANIMAL HUSBANDRY, AGRICULTURAL MECHANICS, EXTENSION METHODS, VETERINARY MEDICINE, AGRICULTURAL CHEMISTRY, AND DAIRY SCIENCE. PRACTICAL TRAINING WAS EMPHASIZED THROUGHOUT. CHANGES WERE MADE IN SUBJECT MATTER EMPHASIS, AND COURSES WERE ARRANGED SEQUENTIALLY. ARAPAI BEGAN TO SPECIALIZE IN AGRICULTURAL MECHANIZATION, WHILE BUKALASA DEVELOPED HOME ECONOMICS FOR WOMEN. THE 3 SCHOOLS NOW CONDUCT 2-YEAR CERTIFICATE PROGRAMS, WITH A 3-YEAR DIPLOMA PROGRAM AVAILABLE FOR EXCEPTIONAL STUDENTS. ONLY THE 3-YEAR COURSE WAS OFFERED FROM 1964 TO 1969 AT THE AGRICULTURAL COLLEGES. OTHER CONTRIBUTIONS INCLUDE BRITISH OPEX STAFF AND FAO AND DANISH COMMODITIES.

Abstract: BRITISH HONDURAS (BELISE) PROVIDED WITH GRANT, TECHNICAL ADVISORY ASSISTANCE, ON-JOB AND U.S. PARTICIPANT TRAINING TO STRENGTHEN INVESTMENT PROMOTION SKILLS AND ESTABLISH PERMANENT ADMINISTRATIVE STRUCTURE WITHIN GOVT TO IDENTIFY AND PROMOTE PRIVATE INVESTMENT OPPORTUNITIES. U.S. TECHNICAL ADVISORS WILL COLLABORATE WITH MINISTER OF TRADE AND INDUSTRY IN ORGANIZATION AND STAFFING OF INVESTMENT PROMOTION CENTER. INVESTMENT PROMOTION OFFICER, ADMINISTRATIVE ASSISTANT AND OTHER APPROPRIATE OFFICERS WITHIN MINISTRY WILL BE TRAINED. CENTER'S WORK WILL CONCERN IDENTIFICATION AND PROMOTION OF SPECIFIC INDUSTRIAL OPPORTUNITIES. CENTER WILL CONDUCT 6-8 WEEK SURVEY TO DETERMINE INVESTMENT PRIORITIES, POTENTIAL AND GENERAL INVESTMENT CLIMATE. PRE-INVESTMENT STUDIES OF OFF-SHORE INDUSTRY, TOURISM, LIVESTOCK PRODUCTION AND MECHANIZED FIELD CROPS WILL ALSO BE MADE. PROMOTIONAL BROCHURES AND INVESTMENT GUIDE WILL BE PREPARED. FOLLOWING PRELIMINARY STUDIES, THERE WILL BE AGREESIVE SEEKING-OUT OF NEW INVESTORS IN WHICH CENTER WILL COOPERATE WITH SUCH GROUPS AS DEVELOPMENT FINANCE CORPORATION, BELIZE AND MICHIGAN PARTNERS OF ALLIANCE, CHAMBERS OF COMMERCE AND LOCAL BANKS. U.S. AND CANADIAN INVESTMENTS WILL BE ENCOURAGED. INVESTMENT PROJECTS WILL BE FULLY DEVELOPED AND PRESENTED IN FORMAT ACCEPTABLE TO POTENTIAL INVESTORS. CENTER WILL PREPARE 3-5 YR RECRUITMENT PLAN. USAID FUNDING WILL BE CHANNELED THROUGH ROCAP. HONDURAS WILL PROVIDSTAFF SERVICES, OFFICE SPACE AND LONG-TERM MAINTENANCE. PRIMARY BENEFICIARIES ARE HONDURAN CIVIL SERVANTS WHO RECEIVE TRAINING. SECONDARY BENEFICIARIES INCLUDE JOB-HOLDERS RESULTING FROM NEW INVESTMENTS. UNDP ALSO PROVIDED TECHNICAL ADVISORS.

Abstract: USAID PUBLIC HEALTH ADVISORS ASSIST ETHOPIAN MIN. OF PUBLIC HEALTH (MPH) TO DEVELOP INFRASTRUCTURE FOR GENERALIZED DECENTRALIZED HEALTH SERVICES. OTHER INTEGRAL DONORS INCLUDE SWEDISH INTNATL DEVEL AGENCY, WHO, & UNICEF.

Abstract: Loan is provided to the Central American Bank for Economic Integration (CABEI to finance the contruction of roads and other infrastructure essential to economic development in the region. This loan will supplement and continue activities begun under a previous project (5960030).  Twelve subprojects, to include the construction of 483 km of highway paving and improvement, the extension of an airport runway, and the construction of a breaker and canal, will be carried out.  Honduras, Central America's least developed country in terms of infrastructure, will be the recipient of the larger share of the subprojects.  The planned road construction will complete the Central American Common Market integration road network, opening up the northern frontier of Guatemala and the Atlantic Caribbean coastal region from Puerto Barrios in Guatemala to Puerto Castilla in Honduras.  In addition, construction of the network will provide improved road communication to Nicaragua's Atlantic Rama riverport; will open the first road to Costa's Rica's Atlantic port of Limon; will include the reconstruction of sections of the Inter-American Highway; will complete the alternate Pacific coastal highway to Managua; will permit major electrical interconnections; and will initiate the Costa Rican Atlantic coast canal. The participating countries will be responsible for the negotiation of contracts and project supervision (with the assistance of consulting engineers).  In addition, each country will be required to present a maintenance program and agree to allocate funds necessary for the program.

Document Title: What can developing countries learn from Soviet transport?
Category: Document Type~Document Type Collection~Technical Reports (all)~Other USAID Supported Study/Document|Thesaurus~Thesaurus Collection~Economics~Economic administration~Economic development|Notation~Notation Collection~D~D25~D25.J|Notation~Notation Collection~G~G19~G19.3~G19.3H|Thesaurus~Thesaurus Collection~Geographical areas and countries~Europe~Central and Eastern Europe~New Independent States|Notation~Notation Collection~M~M06~M06.S~M06.S4|Thesaurus~Thesaurus Collection~Industry and technology~Technology~Technological change~Technology transfer

Abstract: DISCUSSES SOVIET RAILROAD TRANSPORT ACCOMPLISHMENTS. THE GOVERNMENT-OPERATED RAILROADS OF THE U.S.S.R. HAVE SHOWN WHAT MODERN RAILROADS CAN DO UNDER FAVORABLE CONDITIONS. THEY ARE TECHNOLOGICALLY ALERT, HAVE MAINTAINED HIGH MORALE AMONG THEIR PERSONNEL, AND HAVE A REMARKABLE RECORD OF COST REDUCTION SINCE 1950. SOVIET RAIL PASSENGER SERVICE, WHILE NOT AS IMPRESSIVE AS THE FREIGHT SERVICE, HAS HANDLED MOST OF THE INTERCITY PASSENGER TRAVEL ADEQUATELY FOR MANY YEARS. THIS BOOK, THE SIXTH IN THE BROOKINGS TRANSPORT RESEARCH PROGRAM SERIES, ANALYZES THE SOVIET RECORD AND ITS IMPLICATIONS FOR DEVELOPING AND DEVELOPED COUNTRIES. IN DESCRIBING SOVIET RAILROADING ACCOMPLISHMENTS, THE AUTHOR ACKNOWLEDGES THE MANY DIFFERENCES BETWEEN SOVIET OBJECTIVES AND THOSE OF OTHER NATIONS, BUT HE COMMENDS TO DEVELOPING COUNTRIES THE ENERGETIC OPERATING PROCEDURES AND MODERN RAILROAD EQUIPMENT THAT HAVE CONTRIBUTED TO THE SOVIET ACHIEVEMENT. HE BELIEVES THAT INDUSTRIALLY ADVANCED COUNTRIES CAN GAIN USEFUL PERSPECTIVE ON THEIR OWN TRANSPORT POLICY PROBLEMS BY REVIEWING SOVIET EXPERIENCE. HE CHALLENGES THE CONVENTIONAL VIEW OF THE RELATION BETWEEN TRANSPORT INVESTMENT AND GENERAL ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT BY SHOWING THAT HEAVY CAPITAL OUTLAYS FOR TRANSPORT FACILITIES NEED NOT PRECEDE THE GROWTH OF AGRICULTURE AND INDUSTRY. TRANSPORT CAPACITY CAN BE EXPANDED AS THE DEMAND FOR IT GROWS. THE BOOK ALSO DEALS WITH THE ROLE OF TRUCKS, THE PROBLEM OF LACK OF ROADS, AND THE FUTURE OF THE PASSENGER CAR IN THE SOVIET UNION.

Abstract: PRESENTS AN OVERALL PHILOSOPHY AND DESIGN FOR THE EVALUATION COMPONENT OF THE AFRICAN PRIMARY SCIENCE PROGRAM (APSP). PROPOSED INSTRUMENTS AND STRATEGIES OF EVALUATION ARE DIVIDED INTO THREE CATEGORIES: THOSE FOR EVALUATING CONDITIONS EXISTING PRIOR TO INTRODUCTION OF APSP, THOSE WHICH EVALUATE THE VARIOUS STRATEGIES BY WHICH APSP IS IMPLEMENTED, AND THOSE WHICH EVALUATE THE CONSEQUENCES OF THE PROGRAM. THESE CATEGORIES ARE REFERRED TO AS ANTECEDENTS, TRANSACTIONS, AND OUTCOMES. ADMINISTRATIVE ARRANGEMENTS FOR EVALUATION ACTIVITIES ARE PROPOSED.

Abstract: 1968 PROGRESS REPORT BY FEDERAL UNIV OF CEARA (UFC) AGRIC SCHOOL OFFICIALS OF ONGOING AGRIC EDUC PROJ WITH UNIV OF ARIZONA (UA) TECH ASSISTANCE/PARTIC TRNG FUNDED BY AID AND ALLIANCE FOR PROGRESS TECH COOP COUNCIL. INITIATED IN APRIL 1963, PROJ AIMS AT UPGRADING MANPOWER SKILLS & TECH FACILITIES TO ENABLE UFC TO PROVIDE TECH ASSISTANCE TO AGRICULTURALISTS IN THE NORTHEASTERN REGION,THEREBY PROMOTING INCREASED PRODUCTION AND GREATER DIVERSIFICATION & CONTRIBUTING TO SOCIOECONOMIC DVLP OF BRAZIL. 34 FACULTY MEMBERS IN THE AGRIC SCHOOL & 18 TECHNICIANS IN UFC'S ZOOTECHNIC & RURAL TECH INSTITUTES HAVE PROFITED GREATLY FROM BS & GRAD LEVEL COURSEWORK IN BRAZILIAN & AMERICAN UNIVERSITIES UNDER PROJ. UNDER TERMS OF UA CONTRACT,5 UFC FACULTY HAVE RECIEVED MS DEGREES FROM UA; 2 BS DEGRESS;7 ARE CURRENTLY IN ARIZONA;& 6 ARE SLETED TO GO WITHIN THE COMING YEAR. THE AMERICAN TEAM RENDERING TECH ASSISTANCE IS CURRENTLY COMPOSED OF 13 MEMBERS WITH SCHEDULED REDUCTION TO 9 BY JULY 1969 & EVENTUAL PHASING DOWN TO SHORT-TERM ASSISTANCE. US TECHNICIANS HAVE,IN EACH CASE,SERVED IN ADV/COUNSELING ROLE UNDER DIRECTION OF BRAZILIAN COUNTERPARTS. ACTIVITIES UNDERTAKEN UTILIZING ADV ASSISTANCE INCLUDE SURVEYS OF MILK PRODUCTION & MARKETING OF BROILERS & BEEF CATTLE;STUDIES ON SWEET POTATOES,PUMPKIN,PEANUTS,& PAPAYA TREES;LINING OF IRRIGATION CANALS;ORGANIZATION OF A DOMESTIC SCIENCES DEPT;CONSTRUCTION OF SEED PROCESSING/STORAGE FACILITIES;FERTILIZER EXPERIMENTS;& SOIL MAPPING. NEW LABS HAVE BEEN INSTALLED FOR ELECTRICITY & BASIC ELECTRONICS,AGRIC ENTOMOLOGY,& FOR SEED ANALYSIS. EXISTING LABS FOR ANIMAL NUTR,BOTANY,& SOILS & FERTILIZER HAVE BEEN UPGRADED. MECHANICS/AGR MACHINERY SHOP,AND GREENHOUSE FOR FRUIT TREE PROPAGATION CONSTRUCTED. 2 TRACTORS PURCHASED;BOOKS AND JOURNAL SUBSCRIPTIONS PURCHASED FOR LIBRARY;LAB EQUIPMENT DONATED. AGRIC SCHOOL ENROLLMENT INCREASED FROM 270 IN 1963 TO 546 IN 1967. SCHOOL NOW GRADUATES 140 AGRONOMISTS/YEAR. WITH IMPROVED CURRIC ADMIN AND UPGRADED FACULTY & FACILITIES,UFC'S AGRIC SCHOOL HOPES BY 1970 TO INITIATE POST-GRAD MASTER'S DEGREEE LEVEL PRGM.ADDITIONAL AID FUNDING HAS EXTENDED UA CONTRACT THROUGH END OF 68.
